1
00:00:07,080 --> 00:00:09,840
[dramatic music]

2
00:00:16,040 --> 00:00:19,720
[gentle instrumental music]

3
00:02:09,520 --> 00:02:12,040
[jazzy music]

4
00:03:00,440 --> 00:03:01,880
- What do you want?

5
00:03:01,920 --> 00:03:04,560
- [Lefty] I just, I
wanna talk to you, Becky.

6
00:03:06,480 --> 00:03:09,600
- I told you I didn't
wanna see you anymore.

7
00:03:09,640 --> 00:03:12,160
- Come on, babe, you
didn't mean that.

8
00:03:12,200 --> 00:03:13,120
We're in love.

9
00:03:15,240 --> 00:03:17,880
- I gotta go, my parents
are expecting me for dinner.

10
00:03:19,440 --> 00:03:22,440
[door slams shut]

11
00:03:22,480 --> 00:03:24,520
- I'll come with you.
- No.

12
00:03:24,560 --> 00:03:27,400
How many times do we have
to go through this, Lefty?

13
00:03:27,440 --> 00:03:30,000
And things just didn't
work out between us,

14
00:03:30,040 --> 00:03:31,720
and now it's over.

15
00:03:31,760 --> 00:03:33,240
I thought you understood.

16
00:03:33,280 --> 00:03:35,560
- Yes, I understand, you
think you're better than me.

17
00:03:35,600 --> 00:03:36,520
You always did.

18
00:03:37,480 --> 00:03:38,480
- That's not true.

19
00:03:40,320 --> 00:03:42,160
I just don't love you.

20
00:03:42,200 --> 00:03:44,440
Why can't you accept
that and leave me alone?

21
00:03:45,880 --> 00:03:47,280
- Not till I'm ready.

22
00:03:47,320 --> 00:03:49,120
[Becky gasps]
[dramatic music]

23
00:03:49,160 --> 00:03:51,280
- Don't you ever
come here again!

24
00:03:51,320 --> 00:03:54,400
If you do, I'm gonna
call the police!

25
00:03:56,240 --> 00:03:58,120
- Becky, come back.

26
00:03:58,160 --> 00:03:59,080
I'm sorry.

27
00:04:14,880 --> 00:04:17,880
[crickets chirping]

28
00:04:20,200 --> 00:04:22,760
[laughing]
- Oh, Becky.

29
00:04:22,800 --> 00:04:25,200
- A toast to our
wonderful daughter

30
00:04:25,240 --> 00:04:28,000
who's not only had her first
novel fast-track published

31
00:04:28,040 --> 00:04:29,600
to great critical acclaim.

32
00:04:29,640 --> 00:04:32,240
- Thank you, thank you.
- But has sold said novel

33
00:04:32,280 --> 00:04:34,120
as a five-hour miniseries, hear,
hear.

34
00:04:34,160 --> 00:04:35,720
- Television, oh, well.

35
00:04:35,760 --> 00:04:37,480
- Whoever said there's no
business like show business

36
00:04:37,520 --> 00:04:39,360
wasn't kidding, you're gonna
learn that, sweetheart.

37
00:04:39,400 --> 00:04:40,320
- I already know, Dad.

38
00:04:40,360 --> 00:04:42,760
I had to listen to
your war stories

39
00:04:42,800 --> 00:04:45,920
about how the studios abuse
us writers all my life.

40
00:04:45,960 --> 00:04:48,120
- Most of which he made up,
Becky.

41
00:04:48,160 --> 00:04:50,080
- I know that too, Mom.
- All right, all right.

42
00:04:50,120 --> 00:04:51,960
Enough about my trials
and tribulations.

43
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:53,520
- I'd like to make a toast.

44
00:04:54,440 --> 00:04:58,840
To my mom for giving me life,

45
00:04:58,880 --> 00:05:03,280
courage, and the strength
to survive any situation.

46
00:05:03,320 --> 00:05:08,320
And to my dad for his support,
belief, and inspiration.

47
00:05:09,400 --> 00:05:11,280
I love you both very much.

48
00:05:14,400 --> 00:05:17,320
[glasses clinking]

49
00:05:18,880 --> 00:05:22,280
- Well, I always seem to be
the one to call it an evening,

50
00:05:22,320 --> 00:05:24,160
but I really am rather tired.

51
00:05:24,200 --> 00:05:25,600
- [Dad] I'll get your chair.

52
00:05:31,320 --> 00:05:33,160
- You're gonna ask Dad
to tuck you in tonight?

53
00:05:33,200 --> 00:05:35,000
- Oh, those days are over,
my sweet.

54
00:05:35,040 --> 00:05:36,200
And even when we were married,

55
00:05:36,240 --> 00:05:38,240
I always preferred
sleeping alone.

56
00:05:38,280 --> 00:05:39,960
- Liar.
[Mom chuckles]

57
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:41,200
- What about you, honey?

58
00:05:41,240 --> 00:05:43,480
You're not still seeing
that guitarist, are you?

59
00:05:43,520 --> 00:05:44,720
- No, Mom, I told you.

60
00:05:44,760 --> 00:05:45,960
I broke up with him.
- Oh.

61
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:48,520
- Well, I'm glad to hear
it, you deserve better.

62
00:05:48,560 --> 00:05:50,960
- You've said that about
every guy I've ever dated.

63
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:52,600
- And all of us know
I'm never wrong.

64
00:05:52,640 --> 00:05:54,880
- Oh, yes, Gus, and that's
certainly true.

65
00:05:54,920 --> 00:05:56,040
- Need some help?
[Becky chuckling]

66
00:05:56,080 --> 00:05:57,760
- Immaculata will
take care of me.

67
00:05:57,800 --> 00:06:00,960
Now call me soon, both of you.

68
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:02,040
Goodnight.

69
00:06:02,080 --> 00:06:03,560
- Goodnight, Peach.
- Goodnight, Mom.

70
00:06:03,600 --> 00:06:05,240
- Wanna walk your old
man to his car?

71
00:06:05,280 --> 00:06:07,080
- Only if you'll do
the same for me.

72
00:06:08,960 --> 00:06:12,600
[gentle instrumental music]

73
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:23,880
- [Gus] You all right
about this breakup?

74
00:06:23,920 --> 00:06:25,720
- [Becky] I'm fine, Dad.

75
00:06:25,760 --> 00:06:27,080
It took me a while
but I found out

76
00:06:27,120 --> 00:06:28,800
I really didn't love
him after all.

77
00:06:30,920 --> 00:06:32,120
- Well, I'm proud of you, Becky.

78
00:06:35,360 --> 00:06:38,120
You've turned into a wonderful
woman and a terrific writer.

79
00:06:38,160 --> 00:06:39,360
- [Becky] It was easy.

80
00:06:39,400 --> 00:06:41,080
I'm my father's
daughter after all.

81
00:06:41,120 --> 00:06:42,560
- Ah, thank you.

82
00:06:42,600 --> 00:06:45,000
Drive carefully, huh?
- I will.

83
00:06:49,520 --> 00:06:50,360
- Goodnight, darling.

84
00:06:50,400 --> 00:06:51,800
- Goodnight, Dad.

85
00:06:58,520 --> 00:07:01,520
[suspenseful music]

86
00:07:38,400 --> 00:07:41,320
[doorbell ringing]

87
00:07:42,480 --> 00:07:44,560
- [Gus] Who is it?

88
00:07:44,600 --> 00:07:46,160
- [Detective Jackson] Mr.
Augustus Bailey?

89
00:07:46,200 --> 00:07:47,360
- [Gus] Yes.

90
00:07:47,400 --> 00:07:48,840
- [Detective Jackson]
Detective Jackson, LAPD.

91
00:07:48,880 --> 00:07:50,360
I'd like to talk to you, sir.

92
00:08:06,920 --> 00:08:07,840
- What's the problem?

93
00:08:09,400 --> 00:08:10,880
- [Detective Jackson] I'm sorry
to have disturbed you, sir,

94
00:08:10,920 --> 00:08:12,680
but I'm afraid I have
some bad news.

95
00:08:13,880 --> 00:08:16,400
You have a daughter,
Rebecca Lee Bailey,

96
00:08:16,440 --> 00:08:21,440
living at 235 West Hayden
Avenue in West Los Angeles?

97
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:22,600
- Yes.

98
00:08:23,880 --> 00:08:26,920
Dear God, she hasn't been
in a car crash, has she?

99
00:08:26,960 --> 00:08:27,800
- No, sir.

100
00:08:29,360 --> 00:08:31,480
I'm sorry to have to
tell you this,

101
00:08:31,520 --> 00:08:33,560
but your daughter is dead.

102
00:08:33,600 --> 00:08:35,000
It appears she was murdered.

103
00:08:37,200 --> 00:08:38,040
- That can't be.

104
00:08:39,360 --> 00:08:40,840
I was with her two hours ago.

105
00:08:42,680 --> 00:08:43,720
Has to be a mistake.

106
00:08:45,440 --> 00:08:47,280
- A neighbor reported
hearing screams

107
00:08:47,320 --> 00:08:50,320
coming from inside your
daughter's apartment.

108
00:08:50,360 --> 00:08:52,720
Our officers investigated
and found the body.

109
00:08:55,320 --> 00:08:56,320
- No.

110
00:08:56,360 --> 00:08:59,720
[dramatic music]

111
00:08:59,760 --> 00:09:04,680
No.

112
00:09:04,720 --> 00:09:05,560
Not Becky.

113
00:09:07,760 --> 00:09:08,600
No, please.

114
00:09:09,560 --> 00:09:10,400
Not Becky.

115
00:09:15,520 --> 00:09:18,400
- I'll need you to make an
identification, Mr. Bailey.

116
00:09:24,080 --> 00:09:24,920
- Yes.

117
00:09:26,960 --> 00:09:28,480
But I hope to God you're wrong.

118
00:09:30,080 --> 00:09:31,320
You have to be wrong.

119
00:09:34,240 --> 00:09:36,280
- We have a suspect in custody,
sir.

120
00:09:37,600 --> 00:09:38,440
- Who?

121
00:09:40,320 --> 00:09:43,160
- [Detective Jackson] Francis
Flint, also known as Lefty.

122
00:09:55,280 --> 00:09:57,720
- I don't believe you.

123
00:09:57,760 --> 00:10:00,440
- The police took me to see her.

124
00:10:01,480 --> 00:10:03,120
- How did it happen?

125
00:10:04,680 --> 00:10:05,680
- They are not sure.

126
00:10:12,880 --> 00:10:14,680
- How did she die, Gus?

127
00:10:18,920 --> 00:10:19,880
- She was murdered.

128
00:10:22,280 --> 00:10:23,120
Strangled

129
00:10:25,760 --> 00:10:26,600
by Lefty Flint.

130
00:10:30,120 --> 00:10:30,960
- Oh, God.

131
00:10:33,400 --> 00:10:34,240
Dear God.

132
00:10:37,920 --> 00:10:41,720
Not my child.

133
00:10:41,760 --> 00:10:42,760
Not my baby.

134
00:10:48,880 --> 00:10:50,440
What do we do, Gus?

135
00:10:53,720 --> 00:10:55,200
What do we do now?

136
00:10:56,520 --> 00:10:58,480
- We make sure Flint goes away

137
00:11:01,600 --> 00:11:03,200
for the rest of his damned life.

138
00:11:04,760 --> 00:11:06,160
- A formal arrest has been made

139
00:11:06,200 --> 00:11:08,560
in connection with last
night's brutal slaying

140
00:11:08,600 --> 00:11:11,120
of Becky Bailey,
successful novelist

141
00:11:11,160 --> 00:11:14,120
and daughter of writer Augustus
Bailey and his ex-wife,

142
00:11:14,160 --> 00:11:16,840
socialite Peach
Prindible Bailey.

143
00:11:16,880 --> 00:11:18,520
Francis Lefty Flint

144
00:11:18,560 --> 00:11:21,080
has been charged with
murder in the first degree.

145
00:11:21,120 --> 00:11:23,160
Flint, entertainer at a
Malibu restaurant

146
00:11:23,200 --> 00:11:25,080
and estranged boyfriend
of the victim,

147
00:11:25,120 --> 00:11:27,400
has admitted to committing
the violent crime,

148
00:11:27,440 --> 00:11:29,760
and his trial is expected
to begin shortly.

149
00:11:29,800 --> 00:11:31,400
[dramatic news music]

150
00:11:31,440 --> 00:11:34,680
Until tomorrow, this is
Bernard Slatkin for Focus

151
00:11:34,720 --> 00:11:35,840
on special assignment.

152
00:11:36,800 --> 00:11:38,440
- Honey, we gotta go.

153
00:11:38,480 --> 00:11:40,440
The van to the
airport's waiting.

154
00:11:40,480 --> 00:11:43,000
- [Anchorman] Thank you,
Bernard.

155
00:11:43,040 --> 00:11:45,240
- I'm sorry, I was
watching something on TV.

156
00:11:47,040 --> 00:11:49,200
- [Friend] Ruby, are
you all right?

157
00:11:49,240 --> 00:11:51,200
You look like you've
just seen a ghost.

158
00:11:53,280 --> 00:11:54,080
- I have.

159
00:11:58,080 --> 00:11:59,120
[solemn music]

160
00:11:59,160 --> 00:12:02,320
- The night Peach gave
birth to Becky,

161
00:12:03,640 --> 00:12:05,760
I remember thinking for
the first time

162
00:12:07,200 --> 00:12:08,480
about my own mortality.

163
00:12:10,880 --> 00:12:12,960
Suddenly my life became
more precious

164
00:12:14,640 --> 00:12:16,240
because of that beautiful child.

165
00:12:18,880 --> 00:12:23,080
I had to live long enough
to ensure her happiness.

166
00:12:25,320 --> 00:12:26,360
I wanted to catch her

167
00:12:27,760 --> 00:12:29,680
when she tried to take
her first steps.

168
00:12:31,520 --> 00:12:34,040
I wanted to teach her how
to ride a bike,

169
00:12:35,480 --> 00:12:36,760
dribble a basketball.

170
00:12:38,880 --> 00:12:43,120
I wanted to introduce
her to the power of words

171
00:12:44,720 --> 00:12:47,960
and watch her discover
the magic of love.

172
00:12:50,920 --> 00:12:54,720
I wanted to walk her down the
aisle into a loving marriage.

173
00:12:56,720 --> 00:12:59,640
And I wanted to hold her
first child and feel renewed.

174
00:13:03,760 --> 00:13:04,680
Most of all,

175
00:13:07,360 --> 00:13:08,640
I wanted to protect Becky

176
00:13:11,600 --> 00:13:15,640
from any kind of harm.

177
00:13:17,800 --> 00:13:19,240
Goodbye, my darling daughter.

178
00:13:52,160 --> 00:13:53,000
- Peach.

179
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:55,280
I'm so sorry.

180
00:13:58,000 --> 00:13:58,840
Gus.

181
00:14:00,240 --> 00:14:01,520
- Thanks for coming, Faye.

182
00:14:02,800 --> 00:14:04,480
- She's the daughter
I never had.

183
00:14:06,880 --> 00:14:09,800
When Becky was seven,
eight years old,

184
00:14:09,840 --> 00:14:11,640
you brought her to the
set of Memphis Belle,

185
00:14:11,680 --> 00:14:12,840
do you remember that?

186
00:14:12,880 --> 00:14:14,200
- Hmm.

187
00:14:14,240 --> 00:14:17,080
- She told me that I should
read her father's lines

188
00:14:17,120 --> 00:14:19,200
exactly as they were written.

189
00:14:19,240 --> 00:14:23,240
And if I did, she promised me

190
00:14:23,280 --> 00:14:25,640
that she would someday
write a movie for me.

191
00:14:27,760 --> 00:14:30,120
You know, because of
that promise,

192
00:14:30,160 --> 00:14:32,680
I never changed a
word you wrote.

193
00:14:35,880 --> 00:14:38,880
[suspenseful music]

194
00:14:53,680 --> 00:14:56,840
[reporters clamoring]

195
00:15:20,680 --> 00:15:23,880
- Winding up what has been
a lengthy and heated trial,

196
00:15:23,920 --> 00:15:26,640
Francis Lefty Flint, admitted
killer of Becky Bailey,

197
00:15:26,680 --> 00:15:29,640
has just arrived at the
Santa Monica courthouse.

198
00:15:29,680 --> 00:15:30,920
Flint's attorney has announced

199
00:15:30,960 --> 00:15:33,280
that his client will take
the stand today

200
00:15:33,320 --> 00:15:36,160
and testify on his own behalf.

201
00:15:36,200 --> 00:15:38,520
And now I see Becky's
parents have arrived.

202
00:15:38,560 --> 00:15:41,640
Peach Prindible Bailey herself
the victim of our cruel fate,

203
00:15:41,680 --> 00:15:45,000
paralyzed after being thrown
from a horse five years ago.

204
00:15:45,040 --> 00:15:46,280
And Augustus Bailey,

205
00:15:46,320 --> 00:15:48,920
the noted Hollywood
screenwriter and journalist.

206
00:15:51,040 --> 00:15:54,120
- Becky told me that her
parents didn't approve of me,

207
00:15:54,160 --> 00:15:55,800
so I thought I'd make
it easy on her

208
00:15:55,840 --> 00:15:57,400
and I told her that
maybe it would be better

209
00:15:57,440 --> 00:16:00,040
if we didn't see one
another for a while.

210
00:16:00,080 --> 00:16:01,320
- Are you saying that
you're the one

211
00:16:01,360 --> 00:16:03,480
who ended this relationship?

212
00:16:03,520 --> 00:16:05,000
- Yes, sir.

213
00:16:05,040 --> 00:16:07,680
Not because I didn't love Becky,
I did.

214
00:16:08,840 --> 00:16:10,400
Because I knew it would
be better for her

215
00:16:10,440 --> 00:16:11,880
with me out of her life.

216
00:16:11,920 --> 00:16:15,040
- And why were you at Becky
Bailey's apartment that night?

217
00:16:15,080 --> 00:16:16,680
- Becky called me.

218
00:16:16,720 --> 00:16:18,560
She said she missed me,
that she wanted to see me,

219
00:16:18,600 --> 00:16:21,840
and that she didn't care what
her parents thought anymore.

220
00:16:21,880 --> 00:16:23,160
- [Prosecutor] So you
went to Becky's apartment

221
00:16:23,200 --> 00:16:25,120
at her request?
- Yes.

222
00:16:25,160 --> 00:16:29,000
When I arrived, she asked
me to spend the night,

223
00:16:29,040 --> 00:16:31,640
but I told her I didn't
think it would be right.

224
00:16:32,480 --> 00:16:33,960
Without her parents blessing,

225
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:38,440
it would make the love we felt
for each other dirty, unholy.

226
00:16:41,520 --> 00:16:43,080
So I started to leave,

227
00:16:44,400 --> 00:16:46,680
and Becky got hysterical.

228
00:16:46,720 --> 00:16:49,200
She started screaming
saying that if I left,

229
00:16:49,240 --> 00:16:51,760
she'd do something crazy,
maybe even kill herself.

230
00:16:53,400 --> 00:16:56,280
I tried to calm her down,

231
00:16:56,320 --> 00:16:57,880
but she just kept hitting me,
you know,

232
00:16:57,920 --> 00:17:00,400
just over and over again.

233
00:17:00,440 --> 00:17:02,960
I just wanted her to stop.

234
00:17:04,640 --> 00:17:05,720
I loved Becky.

235
00:17:07,320 --> 00:17:08,800
I never meant to hurt her.

236
00:17:08,840 --> 00:17:11,160
- But you did hurt
Becky Bailey, Mr. Flint.

237
00:17:11,200 --> 00:17:13,040
You silenced her screams forever

238
00:17:13,080 --> 00:17:17,040
and you used your hands
as your weapon.

239
00:17:17,080 --> 00:17:22,080
[spectators murmuring]
[dramatic music]

240
00:17:35,240 --> 00:17:36,920
- It is the judgment
of this court

241
00:17:36,960 --> 00:17:39,080
that the defendant
Francis Flint,

242
00:17:40,480 --> 00:17:43,240
having been found guilty of
the crime of manslaughter

243
00:17:43,280 --> 00:17:44,480
by the jury of this court

244
00:17:44,520 --> 00:17:47,360
for the City of Santa Monica,
California,

245
00:17:47,400 --> 00:17:50,160
be imprisoned for a period
of three years.

246
00:17:50,200 --> 00:17:51,560
[spectators gasping]

247
00:17:51,600 --> 00:17:55,240
However, it is also the
court's judgment

248
00:17:55,280 --> 00:17:59,080
that since the defendant
has no previous convictions,

249
00:17:59,120 --> 00:18:00,600
he be allowed a parole hearing

250
00:18:00,640 --> 00:18:03,120
after serving 1 1/2 years
of his sentence.

251
00:18:03,160 --> 00:18:05,000
[spectators protesting]

252
00:18:05,040 --> 00:18:08,440
The defendant will herewith
be remanded to the custody.

253
00:18:08,480 --> 00:18:11,240
[hammer banging]

254
00:18:18,320 --> 00:18:22,080
[reporters clamoring]

255
00:18:22,120 --> 00:18:24,000
- You think you got a
fair sentence?

256
00:18:24,040 --> 00:18:25,800
- God's on your side.

257
00:18:30,640 --> 00:18:33,120
- [Woman] God will punish you!

258
00:18:34,440 --> 00:18:35,920
- Mr. Flint, Mr. Flint.

259
00:18:35,960 --> 00:18:37,120
Is there anything
you'd like to say

260
00:18:37,160 --> 00:18:38,560
to Becky's parents, Mr. Flint?

261
00:18:40,960 --> 00:18:43,440
- I just hope they
can forgive me.

262
00:18:43,480 --> 00:18:44,320
God has.

263
00:18:47,360 --> 00:18:49,600
- [Woman] God will
never forgive you!

264
00:18:49,640 --> 00:18:51,480
- [Man] God loves you!

265
00:18:56,360 --> 00:18:59,200
- [Man] You'll burn in hell!

266
00:18:59,240 --> 00:19:01,800
[solemn music]

267
00:19:27,600 --> 00:19:29,200
- Something else I can
do for you Mr. Renthal?

268
00:19:29,240 --> 00:19:31,600
- Yes, you could sit down
and talk to me.

269
00:19:31,640 --> 00:19:32,960
I can't ever seem to fall asleep

270
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:34,680
on these damn red-eye flights.

271
00:19:36,520 --> 00:19:38,120
- Well, maybe for just a minute.

272
00:19:40,440 --> 00:19:42,280
I thought people like you
never flew commercial,

273
00:19:42,320 --> 00:19:44,200
Mr. Renthal, private
jets and all.

274
00:19:44,240 --> 00:19:45,840
- It's Elias, and you
shouldn't believe

275
00:19:45,880 --> 00:19:47,840
everything you read
in newspapers.

276
00:19:47,880 --> 00:19:49,600
I'm just an average
guy from Chicago

277
00:19:49,640 --> 00:19:51,120
who's made a little money.

278
00:19:51,160 --> 00:19:52,520
- Oh, I guess that's why

279
00:19:52,560 --> 00:19:55,200
you're on the cover of Wall
Street Magazine this week.

280
00:19:56,480 --> 00:19:57,560
- Where are you from?

281
00:19:59,040 --> 00:20:01,360
- Someplace I just fly over now.

282
00:20:01,400 --> 00:20:02,240
- Married?

283
00:20:03,720 --> 00:20:04,640
- Never.

284
00:20:04,680 --> 00:20:06,160
- I used to be.

285
00:20:06,200 --> 00:20:08,080
My ex-wife said she didn't
want to stay with a guy

286
00:20:08,120 --> 00:20:09,800
who had no class.

287
00:20:09,840 --> 00:20:11,160
But, hell, you could buy that.

288
00:20:11,200 --> 00:20:14,480
You got enough money, you
can buy anything you want.

289
00:20:14,520 --> 00:20:17,160
- Yeah, you can even
erase the past,

290
00:20:17,200 --> 00:20:21,600
become somebody important,
you know, admired.

291
00:20:21,640 --> 00:20:24,320
Forget all the bad things
that ever happened to you.

292
00:20:24,360 --> 00:20:25,720
- [Elias] Did those happen?

293
00:20:27,720 --> 00:20:28,920
- Not to people like me.

294
00:20:30,840 --> 00:20:33,440
- I can make it happen for you.

295
00:20:35,840 --> 00:20:39,680
- Oh, I'm sorry, Elias, Mr.
Renthal,

296
00:20:39,720 --> 00:20:41,160
but I gotta get back to work.

297
00:20:45,160 --> 00:20:46,120
I'll see you later.

298
00:20:55,320 --> 00:20:56,440
- [Woman] There you go.

299
00:21:24,480 --> 00:21:25,400
- [Gus] Hi.

300
00:21:26,640 --> 00:21:27,440
- [Peach] Hi.

301
00:21:28,520 --> 00:21:30,320
- My plane leaves in a
couple of hours.

302
00:21:30,360 --> 00:21:31,880
Just came over to say goodbye.

303
00:21:33,160 --> 00:21:35,160
- You sure you want to
move to New York?

304
00:21:35,880 --> 00:21:37,000
I remember a time

305
00:21:37,040 --> 00:21:39,640
when you couldn't wait
to get to Hollywood.

306
00:21:39,680 --> 00:21:40,720
- Well, it's not popular

307
00:21:40,760 --> 00:21:42,240
to write movies about
people anymore.

308
00:21:42,280 --> 00:21:45,280
Only a lot of chases,
special effects,

309
00:21:45,320 --> 00:21:47,720
and I have to make a living.

310
00:21:50,240 --> 00:21:51,640
- What are you gonna
do in New York?

311
00:21:51,680 --> 00:21:53,880
- I have a few appointments
with a couple of magazines.

312
00:21:55,400 --> 00:21:58,280
Besides, there's no reason to
hang around here any longer.

313
00:21:59,720 --> 00:22:00,560
- Oh.

314
00:22:02,400 --> 00:22:06,040
[gentle instrumental music]

315
00:22:12,840 --> 00:22:13,880
- I'm proud of you,

316
00:22:15,280 --> 00:22:17,040
the way you've gotten
through all this.

317
00:22:18,600 --> 00:22:20,480
- I'm proud of you too.

318
00:22:23,280 --> 00:22:25,200
You'll miss your plane.

319
00:22:26,440 --> 00:22:27,280
- Yeah.

320
00:23:32,200 --> 00:23:34,160
It's not over yet, Becky.

321
00:23:36,560 --> 00:23:37,400
I promise you.

322
00:23:38,720 --> 00:23:39,560
It's not over.

323
00:23:58,080 --> 00:24:01,760
[gentle instrumental music]

324
00:24:11,120 --> 00:24:12,760
Good evening, Charlie.

325
00:24:12,800 --> 00:24:14,160
- Good evening, Mr. Bailey.

326
00:24:20,120 --> 00:24:22,800
[guests chattering]
[laughing]

327
00:24:22,840 --> 00:24:25,400
- What I simply cannot
stand is to be bored.

328
00:24:25,440 --> 00:24:27,720
And there's never
anything boring

329
00:24:27,760 --> 00:24:29,160
with the doers of the world.

330
00:24:29,200 --> 00:24:32,880
- [Man] That's just
what I was going to say.

331
00:24:35,640 --> 00:24:36,640
- Thank you.

332
00:24:47,000 --> 00:24:49,120
- Hello, Gus.
[laughing]

333
00:24:49,160 --> 00:24:51,720
Aren't you glad you're
away from California?

334
00:24:51,760 --> 00:24:54,480
Such a synchronicity of
theme at dinner, the movies.

335
00:24:54,520 --> 00:24:57,880
The people are so superficial
and such frauds. [chuckling]

336
00:24:57,920 --> 00:24:59,840
- Well, we couldn't accuse
anyone who comes to your parties

337
00:24:59,880 --> 00:25:01,360
of being like that, could we,
Maisie?

338
00:25:01,400 --> 00:25:03,680
- Well, my parties
aren't about people, Gus.

339
00:25:03,720 --> 00:25:05,800
My parties are about
conversation.

340
00:25:05,840 --> 00:25:08,520
After coming here for a year,
you should understand that.

341
00:25:09,600 --> 00:25:13,840
Oh, excuse me, I see,
Senator Marx.

342
00:25:13,880 --> 00:25:15,600
- Hello, Gus.

343
00:25:15,640 --> 00:25:16,960
- Hello, Justine.

344
00:25:17,000 --> 00:25:18,880
You look beautiful.

345
00:25:18,920 --> 00:25:20,360
How's Lil?

346
00:25:20,400 --> 00:25:23,040
- Oh, well, Mother is
Mother, always the same.

347
00:25:23,080 --> 00:25:25,560
Tell me, Gus, do you
know that man over there?

348
00:25:25,600 --> 00:25:27,280
Talking to Violet Bastito?

349
00:25:28,880 --> 00:25:31,120
- That's Bernie Slatkin,
anchorman for Focus.

350
00:25:32,360 --> 00:25:34,080
- That's where I've seen him.

351
00:25:34,120 --> 00:25:35,480
Do you know him?

352
00:25:35,520 --> 00:25:36,320
- We've met.

353
00:25:38,600 --> 00:25:41,400
- You're sitting under the
Renoir next to Senator Marx.

354
00:25:47,320 --> 00:25:50,120
Ezzie, I'm sitting you
next to Mrs. Renthal.

355
00:25:50,160 --> 00:25:52,600
- Mrs. Renthal, the wife
of the hamburger king

356
00:25:52,640 --> 00:25:54,440
who's in all the newspapers?

357
00:25:54,480 --> 00:25:56,400
How dare you waste me
next to her.

358
00:25:56,440 --> 00:25:59,440
- Oh, Ezzie, try to be nice.

359
00:25:59,480 --> 00:26:01,480
This is the Renthals first
New York party,

360
00:26:01,520 --> 00:26:02,880
and I want them to feel at home.

361
00:26:02,920 --> 00:26:04,040
- Well, I'm sure they will,

362
00:26:04,080 --> 00:26:06,040
as long as they keep
buying your paintings.

363
00:26:06,080 --> 00:26:08,120
[Maisie scoffs]

364
00:26:08,160 --> 00:26:10,520
- Now, Ezzie, you know
perfectly well

365
00:26:10,560 --> 00:26:12,840
that Maisie Verdurin has
a genius for seating.

366
00:26:12,880 --> 00:26:15,600
She absolutely agonizes
over her placement.

367
00:26:15,640 --> 00:26:18,520
Besides which, had you
bothered to read my column

368
00:26:18,560 --> 00:26:21,520
yesterday morning, you would
know that Elias Renthal

369
00:26:21,560 --> 00:26:22,840
is the man to watch.

370
00:26:22,880 --> 00:26:25,880
He made all those millions
in the past eight years

371
00:26:27,280 --> 00:26:30,400
from hamburger franchises
to company takeovers, dear.

372
00:26:30,440 --> 00:26:32,400
- Still say the only
respectable way to make money

373
00:26:32,440 --> 00:26:33,240
is to inherit it.

374
00:26:34,520 --> 00:26:36,800
And you can put that in
your column, sweetie.

375
00:26:48,840 --> 00:26:50,600
- We're all wrong for
this crowd, Elias.

376
00:26:50,640 --> 00:26:51,720
- Don't kid yourself, baby.

377
00:26:51,760 --> 00:26:52,960
Once these people get
to know us--

378
00:26:53,000 --> 00:26:54,680
- They'll ask us to leave.

379
00:26:54,720 --> 00:26:55,560
- Oh.

380
00:26:56,800 --> 00:27:00,080
I'd just about given you two up.

381
00:27:00,120 --> 00:27:01,160
- I'm sorry we're so late.

382
00:27:01,200 --> 00:27:02,760
I don't think you've
met my wife Ruby.

383
00:27:02,800 --> 00:27:05,040
- Oh, I'm so pleased
to meet you.

384
00:27:05,080 --> 00:27:06,760
- Thank you for inviting us.

385
00:27:07,600 --> 00:27:08,120
- Hey.

386
00:27:09,560 --> 00:27:12,200
- Oh, is that the painting
you wanted me to see, Elias?

387
00:27:12,240 --> 00:27:13,840
- Yes, Monet's Water Lilies.

388
00:27:13,880 --> 00:27:15,920
- Well, that is the
color pink I like.

389
00:27:15,960 --> 00:27:17,600
- Maisie, I think you got
yourself a sale.

390
00:27:17,640 --> 00:27:18,840
Go ahead, baby, take
a closer look.

391
00:27:18,880 --> 00:27:19,680
- Oh, no, uh,

392
00:27:19,720 --> 00:27:20,880
I want you to see the picture,

393
00:27:20,920 --> 00:27:23,480
but the waiters are just
about to serve.

394
00:27:23,520 --> 00:27:24,720
- You got the right idea,
Maisie, honey.

395
00:27:24,760 --> 00:27:26,080
[Maisie giggling]

396
00:27:26,120 --> 00:27:29,400
Never do business on an empty
stomach, huh? [laughing]

397
00:27:29,440 --> 00:27:31,480
- Elias, I have you
sitting next to me,

398
00:27:31,520 --> 00:27:33,800
and you are sitting with
Ezzie Fenwick,

399
00:27:33,840 --> 00:27:37,600
who's the best friend of
all the ladies in New York.

400
00:27:37,640 --> 00:27:38,480
- Great.

401
00:27:50,440 --> 00:27:52,640
- It's been a long time, Mr.
Bailey.

402
00:27:52,680 --> 00:27:54,160
Bernie Slatkin.
- Gus.

403
00:27:54,200 --> 00:27:55,640
I always wanted to thank you,

404
00:27:55,680 --> 00:27:58,520
the way you handled your news
coverage about my daughter.

405
00:27:58,560 --> 00:28:00,840
You're the only reporter
who didn't exploit our loss.

406
00:28:00,880 --> 00:28:03,000
- I just tried to put
myself in your shoes.

407
00:28:03,040 --> 00:28:04,400
That made it hard to
be objective.

408
00:28:04,440 --> 00:28:07,320
- [Gus] Well, we appreciated
your sensitivity.

409
00:28:07,360 --> 00:28:10,440
- Gus, be a dear, give
us some advice.

410
00:28:10,480 --> 00:28:12,920
I've decided to take
up reading as a hobby.

411
00:28:12,960 --> 00:28:14,720
Could you recommend
something with short chapters

412
00:28:14,760 --> 00:28:15,720
about rich people?

413
00:28:15,760 --> 00:28:16,880
- What about Trollope?

414
00:28:17,840 --> 00:28:19,080
- Excuse me?

415
00:28:19,120 --> 00:28:21,640
- I think he means the
author, Anthony Trollope.

416
00:28:24,520 --> 00:28:25,760
- Can I take him home?

417
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:29,360
Or will he keep me up all night?

418
00:28:29,400 --> 00:28:31,320
- I hate to read in bed.

419
00:28:31,360 --> 00:28:32,200
- So do I.

420
00:28:39,160 --> 00:28:40,360
[laughing]

421
00:28:40,400 --> 00:28:42,520
- Just look at that
Renthal woman.

422
00:28:42,560 --> 00:28:44,040
She absolutely won't do.

423
00:28:44,080 --> 00:28:45,160
Dress like she's going

424
00:28:45,200 --> 00:28:47,200
to the opening of the
opera in Istanbul.

425
00:28:48,240 --> 00:28:50,040
As you must be having
a field day.

426
00:29:03,200 --> 00:29:04,880
- Where did you get that dress?

427
00:29:06,160 --> 00:29:07,720
- [Ruby] Chicago.

428
00:29:07,760 --> 00:29:08,920
- [Ezzie] I thought so.

429
00:29:10,320 --> 00:29:12,080
Why on earth did you ever leave?

430
00:29:13,200 --> 00:29:15,000
- Well, Elias's
business is here now.

431
00:29:16,080 --> 00:29:18,760
- Your husband's not
quite as imposing

432
00:29:18,800 --> 00:29:20,840
as I thought he'd be, Mrs.
Renthal.

433
00:29:26,800 --> 00:29:28,480
- Well, my husband can
be very imposing

434
00:29:28,520 --> 00:29:30,400
when he opens his wallet, Mr.
Fenwick.

435
00:29:43,480 --> 00:29:44,360
- Goodnight, Bernie.

436
00:29:44,400 --> 00:29:45,240
- Goodnight, Gus.

437
00:30:16,400 --> 00:30:17,240
- Mr. Bailey?

438
00:30:18,160 --> 00:30:19,400
- My friends call me Gus.

439
00:30:20,280 --> 00:30:21,720
- My name is Ruby Nolte Renthal.

440
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:25,400
I want to talk to you
privately for a moment.

441
00:30:25,440 --> 00:30:26,120
- [Gus] What about?

442
00:30:27,320 --> 00:30:29,000
- I just wanted to tell
you how sorry I am

443
00:30:29,040 --> 00:30:31,280
about what happened to
your daughter.

444
00:30:31,320 --> 00:30:31,840
- Thank you.

445
00:30:33,120 --> 00:30:35,360
- I wish I could have
done something for her.

446
00:30:38,360 --> 00:30:40,080
- You sound like you knew Becky.

447
00:30:40,120 --> 00:30:42,000
- No, no, I didn't.

448
00:30:43,520 --> 00:30:45,560
You don't always have to
know a person to feel sorry.

449
00:30:45,600 --> 00:30:48,440
- [Elias] No, thanks, I'm
sure I'll find her, thanks.

450
00:30:49,840 --> 00:30:52,360
- Maybe you and I could
have lunch together sometime

451
00:30:52,400 --> 00:30:53,400
and just talk.

452
00:30:53,440 --> 00:30:54,760
- [Gus] I'd like that.

453
00:30:54,800 --> 00:30:56,960
- So would I, very much.

454
00:30:57,000 --> 00:30:58,800
- What the hell is
going on in here?

455
00:31:00,160 --> 00:31:01,680
- Just getting my coat, Elias.

456
00:31:03,520 --> 00:31:07,320
- Maisie wants us to look at
that picture again up close.

457
00:31:08,640 --> 00:31:10,840
- Elias, this is
Augustus Bailey.

458
00:31:10,880 --> 00:31:12,720
He wrote that article
you like so much

459
00:31:12,760 --> 00:31:14,920
on Laurance Van Degan
in the Knickerbocker.

460
00:31:16,600 --> 00:31:18,040
- Pleased to meet you.
- Same.

461
00:31:19,040 --> 00:31:20,680
And nice meeting you, Mrs.
Renthal.

462
00:31:20,720 --> 00:31:22,400
- [Ruby] My friends
call me Ruby.

463
00:31:25,960 --> 00:31:27,760
- Guy's old enough to
be your father.

464
00:31:27,800 --> 00:31:29,640
- You're old enough to
be my father.

465
00:31:29,680 --> 00:31:30,600
- What the hell is this?

466
00:31:30,640 --> 00:31:32,120
We go to our first
New York party

467
00:31:32,160 --> 00:31:33,360
and I find you in the
bedroom with--

468
00:31:33,400 --> 00:31:34,640
- The coats.

469
00:31:34,680 --> 00:31:37,960
Calm down, Mr. Bailey
writes about rich people.

470
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:40,240
- Like us?

471
00:31:40,280 --> 00:31:43,120
- Us, I love that word.

472
00:31:43,160 --> 00:31:45,400
- Well, we made it through
the first party

473
00:31:45,440 --> 00:31:46,960
without anyone asking
us to leave.

474
00:31:47,000 --> 00:31:48,680
- Oh, we haven't made it
to the door yet.

475
00:31:49,920 --> 00:31:51,720
Will we ever fit in
with this crowd, Elias?

476
00:31:51,760 --> 00:31:52,920
- No problem.

477
00:31:52,960 --> 00:31:55,320
We're important people now,
a team,

478
00:31:55,360 --> 00:31:56,920
and don't you ever forget that.

479
00:31:58,080 --> 00:31:59,920
- I love you, Elias.

480
00:31:59,960 --> 00:32:01,480
- Same here.

481
00:32:01,520 --> 00:32:05,360
Now, let's go look at
that $6 million Monet

482
00:32:05,400 --> 00:32:07,400
and make sure it's the
right color pink.

483
00:32:22,400 --> 00:32:23,480
[coins rattling]

484
00:32:23,520 --> 00:32:24,920
- They shouldn't allow this.

485
00:32:31,880 --> 00:32:33,240
- You give him anything?

486
00:32:33,280 --> 00:32:34,680
- It's hard to pretend
you have no money

487
00:32:34,720 --> 00:32:36,640
when you're climbing
into a limousine.

488
00:32:36,680 --> 00:32:38,840
- Oh, let's go to The
Carlyle hear Bobby Short.

489
00:32:44,200 --> 00:32:47,200
- Would you like a ride
home, Miss Altemus?

490
00:32:47,240 --> 00:32:50,120
- No, thank you, I have
a driver and a car.

491
00:32:50,160 --> 00:32:51,360
Actually, it's my mother's car.

492
00:32:52,640 --> 00:32:55,720
- Well, maybe you'd like
to give me a ride home.

493
00:32:55,760 --> 00:32:57,880
- Well, my driver doubles
as my bodyguard.

494
00:32:59,600 --> 00:33:01,440
- Only my thoughts
will be impure.

495
00:33:04,960 --> 00:33:07,880
[Justine chuckles]

496
00:33:16,760 --> 00:33:17,760
Do you like it?

497
00:33:17,800 --> 00:33:18,720
My place, I mean.

498
00:33:20,440 --> 00:33:22,320
- Actually, no.

499
00:33:23,400 --> 00:33:25,080
I know that I look crestfallen.

500
00:33:25,120 --> 00:33:27,320
I've been brought up
on Empire sofas

501
00:33:27,360 --> 00:33:31,240
and the neoclassic look as
dictated by Cora Mandell.

502
00:33:31,280 --> 00:33:33,480
- [Bernie] Who's Cora Mandell?

503
00:33:33,520 --> 00:33:36,360
- Well, the doyenne
of decorators.

504
00:33:36,400 --> 00:33:39,040
- Is that what you do
for a living, decorating?

505
00:33:39,080 --> 00:33:40,160
Or don't you work?

506
00:33:43,440 --> 00:33:47,680
- I'm very involved
with several charities.

507
00:33:47,720 --> 00:33:51,360
And one day a week, I work at
a hospital as a nurse's aide.

508
00:33:55,200 --> 00:33:56,520
- Sounds strenuous.

509
00:33:58,560 --> 00:34:00,760
When do you find time to relax?

510
00:34:00,800 --> 00:34:01,920
- I'm here now, aren't I?

511
00:34:03,080 --> 00:34:05,120
In that cab, that is what
you offered me.

512
00:34:07,880 --> 00:34:11,560
[gentle instrumental music]

513
00:34:19,480 --> 00:34:21,680
