I wouldn't.

767
00:49:37,680 --> 00:49:38,800
- [Lord Biedermeier]
That's just it, Elias.

768
00:49:38,840 --> 00:49:40,920
You're not the average
Joe, not any longer.

769
00:49:40,960 --> 00:49:43,280
And please call me Lucien.

770
00:49:43,320 --> 00:49:45,360
You've made the American
dream a reality,

771
00:49:45,400 --> 00:49:48,440
and the public wants
to know how.

772
00:49:48,480 --> 00:49:50,040
- A book, huh?

773
00:49:50,080 --> 00:49:51,560
I'll have to think about that.

774
00:49:51,600 --> 00:49:53,720
I'm going to London on business.

775
00:49:53,760 --> 00:49:56,240
You could reach me at
the Claridge's Hotel.

776
00:49:56,280 --> 00:49:57,640
- Simply Claridge's, Elias.

777
00:49:57,680 --> 00:50:01,080
Not The Claridge's, nor The
Claridge's Hotel, either.

778
00:50:01,120 --> 00:50:04,440
[patrons chattering]

779
00:50:04,480 --> 00:50:05,440
- Hello, Justine.

780
00:50:05,480 --> 00:50:07,160
Haven't seen you for
quite a while.

781
00:50:07,200 --> 00:50:08,440
How've you been?

782
00:50:08,480 --> 00:50:10,320
- I've been in love, Chick.

783
00:50:10,360 --> 00:50:12,320
- [Chick] That's wonderful.

784
00:50:12,360 --> 00:50:13,920
Excuse me.

785
00:50:13,960 --> 00:50:17,040
- [Elias] People Like Us,
I like that.

786
00:50:17,080 --> 00:50:18,560
So will Ruby.

787
00:50:18,600 --> 00:50:20,840
- [Lucien] By the way,
who's your tailor?

788
00:50:20,880 --> 00:50:25,320
I could recommend mine
if you don't have one.

789
00:50:25,360 --> 00:50:27,440
- Who is that
horribly dressed man

790
00:50:27,480 --> 00:50:29,280
lunching with Lord Biedermeier?

791
00:50:29,320 --> 00:50:31,680
- It's Elias Renthal,
the financier.

792
00:50:31,720 --> 00:50:34,760
- Oh, oh, I read about him in
his wife in Dolly's column.

793
00:50:34,800 --> 00:50:37,120
The new people. [chuckling]

794
00:50:37,160 --> 00:50:39,600
Well, I'll have whatever
Justine's drinking, Chick.

795
00:50:42,880 --> 00:50:45,120
I suppose you invited your
mother to lunch

796
00:50:45,160 --> 00:50:47,280
to discuss Mr. Bernard Slatkin.

797
00:50:48,800 --> 00:50:50,520
- Who have you been talking to,
Mother?

798
00:50:50,560 --> 00:50:52,800
- Well, Joe doesn't tell tales,

799
00:50:52,840 --> 00:50:54,800
but you have been keeping
him and the car out

800
00:50:54,840 --> 00:50:55,840
frightfully late.

801
00:50:57,280 --> 00:50:58,480
- I'd like to show you the ring

802
00:50:58,520 --> 00:51:00,360
that Bernie has given me, look.

803
00:51:02,640 --> 00:51:05,320
- Well, that's a garnet,
for God's sake.

804
00:51:05,360 --> 00:51:07,680
With a lot of pokey
little diamonds around it.

805
00:51:09,520 --> 00:51:11,920
An announcer who earns as
much as he's reputed to

806
00:51:11,960 --> 00:51:13,480
certainly can do
better than that.

807
00:51:13,520 --> 00:51:15,320
- But he's an anchorman,
not an announcer.

808
00:51:15,360 --> 00:51:17,240
And the ring belonged
to his aunt.

809
00:51:17,280 --> 00:51:18,440
- Yes, I'm sure it did.

810
00:51:19,360 --> 00:51:20,600
Well, just turn it back around,

811
00:51:20,640 --> 00:51:23,360
so when we leave and say
hello to Violet and Ezzie,

812
00:51:23,400 --> 00:51:24,560
they won't notice.

813
00:51:30,280 --> 00:51:31,640
- I found someone I love,
Mother,

814
00:51:31,680 --> 00:51:33,760
and I'm going to marry him.

815
00:51:33,800 --> 00:51:35,680
I hoped that you'd be
happy for me.

816
00:51:37,520 --> 00:51:40,960
- You know I've always
wanted you to marry, Justine.

817
00:51:41,000 --> 00:51:43,800
I would simply prefer my
son-in-law to be one of us.

818
00:51:44,880 --> 00:51:46,680
I'm sure his family
feels the same.

819
00:51:47,560 --> 00:51:48,920
- Bernie's parents are dead.

820
00:51:48,960 --> 00:51:50,680
He was raised by his
aunt and uncle.

821
00:51:51,600 --> 00:51:53,160
- How unfortunate for everyone.

822
00:51:55,160 --> 00:51:57,320
Well, since that piece of
jewelry appears to mean

823
00:51:57,360 --> 00:51:58,400
what I think it does,

824
00:51:58,440 --> 00:52:00,760
we should discuss plans
for the wedding.

825
00:52:02,320 --> 00:52:05,000
- Oh, Bernie and I want to
invite family and a few friends.

826
00:52:05,040 --> 00:52:07,160
We'd like to keep the
occasion intimate and small.

827
00:52:07,200 --> 00:52:09,280
- Your ring is small enough.

828
00:52:10,640 --> 00:52:13,280
You are my only daughter,
Justine.

829
00:52:13,320 --> 00:52:15,480
And I insist on giving
you a proper wedding.

830
00:52:16,760 --> 00:52:18,760
You know, I wanna do
this for you.

831
00:52:18,800 --> 00:52:20,360
Now please, don't be difficult.

832
00:52:21,760 --> 00:52:23,440
- If you won't be when
Daddy gives me away.

833
00:52:24,880 --> 00:52:27,360
- I haven't cared about
anything your father has done

834
00:52:27,400 --> 00:52:28,800
in the last 10 years.

835
00:52:30,600 --> 00:52:33,600
Now, when am I going to
meet your Mr. Slatkin?

836
00:52:34,760 --> 00:52:36,240
- As soon as you say, Mother.

837
00:52:38,720 --> 00:52:40,280
- Cocktails and hors d'oeuvres

838
00:52:40,320 --> 00:52:42,880
with the entire family,
of course.

839
00:52:42,920 --> 00:52:44,440
Although I don't know how
my dear brother

840
00:52:44,480 --> 00:52:46,160
is going to react to this news.

841
00:52:47,600 --> 00:52:49,720
- Well, he'll just have
to keep a stiff upper lip.

842
00:52:49,760 --> 00:52:50,720
It shouldn't be too difficult

843
00:52:50,760 --> 00:52:52,440
for uncle Laurance,
shouldn't it?

844
00:53:03,600 --> 00:53:06,360
- I really liked your
father and your stepmother.

845
00:53:06,400 --> 00:53:09,440
But you never told me why
your parents got divorced.

846
00:53:10,920 --> 00:53:14,520
- Hmm, I think you'll understand
once you've met my mother.

847
00:53:14,560 --> 00:53:16,480
She can be dreadful.

848
00:53:16,520 --> 00:53:19,720
Polite and charming
[chuckling] but dreadful.

849
00:53:20,880 --> 00:53:23,040
- I know all about
people like your mother.

850
00:53:25,080 --> 00:53:26,960
I'm in show business, remember?

851
00:53:39,240 --> 00:53:41,360
- So, why the party, Mother?

852
00:53:41,400 --> 00:53:43,360
I thought you didn't
approve of Bernie.

853
00:53:43,400 --> 00:53:45,600
- I can't ignore the situation,

854
00:53:45,640 --> 00:53:47,840
so it's best just to
put on an approving face

855
00:53:47,880 --> 00:53:50,560
and keep one's private
thoughts to oneself.

856
00:53:50,600 --> 00:53:52,760
I think you'll find a
tie in your old room.

857
00:53:54,920 --> 00:53:56,480
- I'm not staying.

858
00:53:56,520 --> 00:53:57,640
- What?

859
00:53:57,680 --> 00:53:59,080
[laughing]

860
00:53:59,120 --> 00:54:01,520
- No, I can't stand the thought
of being in the same room

861
00:54:01,560 --> 00:54:03,560
with uncle Laurance
and aunt Janet,

862
00:54:03,600 --> 00:54:05,600
or my cousin and his
dreary wife.

863
00:54:05,640 --> 00:54:08,040
- I won't hear a word
against my dear brother.

864
00:54:09,560 --> 00:54:11,720
- Your dear brother
can't stand me, either.

865
00:54:11,760 --> 00:54:13,120
He fired me.

866
00:54:13,160 --> 00:54:15,160
Didn't approve of my
lifestyle, wasn't that it?

867
00:54:15,200 --> 00:54:17,080
- You don't work at
the bank anymore

868
00:54:17,120 --> 00:54:19,080
and all those pressures
are behind you.

869
00:54:21,440 --> 00:54:23,200
- I love Justine and I would
do absolutely anything for her,

870
00:54:23,240 --> 00:54:24,680
but I am still going, Mother.

871
00:54:24,720 --> 00:54:27,200
- And one of these days
you'll find the right girl

872
00:54:27,240 --> 00:54:29,200
and make your old
mother really happy.

873
00:54:31,120 --> 00:54:33,320
My dear Hubie, you look tired.

874
00:54:36,920 --> 00:54:38,280
- Wish Justine luck for me.

875
00:54:40,880 --> 00:54:44,560
[gentle instrumental music]

876
00:55:09,240 --> 00:55:12,000
[all chattering]

877
00:55:22,080 --> 00:55:24,400
- [Justine] Mother,
this is Bernard Slatkin.

878
00:55:24,440 --> 00:55:25,640
- Hello, how are you?

879
00:55:25,680 --> 00:55:27,160
- Pleasure to meet you, ma'am.

880
00:55:27,200 --> 00:55:30,040
- Mr. Slatkin, may I present
my brother, Laurance Van Degan.

881
00:55:30,080 --> 00:55:31,400
- Mr. Slatkin.

882
00:55:31,440 --> 00:55:32,600
- [Lil] And his wife, Janet.

883
00:55:32,640 --> 00:55:33,840
- Hello, how are you?

884
00:55:33,880 --> 00:55:35,960
- [Lil] And my father,
Ormonde Van Degan.

885
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:38,520
Father, this is
Justine's fiance.

886
00:55:38,560 --> 00:55:40,000
- [Bernie] Nice to meet you,
sir.

887
00:55:40,040 --> 00:55:42,640
- [Lil] Oh, and yes, our
cousin, Dodo Fitz Alyn,

888
00:55:42,680 --> 00:55:45,720
my father's loyal companion.
- So happy to meet you.

889
00:55:45,760 --> 00:55:47,520
- [Lil] My nephew,
Young Laurance.

890
00:55:47,560 --> 00:55:48,680
- Mr. Slatkin.

891
00:55:48,720 --> 00:55:50,480
- [Lil] And his wife, Laura.

892
00:55:50,520 --> 00:55:51,760
- Hello.

893
00:55:51,800 --> 00:55:53,800
- Nice to meet you both.

894
00:55:53,840 --> 00:55:55,360
- Oh.

895
00:55:55,400 --> 00:55:58,320
Oh, Parker, tell Gertie
the canapes look yummy.

896
00:55:58,360 --> 00:55:59,360
- Thank you, Parker.

897
00:56:02,720 --> 00:56:04,520
- Some smoked salmon, Mr.
Slatkin?

898
00:56:17,400 --> 00:56:18,720
- [Elias] Max, just because
you're my head trader

899
00:56:18,760 --> 00:56:20,160
and we go back a long time

900
00:56:20,200 --> 00:56:22,040
doesn't mean that you can talk
to me any way you want to.

901
00:56:22,080 --> 00:56:23,360
- [Max] And why not?

902
00:56:23,400 --> 00:56:25,360
I'm the guy who sold the
hamburgers you used to make

903
00:56:25,400 --> 00:56:27,600
while you dreamed about owning
your own franchise someday.

904
00:56:27,640 --> 00:56:28,640
- [Elias] So?

905
00:56:28,680 --> 00:56:30,040
- I also remember you
used to think

906
00:56:30,080 --> 00:56:32,760
the world would be your
oyster if you had a million.

907
00:56:32,800 --> 00:56:34,640
Then I remember you set
10 million as your goal,

908
00:56:34,680 --> 00:56:36,760
then 50, then 100.
- What's your point?

909
00:56:36,800 --> 00:56:39,000
- The point is, you've got
$3 billion now.

910
00:56:39,040 --> 00:56:40,120
When are you gonna stop?

911
00:56:40,160 --> 00:56:41,880
- I can't stop, Max, it's
too damn easy.

912
00:56:41,920 --> 00:56:43,320
You know what it's like?

913
00:56:43,360 --> 00:56:45,800
It's like putting a hunk of
red meat in front of a lion.

914
00:56:45,840 --> 00:56:47,600
Besides, how else am I gonna pay

915
00:56:47,640 --> 00:56:49,120
for that new office building?

916
00:56:50,600 --> 00:56:52,640
- I certainly wouldn't
presume to tell you

917
00:56:52,680 --> 00:56:54,120
what to write, Gus.

918
00:56:54,160 --> 00:56:56,800
But the family would prefer
that you focus the article

919
00:56:56,840 --> 00:57:00,280
more on Justine's background
rather than on Bernie's.

920
00:57:00,320 --> 00:57:00,600
Jewish.

921
00:57:02,160 --> 00:57:04,840
- Bernie's heritage doesn't
seem to matter to Justine, Lil.

922
00:57:04,880 --> 00:57:06,480
- Well, it should matter, Gus.

923
00:57:06,520 --> 00:57:07,840
Marrying an outsider
can do nothing

924
00:57:07,880 --> 00:57:10,520
but create problems
for everyone.

925
00:57:10,560 --> 00:57:12,440
Oh, there's Ezzie and Violet.

926
00:57:13,880 --> 00:57:15,840
There's that cheap man
one's always hearing about.

927
00:57:15,880 --> 00:57:17,240
What is his name?

928
00:57:17,280 --> 00:57:18,800
- [Gus] Elias Renthal.

929
00:57:18,840 --> 00:57:21,080
- Laurance actually wants me
to invite him and his wife

930
00:57:21,120 --> 00:57:22,120
to Justine's wedding.

931
00:57:22,160 --> 00:57:24,480
I mean, he says that's
important to us.

932
00:57:24,520 --> 00:57:26,440
The world has gone mad.

933
00:57:29,920 --> 00:57:31,000
- Mr. Bailey.

934
00:57:32,920 --> 00:57:34,200
- Call me Gus.

935
00:57:34,240 --> 00:57:35,520
- I want you to meet Max Luby,

936
00:57:35,560 --> 00:57:36,800
an old friend and
associate of mine.

937
00:57:36,840 --> 00:57:38,360
- How do you do?

938
00:57:38,400 --> 00:57:41,000
I don't believe you've
met Lil Altemus.

939
00:57:41,040 --> 00:57:42,320
- Hello, how are you?

940
00:57:42,360 --> 00:57:43,280
- Fine, thanks.

941
00:57:44,680 --> 00:57:45,680
I know your brother.

942
00:57:49,880 --> 00:57:53,600
We're in a couple of
business deals together.

943
00:57:53,640 --> 00:57:54,480
- Really?

944
00:57:58,720 --> 00:57:59,920
- Well, I guess
we'll go sit down

945
00:57:59,960 --> 00:58:01,480
before they give our seats away.

946
00:58:03,320 --> 00:58:05,080
Well, it was nice meeting you,
Lil.

947
00:58:08,200 --> 00:58:09,360
See you, Gus.

948
00:58:12,600 --> 00:58:13,840
- I simply can't imagine

949
00:58:13,880 --> 00:58:16,160
Laurance doing business
with that man.

950
00:58:16,200 --> 00:58:18,800
I mean, it's ridiculous,
it's absolutely ridiculous.

951
00:58:21,440 --> 00:58:24,120
[phone ringing]

952
00:58:24,800 --> 00:58:26,000
- Hello.

953
00:58:26,040 --> 00:58:28,560
- Damn it, Gus, I've
tried calling you all day

954
00:58:28,600 --> 00:58:30,240
but you're never in.

955
00:58:30,280 --> 00:58:32,440
I have some information for you.

956
00:58:32,480 --> 00:58:34,080
- Peach, what's going on?

957
00:58:34,120 --> 00:58:36,640
- I had a call from
Lieutenant Jackson.

958
00:58:36,680 --> 00:58:39,200
He wanted me to be the
one to tell you.

959
00:58:39,240 --> 00:58:43,080
The date for Flint's parole
hearing has been moved up

960
00:58:43,120 --> 00:58:44,400
due to good behavior.

961
00:58:45,520 --> 00:58:46,360
- I see.

962
00:58:48,120 --> 00:58:49,400
Okay, bye.

963
00:58:53,840 --> 00:58:57,520
[gentle instrumental music]

964
00:59:11,600 --> 00:59:13,680
- Now, what exactly do
you have in mind?

965
00:59:13,720 --> 00:59:15,840
I mean, in regards to this Mr.
Flint.

966
00:59:15,880 --> 00:59:17,400
- [Gus] I want you to
keep track of him

967
00:59:17,440 --> 00:59:18,480
if he gets out next month.

968
00:59:19,760 --> 00:59:23,800
Where he lives and what
he does with his time.

969
00:59:23,840 --> 00:59:25,080
- Is that all?
- For now, yes.

970
00:59:26,320 --> 00:59:29,600
- So, you want this guy
thrown out a window?

971
00:59:31,040 --> 00:59:32,880
- No, I don't want
anything like that.

972
00:59:32,920 --> 00:59:34,520
- It could look like
an accident.

973
00:59:35,680 --> 00:59:36,960
You wouldn't meet the
person who'd do it

974
00:59:37,000 --> 00:59:38,920
and he'd never know your name.

975
00:59:38,960 --> 00:59:42,400
Easy, not cheap, but safe.

976
00:59:45,200 --> 00:59:46,200
- No, Mr. Feliciano.

977
00:59:48,400 --> 00:59:49,880
I have something else in mind.

978
00:59:52,080 --> 00:59:52,880
Hi, Peach.

979
00:59:55,040 --> 00:59:55,840
How are you feeling?

980
00:59:57,040 --> 00:59:59,760
- Old, if you want to know,
and I hate it.

981
00:59:59,800 --> 01:00:03,320
- I wanted you to know I hired
a detective to watch Flint.

982
01:00:03,360 --> 01:00:05,120
If he's released after
that hearing.

983
01:00:06,160 --> 01:00:07,160
- He can't be let out.

984
01:00:08,400 --> 01:00:10,760
Dear God, has everyone
forgotten what he did?

985
01:00:12,080 --> 01:00:14,360
I want to go to that
parole hearing, Gus.

986
01:00:14,400 --> 01:00:15,600
I have to tell them again

987
01:00:15,640 --> 01:00:17,720
what he did to a
beautiful daughter.

988
01:00:18,640 --> 01:00:20,360
I have to make them remember.

989
01:00:20,400 --> 01:00:22,200
I want them to remember.

990
01:00:22,240 --> 01:00:23,880
- They won't forget Becky,
Peach.

991
01:00:25,000 --> 01:00:26,200
I won't let them forget.

992
01:00:31,600 --> 01:00:34,520
- I wish you could go to
the wedding too, Juanito.

993
01:00:34,560 --> 01:00:36,400
- Maybe if I dressed up
as a loaf of white bread.

994
01:00:36,440 --> 01:00:38,000
- No, it wouldn't work.

995
01:00:38,040 --> 01:00:39,240
You would forget to cut
off the crusts,

996
01:00:39,280 --> 01:00:40,280
and then uncle Laurance

997
01:00:40,320 --> 01:00:42,160
would see right through
your disguise.

998
01:00:43,800 --> 01:00:45,360
- Your sister said she liked me.

999
01:00:45,400 --> 01:00:46,880
- She does and if it were
up to Justine,

1000
01:00:46,920 --> 01:00:47,960
she would have invited you,

1001
01:00:48,000 --> 01:00:49,720
but she's walking on
eggshells as it is

1002
01:00:49,760 --> 01:00:52,040
with this TV announcer.

1003
01:00:52,080 --> 01:00:53,280
- Isn't that what's called
marrying beneath you?

1004
01:00:53,320 --> 01:00:55,360
You know, you two are
a lot alike.

1005
01:00:55,400 --> 01:00:57,000
- Stop that, will you, please?

1006
01:00:57,040 --> 01:00:58,600
I hate it when you're that way.

1007
01:00:58,640 --> 01:00:59,720
- Honest?

1008
01:00:59,760 --> 01:01:00,920
- Bitchy.

1009
01:01:00,960 --> 01:01:02,200
You're like my mother.

1010
01:01:02,240 --> 01:01:04,200
[laughing]
- That's a low blow.

1011
01:01:22,120 --> 01:01:23,880
- How does this look?

1012
01:01:25,360 --> 01:01:27,920
- Look up here. [mumbles]

1013
01:01:27,960 --> 01:01:28,800
Thanks.

1014
01:01:32,880 --> 01:01:36,320
[Hubie groaning]

1015
01:01:36,360 --> 01:01:38,120
You could never tell.

1016
01:01:42,960 --> 01:01:44,840
Hubie, give it a little
more of an angle.

1017
01:01:44,880 --> 01:01:45,720
- You do it.

1018
01:01:46,600 --> 01:01:47,400
- Perfect.

1019
01:01:47,440 --> 01:01:48,280
Now let's go.

1020
01:01:48,320 --> 01:01:49,640
I gotta get back to the gallery.

1021
01:01:49,680 --> 01:01:51,760
One of us has to work
for a living.

1022
01:01:51,800 --> 01:01:54,960
[church bell tolling]

1023
01:02:11,160 --> 01:02:12,240
- Couldn't they have
gotten married

1024
01:02:12,280 --> 01:02:14,240
someplace a little
closer than Long Island?

1025
01:02:14,280 --> 01:02:16,680
- Bernie told us all of
Justine's people

1026
01:02:16,720 --> 01:02:19,480
get baptized, married,
and buried in this church.

1027
01:02:19,520 --> 01:02:21,000
It's their family tradition.

1028
01:02:21,040 --> 01:02:22,120
- [Sol] I still think my nephew

1029
01:02:22,160 --> 01:02:23,840
should be married in
a synagogue.

1030
01:02:23,880 --> 01:02:27,000
- And I say be glad that
Bernie's getting married.

1031
01:02:30,920 --> 01:02:34,000
[gentle organ music]

1032
01:02:53,440 --> 01:02:55,400
Where do you suppose
the girl is?

1033
01:02:55,440 --> 01:02:56,960
- Aren't brides always late?

1034
01:02:59,320 --> 01:03:00,160
- I wasn't.

1035
01:03:02,040 --> 01:03:04,640
[Sol chuckles]

1036
01:03:11,600 --> 01:03:13,080
- [Photographer] Mrs. Altemus,

1037
01:03:13,120 --> 01:03:14,840
would you look this way, please.

1038
01:03:14,880 --> 01:03:18,200
Thank you.
[camera shutter clicking]

1039
01:03:18,240 --> 01:03:20,400
- [Girl] Come on, there she is,
hurry.

1040
01:03:20,440 --> 01:03:24,200
[girls giggling and gasping]

1041
01:03:35,000 --> 01:03:37,320
- Hello, Lil.
- Hubert.

1042
01:03:37,360 --> 01:03:38,440
- Hello, Father.

1043
01:03:38,480 --> 01:03:39,760
- Hello, Hubie.

1044
01:03:39,800 --> 01:03:41,200
- Oh, it's a lovely bouquet,
Justine.

1045
01:03:41,240 --> 01:03:42,960
No one like Lorenza for flowers.

1046
01:03:43,000 --> 01:03:44,120
- Do I look all right, Mother?

1047
01:03:44,160 --> 01:03:44,960
- You look perfect.

1048
01:03:45,000 --> 01:03:46,480
Nevel at his best.

1049
01:03:47,680 --> 01:03:48,680
- Well, I meant me.

1050
01:03:48,720 --> 01:03:49,920
- You look beautiful, Justine.

1051
01:03:49,960 --> 01:03:52,000
- Hubie, it's time for
you to take me in.

1052
01:03:55,520 --> 01:03:56,360
- Good luck, Justine.

1053
01:03:56,400 --> 01:03:57,880
I really want you to be happy.

1054
01:03:59,240 --> 01:04:00,000
- Hubie, what's that?

1055
01:04:01,520 --> 01:04:04,480
- It's nothing, it's just an
irritation from my aftershave.

1056
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:13,840
["Bridal Chorus"]

1057
01:05:05,160 --> 01:05:10,160
[jazzy music]
[girls giggling]

1058
01:05:16,440 --> 01:05:17,480
- You're gaining a lot of space

1059
01:05:17,520 --> 01:05:18,480
in the columns lately, I see.

1060
01:05:18,520 --> 01:05:20,040
- Oh, can you believe this?

1061
01:05:20,080 --> 01:05:21,520
You'd think I was
somebody important.

1062
01:05:21,560 --> 01:05:22,400
- You are.

1063
01:05:28,760 --> 01:05:31,680
- I'm with firm of Weldon
and Stinchfield, Mr. Renthal.

1064
01:05:32,720 --> 01:05:34,280
- They handle a lot
of takeovers.

1065
01:05:34,320 --> 01:05:35,200
- We do our share.

1066
01:05:36,880 --> 01:05:38,280
- Let's talk later.

1067
01:05:38,320 --> 01:05:40,160
I'm really interested
in takeovers.

1068
01:05:45,800 --> 01:05:47,440
- If I ever strike it rich,
my wife and I

1069
01:05:47,480 --> 01:05:50,160
would like to build a home
in Fairfield, in Darien.

1070
01:05:51,280 --> 01:05:53,120
But it's hard with kids.

1071
01:05:54,200 --> 01:05:55,800
We have two little girls.

1072
01:05:55,840 --> 01:05:58,320
- I'm sure in time that
could be arranged, Byron.

1073
01:06:00,520 --> 01:06:02,240
For the proposal I have in mind,

1074
01:06:02,280 --> 01:06:03,560
there would be nothing risky.

1075
01:06:04,920 --> 01:06:08,720
All you'd have to do is
identify certain companies

1076
01:06:08,760 --> 01:06:12,480
that retain Weldon and
Stinchfield in an advisory capacity.

1077
01:06:13,760 --> 01:06:16,360
You know, before takeovers
and mergers happen.

1078
01:06:16,400 --> 01:06:17,480
- This is beautiful.

1079
01:06:19,000 --> 01:06:20,400
- It belonged to Edward VII.

1080
01:06:22,160 --> 01:06:23,320
It's the original felt.

1081
01:06:25,120 --> 01:06:25,920
- Holy smoke.

1082
01:06:29,720 --> 01:06:34,000
- I'd be willing to pay
5% on any profit I make

1083
01:06:35,040 --> 01:06:38,760
with your help, paid in cash,
say,

1084
01:06:38,800 --> 01:06:43,800
on 80,000 shares of West
Virginian Natural Gas.

1085
01:06:46,400 --> 01:06:49,120
It would be a very
handsome amount.

1086
01:06:52,520 --> 01:06:53,320
- Holy smoke.

1087
01:06:54,880 --> 01:06:56,960
- Shall we go now and have
another brandy?

1088
01:07:05,440 --> 01:07:08,680
- Okay, Gus, I want you
to be honest with me.

1089
01:07:08,720 --> 01:07:10,040
What do you think?

1090
01:07:10,080 --> 01:07:11,840
- Well, I seem to be at a
loss for words.

1091
01:07:11,880 --> 01:07:13,160
I don't know how I'm gonna begin

1092
01:07:13,200 --> 01:07:14,960
to describe all this
in my article.

1093
01:07:15,000 --> 01:07:16,760
- Well, do me a favor, try
to write about our apartment

1094
01:07:16,800 --> 01:07:17,640
and not about us.

1095
01:07:18,840 --> 01:07:20,280
Elias thinks my picture's
been in the paper

1096
01:07:20,320 --> 01:07:21,440
too much already.

1097
01:07:21,480 --> 01:07:22,440
- It is.

1098
01:07:22,480 --> 01:07:23,560
And we gotta be careful.

1099
01:07:23,600 --> 01:07:25,000
There are a lot of crazy
people out there

1100
01:07:25,040 --> 01:07:27,160
who like to read about
people like us.

1101
01:07:27,200 --> 01:07:28,840
- Elias wants me to carry a gun.

1102
01:07:28,880 --> 01:07:31,120
- It's for your own protection.

1103
01:07:31,160 --> 01:07:32,640
- Look at this little
pearl-handled number he gave me

1104
01:07:32,680 --> 01:07:33,800
as a stocking present.

1105
01:07:33,840 --> 01:07:37,160
It used to belong to
Queen Marie of Romania.

1106
01:07:37,200 --> 01:07:38,600
Oh, don't be afraid, I
never keep it loaded.

1107
01:07:38,640 --> 01:07:41,000
It's just for show,
you might say.

1108
01:07:41,040 --> 01:07:42,760
- That's not why I bought
you the damn thing, Ruby.

1109
01:07:42,800 --> 01:07:44,040
- [Housekeeper] Excuse me,

1110
01:07:44,080 --> 01:07:45,800
Mr. Van Degan is on the
telephone, Mr. Renthal.

1111
01:07:45,840 --> 01:07:47,720
- All right, tell him I'll
be right there.

1112
01:07:48,920 --> 01:07:51,960
Ruby, why don't you
take Gus on a tour, huh?

1113
01:07:52,000 --> 01:07:53,800
Don't forget to show
him the fumary.

1114
01:07:57,280 --> 01:07:58,760
- You know, in California,
the first thing they do

1115
01:07:58,800 --> 01:08:00,920
after they give you a drink,
they show you their closets.

1116
01:08:00,960 --> 01:08:03,600
[Ruby chuckles]

1117
01:08:07,120 --> 01:08:08,760
- [Ruby] Will you
stay for dinner?

1118
01:08:08,800 --> 01:08:11,200
- I can't, I'm leaving
for the coast tonight.

1119
01:08:11,240 --> 01:08:13,400
Lefty Flint, the man who
murdered my daughter,

1120
01:08:13,440 --> 01:08:16,000
his parole hearing is
tomorrow afternoon.

1121
01:08:16,040 --> 01:08:17,520
- But he's only been in
prison for a year.

1122
01:08:17,560 --> 01:08:20,880
- Yeah, and Becky would
have been 24 this fall.

1123
01:08:21,840 --> 01:08:23,760
- Is your wife going with you?

1124
01:08:23,800 --> 01:08:25,080
- No, I talked her out of it.

1125
01:08:25,120 --> 01:08:26,640
She's not well enough.

1126
01:08:26,680 --> 01:08:28,280
And besides, there's no
point in her going through

1127
01:08:28,320 --> 01:08:30,600
what we went through in
court all over again.

1128
01:08:32,640 --> 01:08:35,440
- Well, there's a chance his
parole will be denied, right?

1129
01:08:35,480 --> 01:08:36,760
- Slim one.

1130
01:08:36,800 --> 01:08:38,880
He's been a model prisoner.

1131
01:08:38,920 --> 01:08:41,160
So, as far as the judicial
system is concerned,

1132
01:08:41,200 --> 01:08:43,560
he will have paid his
debt to society.

1133
01:08:43,600 --> 01:08:45,200
- Well, this isn't justice.

1134
01:08:45,240 --> 01:08:46,280
- [Gus] No, it isn't.

1135
01:08:49,160 --> 01:08:51,680
- Look, Gus, why don't
we take the grand tour

1136
01:08:51,720 --> 01:08:53,160
when you get back?

1137
01:08:53,200 --> 01:08:54,640
- And missing the fumary?

1138
01:08:55,560 --> 01:08:56,400
No way.

1139
01:08:59,600 --> 01:09:03,240
[gentle instrumental music]

1140
01:09:55,120 --> 01:09:57,080
- Macumber, why are you
calling me here?

1141
01:09:57,120 --> 01:09:58,720
I told you never to do that.

1142
01:09:58,760 --> 01:10:01,840
- I apologize, Mr. Renthal,
but I'm not in my office

1143
01:10:01,880 --> 01:10:04,320
and this was the only
number I could remember.

1144
01:10:04,360 --> 01:10:05,520
I thought this was urgent.

1145
01:10:05,560 --> 01:10:07,480
- All right, so
where's the fire?

1146
01:10:07,520 --> 01:10:11,320
- Omaha Fuel has hired Weldon
and Stinchfield as an advisor

1147
01:10:11,360 --> 01:10:15,880
on a proposal by Tri World
Incorporated to acquire them.

1148
01:10:15,920 --> 01:10:18,120
I thought you'd want to
know as soon as possible.

1149
01:10:18,160 --> 01:10:21,160
- All right, but from
now on you're Mr. Brown

1150
01:10:21,200 --> 01:10:23,360
and don't ever call
me here again.

1151
01:10:23,400 --> 01:10:25,760
- Yes, sir, I understand.

1152
01:10:26,640 --> 01:10:27,440
Goodnight.

1153
01:10:29,760 --> 01:10:30,680
[phone line humming]

1154
01:10:30,720 --> 01:10:31,560
[keypad beeping]

1155
01:10:31,600 --> 01:10:32,840
[phone line ringing]

1156
01:10:32,880 --> 01:10:34,440
- [Receptionist] Credit
Suisse of Nassau.

1157
01:10:34,480 --> 01:10:36,680
- Yeah, this is Mr. Rod
Nolte, get me Mr. Gerhard.

1158
01:10:37,920 --> 01:10:40,520
- [Gerhard] Yes, Mr.
Nolte, this is Gerhard.

1159
01:10:40,560 --> 01:10:44,720
- Buy 180,000 shares of
Omaha Natural Gas

1160
01:10:44,760 --> 01:10:47,440
the instant the market opens.

1161
01:10:47,480 --> 01:10:48,440
- [Gerhard] Anything else?

1162
01:10:48,480 --> 01:10:49,280
- [Elias] No, that's all.

1163
01:10:49,320 --> 01:10:50,640
I'll talk to you tomorrow.

1164
01:10:55,320 --> 01:10:56,440
- The smoke.

1165
01:10:56,480 --> 01:10:57,800
- [Elias] That's why
you got me this fumary

1166
01:10:57,840 --> 01:11:00,080
so I wouldn't cloud up
your fancy-schmancy rooms.

1167
01:11:00,120 --> 01:11:01,480
- Don't say fancy-schmancy.

1168
01:11:01,520 --> 01:11:02,760
- Why not?
- Because it's tacky,

1169
01:11:02,800 --> 01:11:03,680
we're past that.

1170
01:11:06,880 --> 01:11:09,280
Listen, honey, I forgot.

1171
01:11:09,320 --> 01:11:11,360
I'll need the plane real
early tomorrow.

1172
01:11:11,400 --> 01:11:13,480
There's an auction at the
California ranch

1173
01:11:13,520 --> 01:11:15,280
and there's a couple
of Remingtons.

1174
01:11:15,320 --> 01:11:18,600
- Couple of who?

1175
01:11:18,640 --> 01:11:19,880
- [Ruby] Horse sculptures.

1176
01:11:21,280 --> 01:11:23,840
I thought they might be
nice for the country house.

1177
01:11:23,880 --> 01:11:26,680
- Okay, have your secretary
set it up with the pilot.

1178
01:11:36,840 --> 01:11:38,040
- Thank you, sweetheart.

1179
01:11:39,920 --> 01:11:41,400
I love you, Elias.

1180
01:11:44,480 --> 01:11:48,120
[gentle instrumental music]

1181
01:12:03,080 --> 01:12:05,840
[dramatic music]

1182
01:12:08,400 --> 01:12:09,760
- [Officer] Let's go,
single file.

1183
01:12:09,800 --> 01:12:11,120
- [Inmate] Yep.

1184
01:12:11,160 --> 01:12:12,960
- [Officer] I saw that one,
Peter.

1185
01:12:13,000 --> 01:12:14,040
- And I can't believe

1186
01:12:14,080 --> 01:12:16,560
that 15 months
constitutes enough time

1187
01:12:17,880 --> 01:12:20,360
to rehabilitate the man
who murdered my daughter.

1188
01:12:22,560 --> 01:12:24,040
I only pray you agree with me.

1189
01:12:31,200 --> 01:12:34,080
- [Warden] We will consider
your remarks Mr. Bailey.

1190
01:12:34,120 --> 01:12:34,920
Thank you.

1191
01:12:42,160 --> 01:12:45,680
I now call Mrs. Elias
Renthal to speak.

1192
01:12:54,440 --> 01:12:57,880
[door clacking]

1193
01:12:57,920 --> 01:12:59,560
Mrs. Renthal, please.

1194
01:13:18,600 --> 01:13:20,720
- My name is Ruby Nolte Renthal,

1195
01:13:22,480 --> 01:13:25,240
and I've come here today
to plead with you

1196
01:13:25,280 --> 01:13:27,760
not to grant Francis
Flint an early release

1197
01:13:27,800 --> 01:13:29,040
from his prison sentence.

1198
01:13:29,080 --> 01:13:30,760
- Warden, I object.

1199
01:13:30,800 --> 01:13:33,520
- This is a hearing,
not a trial, Mr. Pink.

1200
01:13:33,560 --> 01:13:35,080
Objections are not recognized.

1201
01:13:38,240 --> 01:13:39,240
Go on, Mrs. Renthal.

1202
01:13:41,440 --> 01:13:44,960
- I had a two-year
relationship with Francis Flint

1203
01:13:46,240 --> 01:13:49,240
that ended before the
murder of Becky Bailey.

1204
01:13:56,120 --> 01:13:57,920
On four separate occasions,

1205
01:14:01,160 --> 01:14:04,680
Mr. Flint beat me.

1206
01:14:09,120 --> 01:14:13,720
On two separate occasions, I
was hospitalized as a result.

1207
01:14:15,720 --> 01:14:17,600
Once after he threw me
down a stairway

1208
01:14:17,640 --> 01:14:19,240
when I tried to escape from him.

1209
01:14:22,880 --> 01:14:27,000
Another after he broke my
nose and teeth,

1210
01:14:29,640 --> 01:14:33,360
blackened my eyes, and
fractured my jaw.

1211
01:14:35,920 --> 01:14:38,720
- [Warden] Didn't you
press charges at the time?

1212
01:14:38,760 --> 01:14:39,600
- No.

1213
01:14:40,880 --> 01:14:41,840
- I ask why.

1214
01:14:45,760 --> 01:14:46,920
- I was warned not to.

1215
01:14:49,000 --> 01:14:49,920
- By whom?

1216
01:14:49,960 --> 01:14:51,840
- That doesn't matter now.

1217
01:14:51,880 --> 01:14:54,240
All that matters is that
the jury at his trial

1218
01:14:54,280 --> 01:14:56,760
was allowed to think that
Becky Bailey strangulation

1219
01:14:56,800 --> 01:14:59,920
was one single isolated
incident, an accident.

1220
01:15:02,440 --> 01:15:03,280
That's not true.

1221
01:15:08,040 --> 01:15:11,600
Mr. Flint is a classic
abuser of women.

1222
01:15:16,080 --> 01:15:18,120
His weapon is his hands.

1223
01:15:18,160 --> 01:15:20,800
[chair squeaks]

1224
01:15:22,120 --> 01:15:22,960
- Sit down.

1225
01:15:28,040 --> 01:15:30,600
- Are you finished Mrs. Renthal?

1226
01:15:32,120 --> 01:15:32,960
- Yes.

1227
01:15:35,920 --> 01:15:36,840
Yes, am I excused?

1228
01:15:37,800 --> 01:15:38,640
- Certainly.

1229
01:15:38,680 --> 01:15:40,160
And thank you very much.

1230
01:16:01,080 --> 01:16:02,320
- Why didn't you tell me?

1231
01:16:04,920 --> 01:16:06,280
- Because I felt so guilty.

1232
01:16:09,440 --> 01:16:11,120
Ever since I heard about
Becky's death,

1233
01:16:11,160 --> 01:16:12,360
I've lived every day

1234
01:16:12,400 --> 01:16:14,760
knowing if I had only
gone to the police.

1235
01:16:16,240 --> 01:16:19,280
If I'd only done something,
Becky might still be alive.

1236
01:16:20,640 --> 01:16:22,360
- [Gus] Why say anything now?

1237
01:16:24,720 --> 01:16:26,160
- Because of you.

1238
01:16:30,280 --> 01:16:31,200
- Dear God.

1239
01:16:34,680 --> 01:16:36,640
- I knew Lefty years ago.

1240
01:16:38,920 --> 01:16:40,440
Long before he met Becky.

1241
01:16:42,920 --> 01:16:46,080
I just moved to Dallas, I
got a job as a waitress.

1242
01:16:47,440 --> 01:16:49,440
He played guitar at the
same restaurant.

1243
01:16:53,000 --> 01:16:54,560
I know you might find
this hard to believe,

1244
01:16:54,600 --> 01:16:57,880
but he could be very charming,
very sweet.

1245
01:16:59,600 --> 01:17:01,360
We started spending a lot
of time together

1246
01:17:01,400 --> 01:17:05,040
and after a while he
moved in with me.

1247
01:17:08,320 --> 01:17:10,680
It wasn't long before
the beatings started.

1248
01:17:12,040 --> 01:17:13,440
Afterwards, he'd always cry,

1249
01:17:13,480 --> 01:17:16,880
tell me how sorry he was, how
he never meant to hurt me.

1250
01:17:16,920 --> 01:17:19,120
- Why didn't you ask for help?

1251
01:17:19,160 --> 01:17:20,240
- I was too afraid.

1252
01:17:22,280 --> 01:17:25,680
When I did try to break
it off and get away,

1253
01:17:25,720 --> 01:17:27,080
Lefty came after me.

1254
01:17:30,280 --> 01:17:31,600
Oh, Gus, I'm sorry.

1255
01:17:33,480 --> 01:17:36,040
I am so sorry.
- I'm sorry, Ruby,

1256
01:17:37,720 --> 01:17:38,560
for both of us.

1257
01:17:40,600 --> 01:17:41,720
Does Elias know?
- No.

1258
01:17:43,600 --> 01:17:44,840
No, I never told him.

1259
01:17:46,280 --> 01:17:47,760
I've been so ashamed.

1260
01:17:49,160 --> 01:17:51,160
I felt dirty just being alive.

1261
01:17:55,160 --> 01:17:56,760
Even now I don't know if I
could tell him,

1262
01:17:56,800 --> 01:17:59,240
and he's the best thing
that ever happened to me.

1263
01:18:01,400 --> 01:18:02,360
Someday maybe.

1264
01:18:06,360 --> 01:18:08,600
Not now.

1265
01:18:08,640 --> 01:18:12,400
- Well, I'll call in
a few favors.

1266
01:18:12,440 --> 01:18:14,440
Keep your name out
of the papers.

1267
01:18:14,480 --> 01:18:15,640
- Oh.

1268
01:18:15,680 --> 01:18:19,360
- [Gus] Nobody will find
out about this, Ruby.

1269
01:18:19,400 --> 01:18:20,160
I promise you.

1270
01:18:20,200 --> 01:18:23,880
[gentle instrumental music]

1271
01:18:43,800 --> 01:18:46,000
- [Ruby] Tell Frida we'll
have lunch about one, I think.

1272
01:18:46,040 --> 01:18:47,440
I'll leave the menu to her.

1273
01:18:47,480 --> 01:18:49,080
- Very good, madam.

1274
01:18:58,520 --> 01:19:01,280
- [Ruby] You see, there is
some justice in this world.

1275
01:19:01,320 --> 01:19:03,200
- Hi, did I miss everything?

1276
01:19:03,240 --> 01:19:06,080
- [Ruby] Well, you're too
late for the Easter egg hunt.

1277
01:19:06,120 --> 01:19:08,920
- [Gus] This wouldn't have
happened without you, Ruby.

1278
01:19:08,960 --> 01:19:11,040
- You gave me the courage
to do it, Gus.

1279
01:19:11,080 --> 01:19:12,120
- [Gus] You remember
that other woman

1280
01:19:12,160 --> 01:19:12,920
who was at the hearing?

1281
01:19:12,960 --> 01:19:14,360
- [Ruby] Yes.

1282
01:19:14,400 --> 01:19:16,040
- [Gus] Yeah, well, I had a
detective do some checking,

1283
01:19:16,080 --> 01:19:19,200
and it seems like Lefty
has found his next victim.

1284
01:19:20,760 --> 01:19:22,360
- I was afraid of that.

1285
01:19:22,400 --> 01:19:23,200
- Thank you.

1286
01:19:23,240 --> 01:19:24,800
Her name is Marguerite Hanrahan.

1287
01:19:24,840 --> 01:19:27,520
She started writing to him
when he first went to prison.

1288
01:19:27,560 --> 01:19:29,800
And I guess she believed
he was born again

1289
01:19:29,840 --> 01:19:31,840
because now she's
gonna marry him.

1290
01:19:31,880 --> 01:19:32,960
- After everything she heard?

1291
01:19:33,000 --> 01:19:34,400
- Hard to believe, isn't it?

1292
01:19:35,400 --> 01:19:36,560
Somehow I've got to convince her

1293
01:19:36,600 --> 01:19:38,480
she's making a terrible mistake.

1294
01:19:38,520 --> 01:19:40,320
- You have to, Gus.

1295
01:19:40,360 --> 01:19:41,440
Somehow you have to.

1296
01:19:41,480 --> 01:19:43,120
- For her sake, I hope I can.

1297
01:19:44,520 --> 01:19:48,400
- Look at your anemones,
so beautiful.

1298
01:19:48,440 --> 01:19:51,120
Lorenza has been here, I see.
- Just.

1299
01:19:51,160 --> 01:19:53,520
Mrs. Renthal has been
monopolizing all of her time

1300
01:19:53,560 --> 01:19:55,280
with that damn ball.

1301
01:19:55,320 --> 01:19:56,120
Happy Easter, Janet.

1302
01:19:57,560 --> 01:20:00,560
Imagine, new people like that
giving that kind of party

1303
01:20:00,600 --> 01:20:02,200
and inviting all of us.

1304
01:20:02,240 --> 01:20:04,640
- [Janet] Laurance feels
we should play along.

1305
01:20:04,680 --> 01:20:05,960
- Why, may I ask.

1306
01:20:06,000 --> 01:20:08,240
- [Janet] Because they are
taking charge, darling.

1307
01:20:08,280 --> 01:20:10,000
People like us in the
social register

1308
01:20:10,040 --> 01:20:11,400
are practically extinct.

1309
01:20:11,440 --> 01:20:14,360
- Janet, my brother,
your husband,

1310
01:20:14,400 --> 01:20:16,400
is still very much in charge.

1311
01:20:16,440 --> 01:20:19,240
The Van Degan Bank, the
Van Degan Foundation,

1312
01:20:19,280 --> 01:20:22,880
the Van Degan Building,
they're all his.

1313
01:20:22,920 --> 01:20:24,960
We'll just see who's in charge.

1314
01:20:25,000 --> 01:20:28,320
I wouldn't dream of accepting
the Renthals invitation.

1315
01:20:28,360 --> 01:20:31,160
- We should talk about that,
Lil.

1316
01:20:32,360 --> 01:20:33,960
- Who is this coming to see me?

1317
01:20:34,000 --> 01:20:35,600
Who is it, who?

1318
01:20:35,640 --> 01:20:36,920
Yes, there she is.

1319
01:20:38,360 --> 01:20:41,920
- Baby Janet loves her
grandma, don't you, sweetheart?

1320
01:20:41,960 --> 01:20:43,280
Yes.

1321
01:20:43,320 --> 01:20:45,480
- And then Juanito
told me that--

1322
01:20:45,520 --> 01:20:48,480
- I didn't know you two
had gotten so close.

1323
01:20:48,520 --> 01:20:49,680
- I bought a
painting for Ormonde

1324
01:20:49,720 --> 01:20:52,440
at Hubie and Juanito's gallery.

1325
01:20:52,480 --> 01:20:55,480
- Nice picture, Hubie,
big colors.

1326
01:20:55,520 --> 01:20:56,760
- Thanks, Grandfather.

1327
01:20:56,800 --> 01:20:59,280
- Parker, you'll be sure
I want you to tell Gertie

1328
01:20:59,320 --> 01:21:01,800
how much we enjoyed the
crab tartlets.

1329
01:21:01,840 --> 01:21:03,720
- I absolutely agree
with Father.

1330
01:21:03,760 --> 01:21:05,760
Elias Renthal is the most
fascinating man

1331
01:21:05,800 --> 01:21:07,640
to come into the financial
community in years

1332
01:21:07,680 --> 01:21:09,360
and necessary to it.

1333
01:21:09,400 --> 01:21:10,480
- It's a surprise.

1334
01:21:10,520 --> 01:21:12,440
I didn't think you people
liked this type.

1335
01:21:12,480 --> 01:21:15,040
- Well, we have been
known to make exceptions

1336
01:21:15,080 --> 01:21:16,480
when they're forced upon us.

1337
01:21:28,560 --> 01:21:31,280
[glass clinking]

1338
01:21:33,040 --> 01:21:36,800
- To the newest member
of our family.

1339
01:21:36,840 --> 01:21:38,400
[thunder rumbling]

1340
01:21:38,440 --> 01:21:40,080
- Long way may it reign.

1341
01:21:40,120 --> 01:21:42,000
[Violet laughing]

1342
01:21:42,040 --> 01:21:44,800
[all chattering]

1343
01:22:00,840 --> 01:22:02,280
- Where's Juanito today?

1344
01:22:03,960 --> 01:22:06,120
- [Hubie] Oh, he's with
some friends.

1345
01:22:12,280 --> 01:22:13,920
- Hubie, when are you
gonna tell me?

1346
01:22:20,760 --> 01:22:25,080
- Well, I thought that
you'd already guessed

1347
01:22:25,120 --> 01:22:25,960
at your wedding.

1348
01:22:31,880 --> 01:22:33,280
- Well, what's gonna happen?

1349
01:22:36,640 --> 01:22:38,600
- What eventually
happens to all of us.

1350
01:22:41,520 --> 01:22:42,680
[Justine crying]

1351
01:22:42,720 --> 01:22:45,000
Justine, please don't,
please don't cry.

1352
01:22:45,040 --> 01:22:47,560
Justine, please, don't cry,

1353
01:22:47,600 --> 01:22:50,000
not with all this family here,
please.

1354
01:22:53,240 --> 01:22:55,080
- You are gonna tell Mother,
yes?

1355
01:23:02,400 --> 01:23:04,160
- As soon as everyone
leaves today.

1356
01:23:07,680 --> 01:23:09,040
- Do you want me to be with you?

1357
01:23:10,240 --> 01:23:12,240
- Do you realize that even
though I am your big brother,

1358
01:23:12,280 --> 01:23:15,920
you have always tried
to take care of me, hmm?

1359
01:23:18,280 --> 01:23:19,800
I think I can do this.

1360
01:23:21,600 --> 01:23:25,280
But thank you very much anyway.

1361
01:23:29,440 --> 01:23:32,000
[solemn music]

1362
01:23:35,720 --> 01:23:37,160
Please don't cry.

1363
01:23:50,960 --> 01:23:52,400
- Fun, wasn't it?

1364
01:23:52,440 --> 01:23:55,200
Now you know what I've had to
go through all these years.

1365
01:23:55,240 --> 01:23:57,280
- [Bernie] You didn't
pick your family.

1366
01:23:57,320 --> 01:23:58,640
- No, but you did.

1367
01:24:00,200 --> 01:24:02,720
Listen, it'll be different when
we have children, I promise.

1368
01:24:02,760 --> 01:24:05,240
They'll wanna come home
for the holidays.

1369
01:24:05,280 --> 01:24:07,880
- Justine, you know how I feel.

1370
01:24:07,920 --> 01:24:10,000
I don't even know if I
wanna have kids.

1371
01:24:10,040 --> 01:24:11,000
All that responsibility.

1372
01:24:12,200 --> 01:24:14,040
- You'll change your
mind, I know you will.

1373
01:24:15,360 --> 01:24:19,000
We won't let them even
meet my family. [chuckles]

1374
01:24:23,000 --> 01:24:24,640
- Wasn't this nice, Hubie?

1375
01:24:26,120 --> 01:24:29,040
Dinner on trays and just
the two of us by the fire.

1376
01:24:29,080 --> 01:24:30,320
- Yes, it's nice.

1377
01:24:31,320 --> 01:24:32,560
- Well, I bet you
couldn't imagine

1378
01:24:32,600 --> 01:24:34,520
your old mother could
rustle up such a good meal

1379
01:24:34,560 --> 01:24:36,680
with Gertie and Parker
out for the evening.

1380
01:24:39,040 --> 01:24:40,040
- [Hubie] Mother,
there's something

1381
01:24:40,080 --> 01:24:41,400
that I want to tell you.

1382
01:24:42,800 --> 01:24:47,240
- Hmm, would you like to
watch television or just talk?

1383
01:24:47,280 --> 01:24:48,840
- Just talk.
- Good.

1384
01:24:49,920 --> 01:24:51,520
Try some of Gertie's fig mousse.

1385
01:24:51,560 --> 01:24:54,400
I don't know how she does it,
something about egg whites.

1386
01:24:58,520 --> 01:25:00,560
- Mother, you can see
that I'm not well.

1387
01:25:00,600 --> 01:25:03,400
- I know they have to use
ripe figs and only white figs.

1388
01:25:03,440 --> 01:25:04,880
I know that's very important.

1389
01:25:05,760 --> 01:25:07,000
- I have AIDS, Mother.

1390
01:25:15,240 --> 01:25:17,520
- It's just that your
color is not good, Hubie.

1391
01:25:17,560 --> 01:25:18,720
You eat like a sparrow.

1392
01:25:21,400 --> 01:25:22,560
- I have lymphoma

1393
01:25:24,600 --> 01:25:25,960
and not much time.

1394
01:25:28,520 --> 01:25:30,960
- Hubie, I thought you and
I might take a little trip

1395
01:25:31,000 --> 01:25:33,120
to, say, St. Moritz
out of season.

1396
01:25:33,160 --> 01:25:35,840
It's just too beautiful for
words and it's so healthy.

1397
01:25:36,920 --> 01:25:38,520
- I might be dead by then.

1398
01:25:38,560 --> 01:25:39,760
- Oh, Hubie!

1399
01:25:41,920 --> 01:25:43,320
This talk is just so morbid.

1400
01:25:46,120 --> 01:25:48,600
I don't know how you can
do this to your family.

1401
01:25:50,680 --> 01:25:52,920
[laughing]

1402
01:25:54,680 --> 01:25:56,720
- Thank you for all your
support, Mother.

1403
01:26:00,680 --> 01:26:01,520
- Paris.

1404
01:26:03,280 --> 01:26:05,720
Paris, that's where we
should go, Hubie.

1405
01:26:05,760 --> 01:26:08,560
Wally Simpson left all her
money to the Pasteur Institute

1406
01:26:08,600 --> 01:26:09,760
and they do marvelous things.

1407
01:26:11,160 --> 01:26:13,120
- Don't you think that I
would have already gone there

1408
01:26:13,160 --> 01:26:14,240
to get help?

1409
01:26:16,040 --> 01:26:17,360
It's too late.

1410
01:26:20,480 --> 01:26:22,640
But that's not why you
suggested it, is it, Mother?

1411
01:26:24,040 --> 01:26:26,440
You just wanna hide me so
that your friends won't know

1412
01:26:26,480 --> 01:26:28,600
that your son is gay
and has AIDS.

1413
01:26:33,520 --> 01:26:34,840
- Hubie, please.

1414
01:26:36,520 --> 01:26:38,360
Nevel told me all about
that disease.

1415
01:26:39,560 --> 01:26:41,800
But I never thought people
like us got it.

1416
01:26:49,080 --> 01:26:51,240
[gasping]

1417
01:26:56,920 --> 01:26:59,920
[suspenseful music]

1418
01:27:50,760 --> 01:27:52,440
Order Malvern water,

1419
01:27:54,840 --> 01:27:56,080
Israeli melons.

1420
01:27:58,520 --> 01:28:00,760
Gertie, please forgive

1421
01:28:02,520 --> 01:28:04,800
the ghastly mess I made.

1422
01:28:07,040 --> 01:28:07,880
I tripped.

1423
01:28:10,360 --> 01:28:14,000
P.S. The fig mousse was yummy.

1424
01:28:58,800 --> 01:29:00,160
- [Woman] Yes, we're ready.

1425
01:29:00,200 --> 01:29:01,440
- [Marguerite] Uh, hi.

1426
01:29:01,480 --> 01:29:03,040
The Chardonnay by the
glasses are special today.

1427
01:29:03,080 --> 01:29:03,880
- [Woman] Uh-huh.

1428
01:29:03,920 --> 01:29:04,720
- [Gus] Hi, Marguerite.

1429
01:29:04,760 --> 01:29:05,600
I'm Gus Bailey.

1430
01:29:07,720 --> 01:29:08,680
- What do you want?

1431
01:29:08,720 --> 01:29:11,040
- [Woman] I like Chardonnay.

1432
01:29:14,480 --> 01:29:16,440
- Talk you out of
marrying Lefty Flint.

1433
01:29:17,560 --> 01:29:19,080
- That's none of your business.

1434
01:29:21,760 --> 01:29:23,600
- Flint is a murderer,
you know that.

1435
01:29:24,600 --> 01:29:25,720
He killed my daughter.

1436
01:29:28,280 --> 01:29:29,840
- He was drunk when he did that.

1437
01:29:30,600 --> 01:29:32,080
He doesn't drink anymore.

1438
01:29:32,120 --> 01:29:34,600
Now I think you'd better get
out of here and leave me alone.

1439
01:29:35,600 --> 01:29:38,640
- Look, here's my
telephone number.

1440
01:29:39,960 --> 01:29:42,520
If you're ever in any sort
of trouble, you call me.

1441
01:29:48,680 --> 01:29:52,360
[gentle instrumental music]

1442
01:29:59,280 --> 01:30:01,280
- [Peach] I'm over here!

1443
01:30:03,040 --> 01:30:03,880
- Hi.

1444
01:30:05,120 --> 01:30:05,960
- Oh, hi.

1445
01:30:12,680 --> 01:30:15,640
I bet that detective you
hired doesn't know about this.

1446
01:30:19,600 --> 01:30:21,200
It's from Flint.

1447
01:30:21,240 --> 01:30:24,160
When he does get out of prison,
he wants to come and see me.

1448
01:30:25,480 --> 01:30:27,960
Our daughter's killer
wants my forgiveness.

1449
01:30:29,960 --> 01:30:32,120
If I ever see that man
again, I'll kill him

1450
01:30:34,080 --> 01:30:35,840
with whatever
strength I have left.

1451
01:30:39,800 --> 01:30:42,720
- You were always stronger
than I was, Peach.

1452
01:30:42,760 --> 01:30:43,640
- So, you left.

1453
01:30:46,720 --> 01:30:48,160
- You asked for a divorce.

1454
01:30:48,200 --> 01:30:49,120
I made you unhappy.

1455
01:30:51,840 --> 01:30:53,600
- I'm not much for looking back.

1456
01:30:55,400 --> 01:30:57,280
Don't be too hard on yourself,
Gus.

1457
01:30:58,400 --> 01:31:00,320
You were a good father.

1458
01:31:05,280 --> 01:31:09,640
Wheel me back inside, will you,
I've got to get back to bed.

1459
01:31:09,680 --> 01:31:10,640
- If you don't mind, Peach,

1460
01:31:12,160 --> 01:31:15,120
I'd like to look for something
in the basement before I go.

1461
01:31:16,480 --> 01:31:18,320
- [Peach] What you want
to go in the basement for?

1462
01:31:18,360 --> 01:31:19,600
- [Gus] Some letters my
father sent me

1463
01:31:19,640 --> 01:31:20,560
when I was in the Army.

1464
01:31:22,040 --> 01:31:24,200
- We packed all your things
and sent them to your apartment

1465
01:31:24,240 --> 01:31:25,640
when we broke up.

1466
01:31:25,680 --> 01:31:27,240
- [Gus] Well, they must
have been left behind,

1467
01:31:27,280 --> 01:31:28,520
wound up down there.

1468
01:31:32,640 --> 01:31:35,640
[suspenseful music]

1469
01:32:09,320 --> 01:32:10,800
- Can I help you?

1470
01:32:10,840 --> 01:32:15,560
- Yeah, I have a little Russian
made weapon here from Korea.

1471
01:32:16,080 --> 01:32:16,720
- It's a beauty.

1472
01:32:16,760 --> 01:32:17,920
Is it for sale?

1473
01:32:17,960 --> 01:32:19,360
- No, I'd like to get
it into working order.

1474
01:32:19,400 --> 01:32:20,440
Can you do that?

1475
01:32:20,480 --> 01:32:21,880
- Sure, I'll need a deposit.

1476
01:32:23,600 --> 01:32:24,800
Your name?

1477
01:32:24,840 --> 01:32:26,600
- Mertens, Gene Mertens.

1478
01:32:36,880 --> 01:32:40,560
[gentle instrumental music]

1479
01:33:59,240 --> 01:34:01,800
[somber music]

1480
01:34:08,240 --> 01:34:11,000
[dramatic music]

1481
01:35:26,040 --> 01:35:28,800
[dramatic music]

1482
01:36:21,080 --> 01:36:24,040
[woman chuckling]

1483
01:36:24,080 --> 01:36:24,720
[clapping]

1484
01:36:24,760 --> 01:36:26,040
- Happy birthday, Peach.

1485
01:36:26,080 --> 01:36:28,560
Now let's see, how old
does this make you exactly?

1486
01:36:28,600 --> 01:36:29,840
- Still younger than you.

1487
01:36:29,880 --> 01:36:31,480
- Would you like me to
cut the cake now, señora?

1488
01:36:31,520 --> 01:36:32,600
- Yes, thank you, Maggie,
my dear.

1489
01:36:32,640 --> 01:36:34,240
We'll have some more
coffee as well.

1490
01:36:35,600 --> 01:36:37,880
That was very sweet of
you to remember, Gus.

1491
01:36:37,920 --> 01:36:39,240
You could've just sent a card.

1492
01:36:39,280 --> 01:36:41,400
- Well I didn't want
you to celebrate alone.

1493
01:36:41,440 --> 01:36:43,160
- You always were too
sentimental.

1494
01:36:43,200 --> 01:36:45,040
- That is probably true

1495
01:36:45,080 --> 01:36:46,840
but I'm glad there are
still a few occasions

1496
01:36:46,880 --> 01:36:48,200
left to celebrate.

1497
01:36:48,240 --> 01:36:50,360
- You make the best
of everything.

1498
01:36:50,400 --> 01:36:51,840
- Not everything.

1499
01:36:53,400 --> 01:36:56,200
Flint's lawyer got him
another parol hearing.

1500
01:36:57,400 --> 01:36:59,480
Should take place within
a couple of months.

1501
01:37:00,600 --> 01:37:02,120
- And he'll get out this time,
won't he?

1502
01:37:02,160 --> 01:37:04,920
- Yes and it will all be over

1503
01:37:04,960 --> 01:37:07,480
and justice will be satisfied.

1504
01:37:10,040 --> 01:37:11,760
- But that's not how we feel,

1505
01:37:11,800 --> 01:37:12,680
is it, Gus?

1506
01:37:15,280 --> 01:37:16,440
- Maybe we will, Peach.

1507
01:37:18,360 --> 01:37:19,200
Someday.

1508
01:37:26,400 --> 01:37:28,760
- [PA Announcer] Arriving
passenger Miles Miller,

1509
01:37:28,800 --> 01:37:31,280
please meet your party at
baggage carousel three.

1510
01:37:34,640 --> 01:37:36,000
- Is that you, Gus?

1511
01:37:36,040 --> 01:37:37,200
- Hello, Faye.

1512
01:37:38,800 --> 01:37:41,560
- Well leave it to you not
to make a big fuss over me.

1513
01:37:41,600 --> 01:37:42,480
- No, you look great.

1514
01:37:42,520 --> 01:37:43,640
- That's better.

1515
01:37:43,680 --> 01:37:45,560
But I'll just bet if I
hadn't spotted you,

1516
01:37:45,600 --> 01:37:46,920
you wouldn't have gotten
up to speak to me.

1517
01:37:46,960 --> 01:37:48,200
- Oh yes I would have.

1518
01:37:48,240 --> 01:37:50,560
I was waiting for the
usual hubbub to die down.

1519
01:37:50,600 --> 01:37:52,080
Headed for Europe or
New York like me?

1520
01:37:52,120 --> 01:37:53,160
- Big Apple, honey.

1521
01:37:53,200 --> 01:37:55,000
Gonna be shooting "Judas
Was A Redhead."

1522
01:37:55,040 --> 01:37:56,480
- Oh, that would make
a good movie.

1523
01:37:56,520 --> 01:38:00,040
- Gus, they don't make
movies of books anymore.

1524
01:38:00,080 --> 01:38:01,680
They make miniseries.

1525
01:38:01,720 --> 01:38:02,720
[chuckling]

1526
01:38:02,760 --> 01:38:03,120
Gus?

1527
01:38:03,160 --> 01:38:04,520
- Yeah.

1528
01:38:04,560 --> 01:38:06,360
- I was in Italy shooting
a picture during the trial.

1529
01:38:06,400 --> 01:38:08,000
You know I would've been there.

1530
01:38:10,360 --> 01:38:13,720
Gus, you've really kept
it in control.

1531
01:38:13,760 --> 01:38:15,960
I would've shot the
son of a bitch.

1532
01:38:23,240 --> 01:38:24,320
Gus?

1533
01:38:24,360 --> 01:38:26,120
You know the Elias Renthall's,
don't you?

1534
01:38:26,160 --> 01:38:27,560
- [Gus] Yes, I do.

1535
01:38:27,600 --> 01:38:29,360
- I know we're talking
big bucks here

1536
01:38:29,400 --> 01:38:30,960
but is he generous?

1537
01:38:31,000 --> 01:38:32,880
- I don't think he'd
finance a movie.

1538
01:38:33,960 --> 01:38:36,200
- Cathy, my best friend,

1539
01:38:36,240 --> 01:38:38,760
she's dying of the Big A.

1540
01:38:38,800 --> 01:38:41,840
Married a guy, had no idea
that he was into needles.

1541
01:38:41,880 --> 01:38:42,840
You know the story.

1542
01:38:43,760 --> 01:38:44,840
[sighing]

1543
01:38:44,880 --> 01:38:47,200
I'm trying to raise money
for the disease.

1544
01:38:47,240 --> 01:38:49,240
In fact, big bucks.

1545
01:38:49,280 --> 01:38:50,520
Think you could help me out?

1546
01:38:50,560 --> 01:38:51,640
- Faye, you're famous.

1547
01:38:51,680 --> 01:38:53,880
You don't need me to meet
Elias Renthall.

1548
01:38:53,920 --> 01:38:55,920
- He didn't return my
phone calls.

1549
01:38:55,960 --> 01:38:59,000
At least not after I told his
secretary what it was about.

1550
01:38:59,040 --> 01:39:00,040
I guess he's only into

1551
01:39:00,080 --> 01:39:03,240
the safe, social
advancement charities.

1552
01:39:03,280 --> 01:39:04,160
Look,

1553
01:39:04,200 --> 01:39:06,200
all I want is an introduction.

1554
01:39:06,240 --> 01:39:07,280
- I'll see what I can do.

1555
01:39:07,320 --> 01:39:08,400
- Terrific.

1556
01:39:08,440 --> 01:39:10,320
We get to New York, I'll
take you to lunch

1557
01:39:10,360 --> 01:39:11,720
or we'll do lunch.

1558
01:39:11,760 --> 01:39:13,600
- How about we both
just eat lunch?

1559
01:39:13,640 --> 01:39:16,160
[laughing]

1560
01:39:16,200 --> 01:39:17,600
It's for an important cause,
Elias.

1561
01:39:17,640 --> 01:39:19,640
Maybe not to some members
of the social set,

1562
01:39:19,680 --> 01:39:22,600
but for thousands of
people afflicted with AIDS.

1563
01:39:22,640 --> 01:39:23,840
- Okay, I'll send the
lady a check.

1564
01:39:23,880 --> 01:39:24,960
- Good.

1565
01:39:25,000 --> 01:39:26,280
- Better yet, I'll invite
her to the ball,

1566
01:39:26,320 --> 01:39:27,320
I'll give it to her there.

1567
01:39:27,360 --> 01:39:28,600
Ruby will love meeting
Faye Converse.

1568
01:39:28,640 --> 01:39:30,680
- Yeah and you'll enjoy
the good public relations.

1569
01:39:30,720 --> 01:39:32,400
- It's for a worthy cause,
right?

1570
01:39:32,440 --> 01:39:33,280
- Right.

1571
01:39:36,080 --> 01:39:37,520
- Ruby hates these things.

1572
01:39:38,600 --> 01:39:39,640
She ever tell you how we met?

1573
01:39:39,680 --> 01:39:40,440
- No.

1574
01:39:40,480 --> 01:39:42,280
- It was on an airplane.

1575
01:39:42,320 --> 01:39:44,680
Must've been the altitude
that got her to marry me.

1576
01:39:44,720 --> 01:39:45,560
- I doubt that.

1577
01:39:46,800 --> 01:39:47,840
- She likes you, Gus.

1578
01:39:50,080 --> 01:39:51,520
- Well, Ruby's a terrific girl.

1579
01:39:51,560 --> 01:39:53,000
You're a lucky man.

1580
01:39:53,040 --> 01:39:54,200
- Well that's what
people say about me

1581
01:39:54,240 --> 01:39:56,520
but I've had my
share of trouble.

1582
01:39:56,560 --> 01:39:57,760
So have you, I've heard.

1583
01:39:59,760 --> 01:40:00,760
I love my wife, Gus,

1584
01:40:02,000 --> 01:40:04,600
and I won't let anybody
hurt her ever again.

1585
01:40:06,040 --> 01:40:11,040
- I understand.

1586
01:40:13,440 --> 01:40:16,120
[phone ringing]

1587
01:40:20,840 --> 01:40:22,080
- Hello?

1588
01:40:22,120 --> 01:40:22,920
- Hi.

1589
01:40:22,960 --> 01:40:24,120
It's me.

1590
01:40:24,160 --> 01:40:25,520
What're you doing?

1591
01:40:25,560 --> 01:40:27,040
- [Young Woman]
Clipping coupons.

1592
01:40:27,080 --> 01:40:28,440
- Just like my Aunt Hester.

1593
01:40:29,360 --> 01:40:31,480
- So when are you coming home?

1594
01:40:31,520 --> 01:40:33,320
- Oh, I don't think I can
get out of here

1595
01:40:33,360 --> 01:40:35,120
at least until two or three.

1596
01:40:37,680 --> 01:40:40,600
- Not again, sweetheart, that's
the third time this week.

1597
01:40:41,440 --> 01:40:43,160
- It can't be helped.

1598
01:40:43,200 --> 01:40:44,960
Don't wait up for me.

1599
01:40:45,000 --> 01:40:46,560
- Okay.

1600
01:40:46,600 --> 01:40:47,440
I love you.

1601
01:40:48,720 --> 01:40:49,560
- Same here.

1602
01:40:56,200 --> 01:40:57,480
[somber music]

1603
01:40:57,520 --> 01:40:58,920
- Feeling guilty?

1604
01:41:00,000 --> 01:41:00,840
- [Man] Shut up.

1605
01:41:02,760 --> 01:41:05,120
- I liked you better when
you were single.

1606
01:41:05,160 --> 01:41:06,480
At least then you didn't
pretend to care

1607
01:41:06,520 --> 01:41:08,760
about anybody but yourself.

1608
01:41:11,800 --> 01:41:14,360
- I care about Justine.

1609
01:41:14,400 --> 01:41:15,240
- Sure you do.

1610
01:41:16,440 --> 01:41:18,760
That's why you're here.

1611
01:41:18,800 --> 01:41:21,080
- And that's why I'm leaving.

1612
01:41:21,120 --> 01:41:23,680
[somber music]

1613
01:41:33,600 --> 01:41:34,520
- It's amazing.

1614
01:41:34,560 --> 01:41:36,240
Everyone we've
invited is coming,

1615
01:41:36,280 --> 01:41:38,200
including your mother.
[Justine laughing]

1616
01:41:38,240 --> 01:41:40,120
- Well I knew she'd
accept eventually.

1617
01:41:40,160 --> 01:41:41,520
Mother just wouldn't be content

1618
01:41:41,560 --> 01:41:43,760
having to hear about your
ball of anointed clearances.

1619
01:41:43,800 --> 01:41:45,120
[laughing]

1620
01:41:45,160 --> 01:41:47,360
- I'll let you in on a
little secret.

1621
01:41:47,400 --> 01:41:48,720
First Lady is coming.

1622
01:41:48,760 --> 01:41:49,720
- The First Lady?

1623
01:41:49,760 --> 01:41:50,680
How wonderful.

1624
01:41:50,720 --> 01:41:52,080
How on Earth, Ruby?

1625
01:41:52,120 --> 01:41:54,320
- Elias has been friends
with the President for years.

1626
01:41:54,360 --> 01:41:57,040
They used to do business
together when he was governor.

1627
01:41:57,080 --> 01:41:58,280
To be perfectly honest,

1628
01:41:58,320 --> 01:42:00,320
I'm happier about you
and Bernie being there.

1629
01:42:00,360 --> 01:42:01,760
I'm gonna need the
moral support.

1630
01:42:01,800 --> 01:42:03,280
[chuckling]

1631
01:42:03,320 --> 01:42:04,680
- I just hope Bernie
doesn't have to work

1632
01:42:04,720 --> 01:42:05,720
late again that night.

1633
01:42:05,760 --> 01:42:06,920
He's been doing a lot of
that these days.

1634
01:42:06,960 --> 01:42:08,120
- Oh, so is Elias.

1635
01:42:08,160 --> 01:42:09,800
But he says, "Somebody
has to earn the rent."

1636
01:42:09,840 --> 01:42:11,440
- Oh, I suppose.

1637
01:42:11,480 --> 01:42:12,280
It's just,

1638
01:42:13,200 --> 01:42:14,680
well, I just can't help feeling

1639
01:42:14,720 --> 01:42:16,160
that Bernie's keeping
something from me.

1640
01:42:16,200 --> 01:42:18,600
That there's some deep dark
secret he's afraid to tell me.

1641
01:42:19,720 --> 01:42:21,200
I always thought when you
married someone

1642
01:42:21,240 --> 01:42:23,680
there wouldn't be a need for
secrets between the two of you,

1643
01:42:23,720 --> 01:42:25,200
no matter what you'd done,

1644
01:42:25,240 --> 01:42:28,240
it wouldn't make any difference
to the person who loved you.

1645
01:42:29,920 --> 01:42:32,360
I just wished Bernie loved
me enough to trust me.

1646
01:42:33,680 --> 01:42:36,160
- Well he does love you,
that's what's important.

1647
01:42:38,560 --> 01:42:39,400
Right?

1648
01:42:40,400 --> 01:42:43,200
[pleasant music]

1649
01:42:43,240 --> 01:42:45,440
- [Worker] Watch behind you!

1650
01:42:45,480 --> 01:42:46,920
Oh, that's good.

1651
01:42:49,240 --> 01:42:50,040
- Be careful.

1652
01:42:50,080 --> 01:42:51,080
If you break any of those

1653
01:42:51,120 --> 01:42:52,800
I'll have you all
dipped in cement.

1654
01:42:52,840 --> 01:42:53,920
Mrs. Renthall,

1655
01:42:53,960 --> 01:42:56,200
isn't it just fabulous
what I have done?

1656
01:42:56,240 --> 01:42:58,200
Your ball will be magnificent.

1657
01:42:58,240 --> 01:42:59,560
Simply magical.

1658
01:42:59,600 --> 01:43:02,800
- Yes, I know, you've done
a wonderful job, Lorenza.

1659
01:43:02,840 --> 01:43:03,840
Would you excuse me?

1660
01:43:10,920 --> 01:43:13,720
- [Elias] Sounds like World
War III going on down there.

1661
01:43:13,760 --> 01:43:15,520
- But Lorenza's
winning the battle.

1662
01:43:19,480 --> 01:43:21,760
Elias, there's something
I wanna tell you about.

1663
01:43:21,800 --> 01:43:23,880
- Something you lied
to me about.

1664
01:43:23,920 --> 01:43:25,920
Like about how much this
is really costing me.

1665
01:43:25,960 --> 01:43:27,720
[chuckling]

1666
01:43:27,760 --> 01:43:30,560
- I've never lied to you
about anything, ever.

1667
01:43:30,600 --> 01:43:31,440
- I know that.

1668
01:43:32,640 --> 01:43:34,760
- Sometimes I haven't told
you everything.

1669
01:43:35,640 --> 01:43:37,080
But I've never lied to you.

1670
01:43:38,640 --> 01:43:41,520
I just don't think there should
be any secrets between us.

1671
01:43:43,640 --> 01:43:46,200
I wanna tell you about
someone I used to know.

1672
01:43:46,240 --> 01:43:48,640
- If that someone is
Lefty Flint,

1673
01:43:48,680 --> 01:43:50,800
I know all about him
and it doesn't matter.

1674
01:43:52,280 --> 01:43:53,280
- How do you know?

1675
01:43:54,040 --> 01:43:55,480
- Well when you took so
long in deciding

1676
01:43:55,520 --> 01:43:56,840
whether you wanted to
marry me or not,

1677
01:43:56,880 --> 01:43:58,240
I figured there must
be another guy,

1678
01:43:58,280 --> 01:43:59,920
so I checked out my competition.

1679
01:44:02,240 --> 01:44:03,400
- You didn't have any.

1680
01:44:03,440 --> 01:44:05,200
- What did I know?

1681
01:44:05,240 --> 01:44:07,600
I just couldn't understand how
an incredible woman like you

1682
01:44:07,640 --> 01:44:09,920
was still unattached and
even remotely interested

1683
01:44:09,960 --> 01:44:10,800
in a guy like me.

1684
01:44:10,840 --> 01:44:12,520
- Oh, more than remotely.

1685
01:44:13,800 --> 01:44:17,720
You are the kindest,
most gentle loving man

1686
01:44:17,760 --> 01:44:18,840
I have ever known.

1687
01:44:20,640 --> 01:44:22,840
- You mean you didn't
marry me for my money?

1688
01:44:23,880 --> 01:44:24,720
- Money?

1689
01:44:26,000 --> 01:44:27,640
You didn't tell me
you had money.

1690
01:44:28,880 --> 01:44:31,160
[laughing]

1691
01:44:35,120 --> 01:44:37,720
- I'm afraid I can't get to
your file at the moment, Gus.

1692
01:44:37,760 --> 01:44:40,000
But I'll make the necessary
adjustment in your will,

1693
01:44:40,040 --> 01:44:42,160
eliminating the bequest
to your daughter

1694
01:44:42,200 --> 01:44:44,160
and leaving everything
to your ex-wife.

1695
01:44:45,240 --> 01:44:47,920
[ominous music]

1696
01:44:52,480 --> 01:44:53,880
- Bea, who is that man?

1697
01:44:55,760 --> 01:44:57,800
- Listen, Gus, you can come
back when I've prepared it

1698
01:44:57,840 --> 01:44:58,800
and we'll have it witnessed.

1699
01:44:58,840 --> 01:44:59,760
- What is going on here?

1700
01:44:59,800 --> 01:45:01,160
Are those the police?

1701
01:45:01,200 --> 01:45:02,160
- Federal ones.

1702
01:45:03,600 --> 01:45:05,800
And that man is one of our
junior lawyers, Byron Macumber.

1703
01:45:05,840 --> 01:45:06,360
- Oh?

1704
01:45:06,400 --> 01:45:07,880
What's he done?

1705
01:45:07,920 --> 01:45:11,880
- Something about an account
in a Swiss bank in the Bahamas.

1706
01:45:11,920 --> 01:45:14,160
Look for a very big
head to roll.

1707
01:45:14,200 --> 01:45:15,080
- [Gus] At Weldon and
Stanchfield?

1708
01:45:15,120 --> 01:45:17,160
- Oh goodness, no, not here.

1709
01:45:17,200 --> 01:45:20,360
Elias Renthall, inside trading.

1710
01:45:21,640 --> 01:45:24,280
- This is Gus Bailey,
is Mrs. Renthall there?

1711
01:45:25,480 --> 01:45:26,760
No.

1712
01:45:26,800 --> 01:45:27,920
When would she be back?

1713
01:45:29,840 --> 01:45:31,400
No, no, no, no message.

1714
01:45:33,160 --> 01:45:34,000
Thank you.

1715
01:45:40,480 --> 01:45:41,560
- Hello?

1716
01:45:41,600 --> 01:45:42,960
- Hi, it's me.

1717
01:45:43,000 --> 01:45:44,280
I know this might upset you

1718
01:45:44,320 --> 01:45:46,800
but is it too late to
cancel the Renthall's party?

1719
01:45:48,440 --> 01:45:50,680
- You have to work late
again tonight?

1720
01:45:50,720 --> 01:45:52,960
- [Bernie] No, I just don't
feel like going to a party.

1721
01:45:54,520 --> 01:45:56,720
- Well, why don't we just
go to the Renthall dinner

1722
01:45:56,760 --> 01:45:59,240
and leave before the
ball starts?

1723
01:45:59,280 --> 01:46:00,600
- I really don't want to,
Justine.

1724
01:46:02,040 --> 01:46:04,000
I thought maybe we could go
out, get something to eat.

1725
01:46:04,040 --> 01:46:05,720
Spend some time
together talking,

1726
01:46:05,760 --> 01:46:06,600
just you and me.

1727
01:46:08,760 --> 01:46:11,600
- I promised Ruby but
I'll call and explain.

1728
01:46:13,320 --> 01:46:15,800
Where do you wanna go,
O'Rourke's?

1729
01:46:15,840 --> 01:46:16,800
- That's too noisy.

1730
01:46:18,240 --> 01:46:19,600
- Well,

1731
01:46:19,640 --> 01:46:21,000
how about Clarence's?

1732
01:46:21,040 --> 01:46:22,840
I know you hate the place
but it'll be empty tonight.

1733
01:46:22,880 --> 01:46:25,760
Everybody that goes there
will be at the Renthall's.

1734
01:46:25,800 --> 01:46:26,920
- That's fine.

1735
01:46:26,960 --> 01:46:28,800
I'll meet you in an hour.

1736
01:46:28,840 --> 01:46:30,240
- Okay.

1737
01:46:30,280 --> 01:46:31,800
I love you.

1738
01:46:31,840 --> 01:46:33,080
- See you in a little while.

1739
01:46:33,120 --> 01:46:33,960
Bye.

1740
01:46:35,120 --> 01:46:37,800
[phone buzzing]

1741
01:46:41,760 --> 01:46:44,560
[crowd commotion]

1742
01:46:46,160 --> 01:46:49,080
[cameras snapping]

1743
01:46:57,920 --> 01:47:00,560
- Dinner for 30 and
everything matches.

1744
01:47:01,880 --> 01:47:02,680
And monogram.

1745
01:47:02,720 --> 01:47:04,520
- R is for Renthall, right?

1746
01:47:04,560 --> 01:47:05,920
Wrong, R is for Rothschild.

1747
01:47:05,960 --> 01:47:07,640
They bought it at the
estate sale.

1748
01:47:09,560 --> 01:47:12,560
[people chattering]

1749
01:47:15,440 --> 01:47:17,920
- Oh, Lil, I thought you
were gonna turn this down.

1750
01:47:17,960 --> 01:47:20,160
- Oh, I just came to see
the furniture.

1751
01:47:20,200 --> 01:47:21,720
Cora told me she bought
certain pieces

1752
01:47:21,760 --> 01:47:24,040
from a palace in Yugoslavia.

1753
01:47:24,080 --> 01:47:25,320
- Hello, Gus.

1754
01:47:25,360 --> 01:47:27,280
Mrs. Altemus, I'm so
happy that you came.

1755
01:47:27,320 --> 01:47:29,120
What a disappointment
that Justine

1756
01:47:29,160 --> 01:47:30,640
had to cancel at the
last minute.

1757
01:47:30,680 --> 01:47:31,600
- Cancel?

1758
01:47:31,640 --> 01:47:33,640
She had an appointment Dodo.

1759
01:47:33,680 --> 01:47:35,800
Well, I'm certain she
had her reasons.

1760
01:47:35,840 --> 01:47:37,320
- Do you have a minute?
We have to talk.

1761
01:47:37,360 --> 01:47:38,080
- Yes, of course.

1762
01:47:38,120 --> 01:47:39,080
Excuse us.

1763
01:47:39,120 --> 01:47:40,480
- [Woman] Hello, Faye!

1764
01:47:40,520 --> 01:47:41,720
- Oh, here's Faye Converse.

1765
01:47:41,760 --> 01:47:42,800
Would you excuse me?

1766
01:47:46,840 --> 01:47:48,160
Excuse me.

1767
01:47:48,200 --> 01:47:49,960
- Sorry I'm late

1768
01:47:50,000 --> 01:47:51,760
and thanks again for
doing this tonight.

1769
01:47:51,800 --> 01:47:53,160
- Oh, no thanks necessary.

1770
01:47:53,200 --> 01:47:54,560
It's a thrill to meet you

1771
01:47:54,600 --> 01:47:58,000
and an honor to contribute
to such a worthwhile cause.

1772
01:47:58,040 --> 01:47:59,640
Come, I'll show you
to your seat.

1773
01:47:59,680 --> 01:48:00,840
You'll be sitting next to Gus.

1774
01:48:00,880 --> 01:48:02,520
- Oh, I love Gus.

1775
01:48:02,560 --> 01:48:04,240
He's the reason I'm
here tonight.

1776
01:48:08,800 --> 01:48:10,480
- Well I have missed you.

1777
01:48:14,400 --> 01:48:15,200
What's wrong?

1778
01:48:15,240 --> 01:48:16,080
Tell me.

1779
01:48:17,400 --> 01:48:19,600
- I guess there's never
an easy way to say this.

1780
01:48:22,720 --> 01:48:24,160
- What is it, your work?

1781
01:48:24,200 --> 01:48:25,800
You're being transferred
to LA, aren't you?

1782
01:48:25,840 --> 01:48:27,240
- No.

1783
01:48:27,280 --> 01:48:28,200
I almost wish I was.

1784
01:48:28,240 --> 01:48:29,640
That might make this easier.

1785
01:48:33,040 --> 01:48:34,080
I...

1786
01:48:37,040 --> 01:48:38,360
I want a divorce.

1787
01:48:42,720 --> 01:48:43,520
- Why?

1788
01:48:44,880 --> 01:48:48,360
- Because you expect me
to be a faithful husband

1789
01:48:48,400 --> 01:48:49,200
and I'm not.

1790
01:48:50,600 --> 01:48:51,520
I never will be.

1791
01:48:54,440 --> 01:48:55,760
- Is there another woman?

1792
01:48:55,800 --> 01:48:57,640
- There will always be
another woman.

1793
01:48:58,840 --> 01:49:00,320
And that's the problem.

1794
01:49:02,440 --> 01:49:04,680
It's the way I've always been.

1795
01:49:07,400 --> 01:49:08,440
- Well is it me?

1796
01:49:08,480 --> 01:49:10,680
Have I done something wrong?

1797
01:49:10,720 --> 01:49:13,160
- No, no, you haven't done
anything wrong,

1798
01:49:13,200 --> 01:49:14,560
except maybe marry me.

1799
01:49:21,680 --> 01:49:23,040
I'm sorry if I hurt you.

1800
01:49:23,960 --> 01:49:25,640
I never meant to do that.

1801
01:49:27,800 --> 01:49:30,480
- And I never thought you would.

1802
01:49:37,760 --> 01:49:40,520
[dramatic music]

1803
01:49:54,960 --> 01:49:57,400
[sobbing]

1804
01:49:57,440 --> 01:49:59,960
[eerie music]

1805
01:50:12,840 --> 01:50:14,920
[crying]

1806
01:50:21,120 --> 01:50:23,360
[somber music]

1807
01:50:23,400 --> 01:50:26,160
[fire crackling]

1808
01:50:31,760 --> 01:50:33,960
- Are you sure you're up
to making dinner?

1809
01:50:34,000 --> 01:50:35,760
- I have to do things.

1810
01:50:38,280 --> 01:50:41,080
- You know, I've always
hated these chairs.

1811
01:50:41,120 --> 01:50:43,920
- Well then you can sell
them after I'm gone.

1812
01:50:43,960 --> 01:50:45,360
Drive mother insane.

1813
01:50:49,000 --> 01:50:50,160
Would you like a drink?

1814
01:50:51,840 --> 01:50:52,880
- I'd like some wine.

1815
01:50:56,800 --> 01:50:58,320
- Ugh.

1816
01:50:58,360 --> 01:50:59,920
I can do it, I have
to do things!

1817
01:50:59,960 --> 01:51:00,960
- I know.

1818
01:51:01,840 --> 01:51:02,960
But let me.

1819
01:51:03,000 --> 01:51:04,880
You see to the food,
I'll be bartender.

1820
01:51:15,280 --> 01:51:17,920
[ominous music]

1821
01:51:19,240 --> 01:51:20,800
- Juanito!

1822
01:51:20,840 --> 01:51:22,280
- Hubey.

1823
01:51:22,320 --> 01:51:24,520
- I think you better
get me to the hospital.

1824
01:51:25,800 --> 01:51:27,680
- Should we call your
mother or Justine?

1825
01:51:27,720 --> 01:51:30,400
- No, they're both at the
Renthall ball.

1826
01:51:30,440 --> 01:51:33,200
You wouldn't be able to
reach either of them.

1827
01:51:33,240 --> 01:51:35,280
- Who needs them anyway?

1828
01:51:35,320 --> 01:51:36,600
I'll take care of you.

1829
01:51:36,640 --> 01:51:37,600
Just like always.

1830
01:51:41,280 --> 01:51:42,200
Just like always,

1831
01:51:43,200 --> 01:51:47,760
I'll take care of you.

1832
01:51:47,800 --> 01:51:50,800
[people chattering]

1833
01:51:53,200 --> 01:51:53,960
[glass shattering]

1834
01:51:54,000 --> 01:51:55,120
- So sorry, darling.

1835
01:51:55,160 --> 01:51:57,680
- Oh, don't give it
another thought, no.

1836
01:51:57,720 --> 01:51:59,680
Only give me an excuse
to change into

1837
01:51:59,720 --> 01:52:02,240
another one of your
marvelous creations.

1838
01:52:02,280 --> 01:52:03,120
Excuse me.

1839
01:52:05,960 --> 01:52:07,520
- Splendid woman.

1840
01:52:07,560 --> 01:52:10,520
The Duchess couldn't
have handled that better.

1841
01:52:10,560 --> 01:52:12,800
- Gus, who the hell are
these people?

1842
01:52:14,040 --> 01:52:15,760
- Well, seated next to
you is Lord Biedermeyer,

1843
01:52:15,800 --> 01:52:17,120
the publisher.

1844
01:52:17,160 --> 01:52:20,080
- Oh, Lucerne, darling.

1845
01:52:20,120 --> 01:52:21,040
How are you?

1846
01:52:21,080 --> 01:52:21,880
- Faye.

1847
01:52:21,920 --> 01:52:23,280
- I didn't see you.

1848
01:52:23,320 --> 01:52:24,760
Probably thinks I'm blind drunk.

1849
01:52:25,880 --> 01:52:28,560
- And to his left is Mrs.
Laura Van Degan.

1850
01:52:28,600 --> 01:52:30,560
To her left is the
Earl of Castoria.

1851
01:52:31,800 --> 01:52:34,360
- Oh my God, he looks
like my third husband.

1852
01:52:35,200 --> 01:52:36,320
After the wake.

1853
01:52:36,360 --> 01:52:38,640
[laughing]

1854
01:52:40,080 --> 01:52:43,720
- And need I say any more
about this great star's career

1855
01:52:43,760 --> 01:52:46,200
and the 40 pictures
that she's made?

1856
01:52:46,240 --> 01:52:48,240
- 60, darling, not 40.

1857
01:52:48,280 --> 01:52:49,760
[laughing]

1858
01:52:49,800 --> 01:52:51,080
- Well, whatever, anyway.

1859
01:52:51,120 --> 01:52:51,960
Faye,

1860
01:52:52,000 --> 01:52:54,280
here's the check
towards the cure

1861
01:52:54,320 --> 01:52:55,840
for the pestilence

1862
01:52:55,880 --> 01:52:59,160
that is dwindling the ranks
of the artistic community.

1863
01:52:59,200 --> 01:53:00,080
- Thank you.

1864
01:53:00,120 --> 01:53:02,560
[applauding]

1865
01:53:04,000 --> 01:53:06,000
Oh my God.

1866
01:53:06,040 --> 01:53:08,600
Two million dollars.

1867
01:53:08,640 --> 01:53:09,480
Oh, Elias!

1868
01:53:11,960 --> 01:53:16,600
Thank you!
[applauding]

1869
01:53:16,640 --> 01:53:19,080
[applauding]

1870
01:53:20,240 --> 01:53:21,080
Thank you.

1871
01:53:22,080 --> 01:53:22,880
Whoa.

1872
01:53:23,920 --> 01:53:24,720
Friends,

1873
01:53:25,600 --> 01:53:27,960
we are an army

1874
01:53:28,000 --> 01:53:33,040
fighting an enemy that
has no allies.

1875
01:53:33,480 --> 01:53:34,440
However,

1876
01:53:35,920 --> 01:53:38,840
every army must enlist support,

1877
01:53:38,880 --> 01:53:42,000
financial and otherwise.

1878
01:53:42,040 --> 01:53:44,720
The Renthall's generosity

1879
01:53:44,760 --> 01:53:46,240
will aid in the struggle

1880
01:53:46,280 --> 01:53:49,320
in which we must all bear arms.

1881
01:53:49,360 --> 01:53:54,000
Therefore I shall dedicate the
rest of my life to this cause

1882
01:53:55,040 --> 01:53:57,320
and I shall forever

1883
01:53:57,360 --> 01:54:00,440
be indebted to his
charitable gentlemen,

1884
01:54:00,480 --> 01:54:03,760
this extraordinary humanitarian.

1885
01:54:03,800 --> 01:54:06,800
Oh, ladies and gentlemen,
Elias Renthall.

1886
01:54:06,840 --> 01:54:09,280
[applauding]

1887
01:54:21,640 --> 01:54:24,280
[ominous music]

1888
01:54:27,640 --> 01:54:28,520
- [Hubert] I can walk in.

1889
01:54:28,560 --> 01:54:29,760
Let me walk in.

1890
01:54:34,160 --> 01:54:36,240
- [Juanito] Don't worry, Hubey.

1891
01:54:36,280 --> 01:54:37,120
I'm with you.

1892
01:54:38,120 --> 01:54:39,480
Everything's gonna be fine.

1893
01:54:42,080 --> 01:54:45,920
[pleasant instrumental music]

1894
01:54:50,800 --> 01:54:53,480
- There can't be a tulip
left in all of Holland.

1895
01:54:53,520 --> 01:54:56,120
- These new people spend
more on flowers

1896
01:54:56,160 --> 01:54:59,080
than we used to
inherit in my day.

1897
01:54:59,120 --> 01:55:02,760
And all they want in return
is to be accepted by us.

1898
01:55:02,800 --> 01:55:04,200
- That'll never happen.

1899
01:55:04,240 --> 01:55:05,520
- Oh, it will.

1900
01:55:05,560 --> 01:55:07,040
Times change.

1901
01:55:07,080 --> 01:55:10,080
- Why don't we retire
upstairs for a cigar?

1902
01:55:10,120 --> 01:55:12,120
There's an elevator we can use.

1903
01:55:14,440 --> 01:55:16,440
- It will never happen.

1904
01:55:16,480 --> 01:55:19,400
- Look around, Lily, it
has happened.

1905
01:55:19,440 --> 01:55:22,320
[pleasant instrumental music]

1906
01:55:22,360 --> 01:55:24,800
[applauding]

1907
01:55:42,640 --> 01:55:44,840
- Isn't it magnificent?

1908
01:55:44,880 --> 01:55:48,080
Of course, they could have
never done it without me.

1909
01:55:48,120 --> 01:55:50,560
- You mean, without me, darling.

1910
01:55:51,960 --> 01:55:55,360
- I'd like nothing better
than to publish a biography

1911
01:55:55,400 --> 01:55:56,960
of the Van Degan family.

1912
01:55:57,000 --> 01:55:58,480
- Damn good cigar.

1913
01:55:58,520 --> 01:56:00,480
- After all, Ormonde,

1914
01:56:00,520 --> 01:56:04,400
your roots in this city
and this nation

1915
01:56:04,440 --> 01:56:07,400
can not be matched by
any other family.

1916
01:56:07,440 --> 01:56:08,760
- Good cigar.

1917
01:56:10,200 --> 01:56:12,920
- You're looking
particularly well these days.

1918
01:56:16,840 --> 01:56:19,200
- Nothing like a good cigar.

1919
01:56:19,240 --> 01:56:21,480
[coughing]

1920
01:56:24,400 --> 01:56:26,200
- Your father was governor,

1921
01:56:26,240 --> 01:56:28,200
you uncle, ambassador to France.

1922
01:56:28,240 --> 01:56:31,200
I think it's time for
important work.

1923
01:56:31,240 --> 01:56:35,840
Yes, yes indeed.
[coughing]

1924
01:56:47,200 --> 01:56:48,320
[applauding]

1925
01:56:48,360 --> 01:56:49,280
- Ruby?

1926
01:56:49,320 --> 01:56:50,480
Ruby, I have to talk to you.

1927
01:56:50,520 --> 01:56:51,920
- Yes, I know but can it wait,
Gus.

1928
01:56:51,960 --> 01:56:53,280
I gotta go change for
the First Lady.

1929
01:56:53,320 --> 01:56:54,400
- I didn't know she was coming.

1930
01:56:54,440 --> 01:56:55,400
- Yes, any minute.

1931
01:56:55,440 --> 01:56:57,320
We'll talk later, I promise.

1932
01:57:03,200 --> 01:57:05,880
[ominous music]

1933
01:57:05,920 --> 01:57:08,200
- I'll pick up the rest of
my stuff later in the week.

1934
01:57:08,240 --> 01:57:09,560
I'll call first.

1935
01:57:11,320 --> 01:57:12,560
I'm sorry, Justine.

1936
01:57:12,600 --> 01:57:14,960
- Stop staying you're sorry.

1937
01:57:15,880 --> 01:57:17,080
[menacing music]

1938
01:57:17,120 --> 01:57:18,760
Stop saying you're sorry!

1939
01:57:18,800 --> 01:57:19,800
Stop saying!

1940
01:57:26,680 --> 01:57:28,240
- I still want you.

1941
01:57:29,480 --> 01:57:32,160
[ominous music]

1942
01:57:56,560 --> 01:58:00,240
[upbeat instrumental music]

1943
01:58:19,240 --> 01:58:21,920
- Well, Lil, how about a dance?

1944
01:58:21,960 --> 01:58:24,160
- How kind, Mr. Renthall.

1945
01:58:24,200 --> 01:58:26,880
- I must have a word with you,
Elias.

1946
01:58:26,920 --> 01:58:30,480
- Not until I've convinced
Lil to drop the formalities.

1947
01:58:30,520 --> 01:58:34,200
[upbeat instrumental music]

1948
01:58:52,720 --> 01:58:53,560
- Bye, Justine.

1949
01:59:04,320 --> 01:59:05,160
- Goodbye.

1950
01:59:10,200 --> 01:59:13,720
[upbeat instrumental music]

1951
01:59:13,760 --> 01:59:15,680
- Elias, it's been so gay.

1952
01:59:15,720 --> 01:59:17,320
- I don't think that's quite
the right word anymore.

1953
01:59:17,360 --> 01:59:19,920
- No, it's a marvelous word

1954
01:59:19,960 --> 01:59:22,080
and I simply refuse
to give it up.

1955
01:59:22,120 --> 01:59:25,680
My friends all know that I
mean it in the old fashion way.

1956
01:59:25,720 --> 01:59:27,880
[laughing]

1957
01:59:27,920 --> 01:59:30,360
[applauding]

1958
01:59:44,080 --> 01:59:45,120
- He's dead.

1959
01:59:45,160 --> 01:59:47,040
- Oh, this is gonna
ruin Ruby's party.

1960
01:59:47,080 --> 01:59:48,960
- It'll certainly put a
damper on it.

1961
01:59:49,000 --> 01:59:50,120
- Did you tell anyone?

1962
01:59:50,160 --> 01:59:51,240
- Heavens no.

1963
01:59:51,280 --> 01:59:53,640
- All right, how about we
don't say a word

1964
01:59:53,680 --> 01:59:55,760
until after the first
lady leaves,

1965
01:59:55,800 --> 01:59:57,000
then we call an ambulance,

1966
01:59:57,040 --> 01:59:59,120
get him back down on the
freight elevator.

1967
02:00:01,360 --> 02:00:04,000
He was an old man, it's not
like it's a big tragedy.

1968
02:00:06,040 --> 02:00:06,880
- All right.

1969
02:00:09,400 --> 02:00:12,280
[triumphant music]

1970
02:00:14,000 --> 02:00:16,440
[applauding]

1971
02:00:18,760 --> 02:00:22,960
- [Woman] Just imagine the
First Lady at the Renthall's.

1972
02:00:23,000 --> 02:00:24,160
So lovely.

1973
02:00:24,200 --> 02:00:25,760
- [Man] Just wait,
there's more to come.

1974
02:00:25,800 --> 02:00:28,240
- I'll let you in on a
little secret.

1975
02:00:28,280 --> 02:00:31,240
I told Ruby to allow 45
minutes for waltzing.

1976
02:00:31,280 --> 02:00:33,360
- I've got a better one.

1977
02:00:33,400 --> 02:00:36,880
I heard that she was warn
not to come here tonight.

1978
02:00:36,920 --> 02:00:39,920
Apparently Elias is under
investigation by the SCC

1979
02:00:39,960 --> 02:00:41,440
for insider trading.

1980
02:00:41,480 --> 02:00:42,160
- Nonsense.

1981
02:00:42,200 --> 02:00:43,120
- Exactly what I said.

1982
02:00:43,160 --> 02:00:44,720
Even I wouldn't
print that rumor.

1983
02:00:44,760 --> 02:00:48,560
[pleasant instrumental music]

1984
02:00:58,440 --> 02:00:59,440
- Laurance!

1985
02:00:59,480 --> 02:01:00,720
Laurance, we're
looking for father.

1986
02:01:00,760 --> 02:01:02,880
He came up here over
an hour ago.

1987
02:01:02,920 --> 02:01:03,880
Now what's in that room?

1988
02:01:03,920 --> 02:01:06,120
- Edward the
Seventh's pool table.

1989
02:01:06,160 --> 02:01:07,520
It's off limits.

1990
02:01:07,560 --> 02:01:09,640
Elias doesn't want the
old felt stained.

1991
02:01:11,480 --> 02:01:13,160
- It's locked but maybe
he's in there.

1992
02:01:13,200 --> 02:01:15,000
Old felt wouldn't mean
a thing to him.

1993
02:01:15,040 --> 02:01:17,080
- Look through the key hole,
Dodo.

1994
02:01:19,480 --> 02:01:21,440
- Oh yes, he's asleep.

1995
02:01:21,480 --> 02:01:22,680
Right on the pool table.

1996
02:01:22,720 --> 02:01:23,880
It's too sweet.

1997
02:01:25,560 --> 02:01:28,440
- Well, I better get
back downstairs.

1998
02:01:28,480 --> 02:01:30,400
Janet will be
wondering where I am.

1999
02:01:31,560 --> 02:01:32,880
- What about father?

2000
02:01:34,680 --> 02:01:35,520
- Let him sleep.

2001
02:01:37,520 --> 02:01:39,600
- Well, Dodo, push the door!

2002
02:01:41,200 --> 02:01:44,320
Or get one of the
servants to open it.

2003
02:01:44,360 --> 02:01:46,680
Maybe there's something wrong.

2004
02:01:46,720 --> 02:01:47,600
[knocking]

2005
02:01:47,640 --> 02:01:51,480
[dramatic instrumental music]

2006
02:02:12,040 --> 02:02:14,320
[gasping]

2007
02:02:14,360 --> 02:02:16,840
[applauding]

2008
02:02:29,120 --> 02:02:32,160
- It's the most beautiful
thing I've ever seen.

2009
02:02:32,200 --> 02:02:34,600
[applauding]

2010
02:02:41,280 --> 02:02:44,040
[dramatic music]

2011
02:02:48,160 --> 02:02:49,000
- Divine.

2012
02:02:50,320 --> 02:02:52,760
[applauding]

2013
02:02:58,640 --> 02:03:01,720
[upbeat dance music]

2014
02:03:17,000 --> 02:03:20,160
