[crowd commotion]

2037
02:04:28,160 --> 02:04:30,240
- Turn on the lights now!

2038
02:04:33,000 --> 02:04:35,920
[women whimpering]

2039
02:04:40,200 --> 02:04:42,920
- Don't worry, Faye,
I'll get you out of here.

2040
02:04:42,960 --> 02:04:44,600
- Thank God.

2041
02:04:44,640 --> 02:04:47,480
[crowd commotion]

2042
02:04:51,840 --> 02:04:53,360
- Father's dead.

2043
02:04:53,400 --> 02:04:55,040
Upstairs on the pool table.

2044
02:04:55,080 --> 02:04:56,280
- What?

2045
02:04:56,320 --> 02:04:59,920
[crowd commotion]

2046
02:04:59,960 --> 02:05:01,640
- The elevator's not working.

2047
02:05:01,680 --> 02:05:04,240
- Who are these
Renthall's anyway?

2048
02:05:04,280 --> 02:05:06,240
- Well he's going to be
arrested for inside trading.

2049
02:05:06,280 --> 02:05:07,680
Just read my column tomorrow.

2050
02:05:07,720 --> 02:05:08,640
- Are those sirens I hear?

2051
02:05:08,680 --> 02:05:09,640
- Is it a fire?

2052
02:05:09,680 --> 02:05:10,480
- [Woman] Fire?!

2053
02:05:10,520 --> 02:05:11,280
- Fire?
- [Man] Fire?

2054
02:05:11,320 --> 02:05:12,680
- Break the glass!

2055
02:05:12,720 --> 02:05:15,360
[crowd yelling]

2056
02:05:18,200 --> 02:05:20,080
Oh my God, we're trapped!

2057
02:05:20,120 --> 02:05:22,720
[somber music]

2058
02:05:29,160 --> 02:05:31,160
- But my clothes, Elias,
my trunks.

2059
02:05:31,200 --> 02:05:34,080
I could never get ready to
leave for Europe in three hours.

2060
02:05:34,120 --> 02:05:36,200
- So have your maids pack
them and ship them to you.

2061
02:05:36,240 --> 02:05:38,000
Europe is nothing but a
big store anyway.

2062
02:05:38,040 --> 02:05:40,080
- Is something bad gonna happen,
Elias?

2063
02:05:40,120 --> 02:05:41,080
- Why'd you ask that for?

2064
02:05:41,120 --> 02:05:42,440
- Don't play games with me!

2065
02:05:42,480 --> 02:05:44,040
You told me we were a team,
remember?

2066
02:05:44,080 --> 02:05:46,640
A team in good times
and in bad times.

2067
02:05:47,800 --> 02:05:48,480
Do we need money?

2068
02:05:48,520 --> 02:05:49,680
- No.

2069
02:05:49,720 --> 02:05:51,160
- I have all that
jewelry, we could sell it.

2070
02:05:51,200 --> 02:05:52,880
There's the money you
signed over to me.

2071
02:05:52,920 --> 02:05:54,280
You can have it back,
it's yours.

2072
02:05:54,320 --> 02:05:55,840
- I'm all right in the
money department

2073
02:05:55,880 --> 02:05:59,400
but thank you, Ruby, I'll
never forget that you offered!

2074
02:05:59,440 --> 02:06:01,600
- You're in some kind
of trouble, aren't you?

2075
02:06:01,640 --> 02:06:02,760
- Maybe.

2076
02:06:02,800 --> 02:06:04,040
- What did you do?

2077
02:06:04,080 --> 02:06:05,760
- What people have
done before me

2078
02:06:05,800 --> 02:06:08,280
and people will do
after I'm gone.

2079
02:06:08,320 --> 02:06:10,240
- Elias, tell me
what's going on!

2080
02:06:14,120 --> 02:06:15,960
- Mr. Augustus Bailey is here,
ma'am.

2081
02:06:17,440 --> 02:06:20,160
- Oh, Gus, I'm so glad
you're all right.

2082
02:06:20,200 --> 02:06:22,160
- I came to see if you were.

2083
02:06:22,200 --> 02:06:23,840
- Oh yeah, I'm terrific.

2084
02:06:24,680 --> 02:06:26,360
The ball was a disaster,

2085
02:06:26,400 --> 02:06:28,440
some of my guests are
in the hospital,

2086
02:06:28,480 --> 02:06:30,080
dead butterflies everywhere

2087
02:06:30,120 --> 02:06:33,320
and Elias is in some
kind of trouble.

2088
02:06:33,360 --> 02:06:36,360
- I wanted to tell you
about Elias last night.

2089
02:06:36,400 --> 02:06:37,240
- What?

2090
02:06:39,560 --> 02:06:42,200
- Have you ever heard of
someone named Byron Macumber?

2091
02:06:44,160 --> 02:06:45,400
- No, why?

2092
02:06:45,440 --> 02:06:47,120
- Well he was arrested

2093
02:06:47,160 --> 02:06:49,200
for leaking inside information.

2094
02:06:49,240 --> 02:06:51,080
It's in all the morning papers.

2095
02:06:51,120 --> 02:06:52,400
Elias was mentioned.

2096
02:06:52,440 --> 02:06:56,400
Not accused but the
implication is unmistakable.

2097
02:06:56,440 --> 02:06:57,720
- Well that's illegal.

2098
02:06:57,760 --> 02:06:59,000
- It would be pretty bad.

2099
02:07:01,000 --> 02:07:03,120
- I just wish he'd been
honest with me.

2100
02:07:04,600 --> 02:07:07,440
There weren't supposed to be
any more secrets between us.

2101
02:07:11,520 --> 02:07:13,200
We're leaving for Europe today.

2102
02:07:14,640 --> 02:07:16,200
Look, Gus, if you need me,

2103
02:07:16,240 --> 02:07:17,840
if anything comes up
about Lefty,

2104
02:07:17,880 --> 02:07:20,440
you just call Max Luby,
he'll know how to reach us.

2105
02:07:21,480 --> 02:07:23,040
- I don't want you to worry,

2106
02:07:23,080 --> 02:07:24,360
especially about Lefty.

2107
02:07:25,280 --> 02:07:26,840
You just take care of yourself.

2108
02:07:29,160 --> 02:07:30,560
- You're a good friend, Gus.

2109
02:07:31,760 --> 02:07:32,800
The only one I have.

2110
02:07:34,200 --> 02:07:36,160
I'll miss you.

2111
02:07:36,200 --> 02:07:37,200
- I'll miss you too.

2112
02:07:38,680 --> 02:07:41,240
[somber music]

2113
02:07:55,360 --> 02:07:57,240
- This is Mr. Renthall,
put me through.

2114
02:07:59,200 --> 02:08:00,040
Larry.

2115
02:08:01,000 --> 02:08:02,080
I just wanted you to know

2116
02:08:02,120 --> 02:08:04,400
that I'm leaving the
country for awhile.

2117
02:08:04,440 --> 02:08:06,080
In case you're sweating,

2118
02:08:06,120 --> 02:08:07,240
I never squeal on a friend.

2119
02:08:08,360 --> 02:08:11,080
- That's very gentlemanly
of you, Elias.

2120
02:08:12,280 --> 02:08:14,680
- Well that's what
people like us are.

2121
02:08:14,720 --> 02:08:15,880
Gents, right?

2122
02:08:21,160 --> 02:08:23,920
[pleasant music]

2123
02:08:35,280 --> 02:08:36,600
- Mrs. Renthall?

2124
02:08:36,640 --> 02:08:37,880
Would you care for
something to drink?

2125
02:08:37,920 --> 02:08:39,200
Coffee, tea.

2126
02:08:39,240 --> 02:08:40,520
- Oh no.

2127
02:08:40,560 --> 02:08:42,080
I've had enough bad
coffee and weak tea

2128
02:08:42,120 --> 02:08:44,840
at 30 thousand feet to
last me a lifetime.

2129
02:08:44,880 --> 02:08:46,240
Thanks anyway.

2130
02:08:46,280 --> 02:08:48,880
[somber music]

2131
02:08:57,200 --> 02:09:00,200
[dial tone buzzing]

2132
02:09:03,160 --> 02:09:04,760
[sighing]

2133
02:09:04,800 --> 02:09:07,040
- Well there's no answer
at the loft or the gallery

2134
02:09:07,080 --> 02:09:08,320
and the machine's not on.

2135
02:09:10,720 --> 02:09:12,640
- You look terrible.

2136
02:09:12,680 --> 02:09:13,440
Do you know that?

2137
02:09:13,480 --> 02:09:14,480
Simply terrible.

2138
02:09:16,680 --> 02:09:19,400
- Wow, I must be such a
disappointment to you, Mother.

2139
02:09:19,440 --> 02:09:20,720
How embarrassing to
have a daughter

2140
02:09:20,760 --> 02:09:22,800
who is so emotionally unstable.

2141
02:09:25,000 --> 02:09:29,040
- Justine, you don't have to
over dramatize the situation.

2142
02:09:29,080 --> 02:09:30,880
- Bernie's left me and it hurts!

2143
02:09:32,000 --> 02:09:33,320
Weren't you hurt when
father left you

2144
02:09:33,360 --> 02:09:36,160
or wasn't that proper behavior?

2145
02:09:36,200 --> 02:09:38,120
- Of course it hurt.

2146
02:09:38,160 --> 02:09:41,360
But in our family, personal
misfortunes are not fodder

2147
02:09:41,400 --> 02:09:42,840
for public consumption.

2148
02:09:44,840 --> 02:09:46,400
I dealt with it silently

2149
02:09:47,480 --> 02:09:49,800
and I kept my dignity.

2150
02:09:49,840 --> 02:09:52,160
- How are you gonna keep
your precious dignity

2151
02:09:52,200 --> 02:09:54,240
when Hubey dies?

2152
02:09:54,280 --> 02:09:57,880
Your son's personal
misfortune is AIDS.

2153
02:09:57,920 --> 02:09:59,720
Not a wounded ego.

2154
02:09:59,760 --> 02:10:02,080
- He does not have that disease,
Justine,

2155
02:10:02,120 --> 02:10:04,280
and I don't want you
saying that to anyone.

2156
02:10:05,360 --> 02:10:07,040
It's just not true!

2157
02:10:09,480 --> 02:10:11,400
Now you go and you pull
yourself together

2158
02:10:11,440 --> 02:10:13,280
and you meet me at Campbell's

2159
02:10:13,320 --> 02:10:16,560
to go over some arrangements
for your grandfather.

2160
02:10:16,600 --> 02:10:19,840
Whatever we do, it should
be extremely private.

2161
02:10:19,880 --> 02:10:20,720
- What else?

2162
02:10:23,280 --> 02:10:24,440
- Yes, Jane?

2163
02:10:24,480 --> 02:10:26,760
- A Mr. Juanito Perez
is on the phone.

2164
02:10:27,800 --> 02:10:28,760
- Who?

2165
02:10:28,800 --> 02:10:30,480
- Hubey's lover, Mother.

2166
02:10:30,520 --> 02:10:33,760
- You know how I loath
that kind of talk, Justine.

2167
02:10:35,760 --> 02:10:36,800
You answer it.

2168
02:10:42,800 --> 02:10:44,960
- Hello, Juanito, it's
Justine, what is it?

2169
02:10:46,880 --> 02:10:49,560
[ominous music]

2170
02:10:55,680 --> 02:10:58,480
- It was good of you, Gus,
to come by

2171
02:10:58,520 --> 02:11:00,080
and take me out for a
breath of air.

2172
02:11:00,120 --> 02:11:01,560
- It's nothing, Lil.

2173
02:11:01,600 --> 02:11:03,760
- Well the doctor prescribed
something for my nerves

2174
02:11:03,800 --> 02:11:07,360
but I honestly don't know
what's to become of me.

2175
02:11:08,400 --> 02:11:11,680
Father dying and now
Hubey's ill.

2176
02:11:13,360 --> 02:11:14,200
Cancer.

2177
02:11:18,720 --> 02:11:20,400
I don't know how I can
live without my son, Gus.

2178
02:11:22,360 --> 02:11:24,120
I mean, know one knows
really what we had.

2179
02:11:24,160 --> 02:11:25,200
I adored him.

2180
02:11:25,240 --> 02:11:27,520
I absolutely adored him.

2181
02:11:27,560 --> 02:11:30,520
Then no one knows more about
that kind of thing than you do.

2182
02:11:31,880 --> 02:11:33,120
- Give Hubey my best.

2183
02:11:33,160 --> 02:11:34,920
Tell him I'll come see
him tomorrow.

2184
02:11:40,440 --> 02:11:42,120
- Well, at least your
grandfather died

2185
02:11:42,160 --> 02:11:43,720
with a smile on his face.

2186
02:11:45,160 --> 02:11:47,960
- He always said that a good
cigar was better than sex.

2187
02:11:48,000 --> 02:11:49,240
[laughing]

2188
02:11:49,280 --> 02:11:53,240
- He was feebleminded,
wasn't he?

2189
02:11:53,280 --> 02:11:55,840
- Juanito, before my
mother arrives.

2190
02:11:57,960 --> 02:11:59,880
- Don't ask me to leave.

2191
02:11:59,920 --> 02:12:01,000
- No, never.

2192
02:12:02,320 --> 02:12:03,920
Would you take out your earring?

2193
02:12:05,600 --> 02:12:06,800
- But you gave it to me.

2194
02:12:07,360 --> 02:12:08,680
- I know

2195
02:12:08,720 --> 02:12:11,600
but the diamond is from my
mother's engagement ring.

2196
02:12:13,000 --> 02:12:14,280
She gave it to me
when she thought

2197
02:12:14,320 --> 02:12:16,920
I was going to marry
Violet Bastito.

2198
02:12:16,960 --> 02:12:18,640
[chuckling]

2199
02:12:18,680 --> 02:12:21,160
- Well she would never
recognize it now.

2200
02:12:21,200 --> 02:12:22,520
But if it makes you happy.

2201
02:12:28,000 --> 02:12:30,240
[groaning]

2202
02:12:41,840 --> 02:12:42,680
- Juanito,

2203
02:12:43,880 --> 02:12:44,880
this is my mother.

2204
02:12:47,280 --> 02:12:48,120
Mother,

2205
02:12:49,000 --> 02:12:51,440
this is Juanito Perez.

2206
02:12:51,480 --> 02:12:52,960
- Hello, how are you?

2207
02:12:53,000 --> 02:12:54,000
- Mrs. Altemus.

2208
02:12:56,080 --> 02:12:56,920
- My word.

2209
02:12:58,840 --> 02:13:01,080
The World Trade Center
just out the window.

2210
02:13:02,960 --> 02:13:06,320
Prettier angle from here than
from Uncle Laurance's boat.

2211
02:13:08,400 --> 02:13:09,480
- Yes, much.

2212
02:13:11,480 --> 02:13:14,280
By the way, we're going to
scatter your grandfather's ashes

2213
02:13:14,320 --> 02:13:16,080
from his boat on the north side.

2214
02:13:17,440 --> 02:13:19,600
He had his happiest days
there as a child.

2215
02:13:21,240 --> 02:13:22,520
- How is Dodo taking it?

2216
02:13:24,800 --> 02:13:25,920
- She's coping.

2217
02:13:27,760 --> 02:13:28,880
We're all coping.

2218
02:13:33,000 --> 02:13:34,000
- I'm gonna split.

2219
02:13:36,120 --> 02:13:37,200
I'll come back later.

2220
02:13:39,400 --> 02:13:40,760
Goodbye, Mrs. Altemus.

2221
02:13:46,240 --> 02:13:49,440
[door closing]

2222
02:13:49,480 --> 02:13:51,440
- I brought you some magazines

2223
02:13:53,360 --> 02:13:55,200
and I thought you'd
like that new book

2224
02:13:55,240 --> 02:13:56,920
on the Princesses of Monaco.

2225
02:13:58,680 --> 02:13:59,520
- Thank you.

2226
02:14:02,520 --> 02:14:03,360
- Well,

2227
02:14:04,440 --> 02:14:06,000
I'm going to let you sleep now.

2228
02:14:11,040 --> 02:14:13,680
[ominous music]

2229
02:15:07,680 --> 02:15:10,440
[pills clinking]

2230
02:15:12,280 --> 02:15:15,040
[dramatic music]

2231
02:15:21,480 --> 02:15:24,400
[groaning]

2232
02:15:24,440 --> 02:15:27,120
[ominous music]

2233
02:15:28,840 --> 02:15:31,600
[water sloshing]

2234
02:15:37,200 --> 02:15:38,800
- Maybe you oughta call Gus.

2235
02:15:38,840 --> 02:15:40,800
Ask him to do another
article about us.

2236
02:15:40,840 --> 02:15:42,960
Talk about our charity work.

2237
02:15:43,000 --> 02:15:44,880
Now might be a good time.

2238
02:15:44,920 --> 02:15:46,360
- Don't think Gus is
the kind of guy

2239
02:15:46,400 --> 02:15:49,680
who will do a puff piece
on us this moment in time.

2240
02:15:49,720 --> 02:15:50,960
- Why not?

2241
02:15:51,000 --> 02:15:52,360
You're friends, aren't you?

2242
02:15:55,440 --> 02:15:56,600
I called Max this morning.

2243
02:15:56,640 --> 02:15:57,720
I told him to sell the plane.

2244
02:15:59,160 --> 02:16:02,400
No sense on holding on to
anything that they can seize.

2245
02:16:02,440 --> 02:16:03,840
Rent is my new policy,

2246
02:16:03,880 --> 02:16:06,160
whether it's sails,
sores or screws.

2247
02:16:08,240 --> 02:16:10,080
- How do I fit into
that new policy?

2248
02:16:11,000 --> 02:16:11,840
Am I rented?

2249
02:16:13,520 --> 02:16:15,240
- I meant the plane.

2250
02:16:15,280 --> 02:16:16,640
I meant this boat.

2251
02:16:16,680 --> 02:16:17,680
I didn't mean you.

2252
02:16:20,200 --> 02:16:22,240
- Well I guess it's
better to rent something

2253
02:16:22,280 --> 02:16:23,280
than to steal it.

2254
02:16:24,920 --> 02:16:26,000
- What the hell does that mean?

2255
02:16:26,040 --> 02:16:26,920
- You're the brains around here,

2256
02:16:26,960 --> 02:16:28,680
why don't you figure it out?

2257
02:16:30,920 --> 02:16:31,760
Don't.

2258
02:16:35,040 --> 02:16:36,640
I promised myself if a
man ever laid

2259
02:16:36,680 --> 02:16:38,160
a hand on me again ever,

2260
02:16:39,040 --> 02:16:39,880
I'd kill him.

2261
02:16:45,800 --> 02:16:48,840
For your information, Gus
explained things to me.

2262
02:16:48,880 --> 02:16:50,040
Something you never
bothered to do.

2263
02:16:50,080 --> 02:16:50,920
- Explained what?

2264
02:16:52,200 --> 02:16:55,120
- About how you were
paying off Byron Macumber.

2265
02:16:55,160 --> 02:16:56,040
- He doesn't know about that.

2266
02:16:56,080 --> 02:16:57,640
Nobody knows about that.

2267
02:17:00,240 --> 02:17:02,880
- I spoke to Gus yesterday.

2268
02:17:02,920 --> 02:17:05,480
He told me Macumber was
just the well known tip

2269
02:17:05,520 --> 02:17:07,160
of the the well known iceberg.

2270
02:17:08,480 --> 02:17:09,000
Elias,

2271
02:17:10,320 --> 02:17:13,080
the SCC has enough
information to press charges.

2272
02:17:20,520 --> 02:17:22,440
- I'm gonna need you to help me,
Ruby.

2273
02:17:23,560 --> 02:17:24,680
We're a team, remember?

2274
02:17:27,120 --> 02:17:28,880
- What do you want me to do,
Elias?

2275
02:17:31,040 --> 02:17:33,640
- Swear to my lies, if it
comes to that.

2276
02:17:36,520 --> 02:17:37,360
- No.

2277
02:17:39,000 --> 02:17:40,040
No, Elias, not that.

2278
02:17:47,040 --> 02:17:49,000
No.

2279
02:17:49,040 --> 02:17:50,440
- Mother sends her love.

2280
02:17:50,480 --> 02:17:53,720
She'd come by but she just
can't cope after her last visit.

2281
02:17:54,560 --> 02:17:55,640
- It doesn't matter.

2282
02:17:56,840 --> 02:17:58,360
- Of course it matters, Hubey.

2283
02:18:00,760 --> 02:18:01,600
- Justine?

2284
02:18:05,440 --> 02:18:07,440
About my inheritance,

2285
02:18:07,480 --> 02:18:10,600
you don't need money and
certainly Mother doesn't.

2286
02:18:11,640 --> 02:18:14,320
So I'm leaving it
all to Juanito.

2287
02:18:14,360 --> 02:18:15,640
- You can't, Hubey.

2288
02:18:16,960 --> 02:18:19,480
- I never thought I'd hear
you say that, Justine.

2289
02:18:20,880 --> 02:18:23,280
- Leave him 500 thousand,
even a million,

2290
02:18:23,320 --> 02:18:25,720
but not the whole thing, Hubey?

2291
02:18:25,760 --> 02:18:27,600
Uncle Laurance will just
take it to court

2292
02:18:27,640 --> 02:18:29,640
and call it undo
influence by Juanito.

2293
02:18:29,680 --> 02:18:32,880
He'll use everything he
can to discredit him.

2294
02:18:32,920 --> 02:18:34,000
- I love Juanito

2295
02:18:35,720 --> 02:18:37,320
and that's what I'm going to do.

2296
02:18:39,200 --> 02:18:41,640
Besides, I hired my
own attorney.

2297
02:18:41,680 --> 02:18:42,360
One of our kind.

2298
02:18:43,800 --> 02:18:46,720
It won't be so easy for Uncle
Laurance to win this one.

2299
02:18:49,280 --> 02:18:50,920
- But all of your money, Hubey.

2300
02:18:52,280 --> 02:18:54,960
You could leave some to
medical research.

2301
02:18:55,000 --> 02:18:55,920
- I know but

2302
02:18:57,800 --> 02:19:00,080
there's just
something inside of me

2303
02:19:00,120 --> 02:19:03,600
that wants to get even
with Uncle Laurance.

2304
02:19:03,640 --> 02:19:07,480
All my life he made me
feel like I was worthless.

2305
02:19:07,520 --> 02:19:10,120
Juanito never made me
feel that way.

2306
02:19:15,240 --> 02:19:18,560
So what's with your
TV announcer?

2307
02:19:18,600 --> 02:19:20,840
Has mother insist
upon calling him?

2308
02:19:22,440 --> 02:19:25,920
- Well he's up some
tropical isle.

2309
02:19:25,960 --> 02:19:29,560
Wherever it is your go to get
a quickie divorce these days.

2310
02:19:29,600 --> 02:19:31,080
- Are you taking it okay?

2311
02:19:32,960 --> 02:19:34,160
- Well,

2312
02:19:34,200 --> 02:19:35,720
I loved him

2313
02:19:35,760 --> 02:19:38,000
and someday I hope I
can forget him.

2314
02:19:39,320 --> 02:19:40,600
[chuckling]

2315
02:19:40,640 --> 02:19:41,920
Yeah, won't be easy.

2316
02:19:43,120 --> 02:19:43,960
I'm pregnant.

2317
02:19:49,320 --> 02:19:50,680
- Does Bernie know?

2318
02:19:52,040 --> 02:19:53,600
- No and Mother doesn't either.

2319
02:19:56,360 --> 02:19:58,560
- Are you going to
have the baby?

2320
02:19:58,600 --> 02:19:59,440
- Oh yes

2321
02:20:00,720 --> 02:20:02,680
and I'm going to be a
wonderful mother.

2322
02:20:03,720 --> 02:20:05,960
[laughing]

2323
02:20:09,120 --> 02:20:13,760
And you know what I'm going to
name the baby if it's a boy?

2324
02:20:14,520 --> 02:20:16,720
Hubert Altemus Slatkin.

2325
02:20:19,000 --> 02:20:21,600
[somber music]

2326
02:20:24,000 --> 02:20:27,000
- It has a certain
insouciant charm.

2327
02:20:28,600 --> 02:20:31,320
[dramatic music]

2328
02:20:32,840 --> 02:20:35,680
- I love being your sister,
Hubey.

2329
02:20:37,480 --> 02:20:39,200
And I am so proud of you.

2330
02:20:40,560 --> 02:20:43,280
[dramatic music]

2331
02:20:48,840 --> 02:20:52,080
[pleasant organ music]

2332
02:21:00,560 --> 02:21:01,720
- [Lil] Wouldn't you
think they could afford

2333
02:21:01,760 --> 02:21:03,320
some heat in this church?

2334
02:21:03,360 --> 02:21:05,840
- [Justine] Yes, Mother.

2335
02:21:05,880 --> 02:21:08,240
- [Lil] The lilacs are lovely.

2336
02:21:08,280 --> 02:21:11,200
- [Justine] Yes, Mother,
thank you.

2337
02:21:35,480 --> 02:21:39,600
[speaking foreign language]

2338
02:21:39,640 --> 02:21:40,480
- Amen.

2339
02:21:41,440 --> 02:21:43,360
- What is that man doing here?

2340
02:21:43,400 --> 02:21:44,880
Who asked him?

2341
02:21:44,920 --> 02:21:47,920
- You don't have to be
invited to a funeral, Mother.

2342
02:21:47,960 --> 02:21:49,400
The church is a public place.

2343
02:21:49,440 --> 02:21:52,800
He has much right to be
here as we have.

2344
02:21:55,720 --> 02:21:56,520
- Juanito.

2345
02:22:09,920 --> 02:22:11,600
- That's the lover.

2346
02:22:11,640 --> 02:22:15,760
- Did you notice the
whole family ignored him?

2347
02:22:15,800 --> 02:22:17,560
- Well everyone knows
he died from.

2348
02:22:19,640 --> 02:22:22,240
- Even though the obit
in the times said cancer.

2349
02:22:23,480 --> 02:22:26,520
- I do not want that man
at my house afterward.

2350
02:22:27,880 --> 02:22:30,400
Thank God we'll never have
to hear from him again.

2351
02:22:31,520 --> 02:22:32,800
- Well that's what you think,
Mother.

2352
02:22:32,840 --> 02:22:34,960
Hubey left
everything to Juanito.

2353
02:22:36,480 --> 02:22:37,320
- What?!

2354
02:22:39,360 --> 02:22:40,520
- Will you please rise?

2355
02:22:47,240 --> 02:22:49,920
The Lord is my Shepard I
shall not want.

2356
02:22:51,240 --> 02:22:54,440
He maketh me to lie
down in green.

2357
02:22:54,480 --> 02:22:55,360
- Oh, there's Gus.

2358
02:22:56,480 --> 02:22:58,760
Make sure you ask him to
come by, Justine.

2359
02:22:59,680 --> 02:23:00,520
- Yes, Mother.

2360
02:23:01,480 --> 02:23:02,560
- No one, else.

2361
02:23:04,400 --> 02:23:06,040
I repeat, no one.

2362
02:23:08,920 --> 02:23:09,760
- Juanito.

2363
02:23:12,800 --> 02:23:14,680
- I know how hard this
must be for you.

2364
02:23:14,720 --> 02:23:15,880
It is for me too.

2365
02:23:18,000 --> 02:23:19,680
We both lost someone we love.

2366
02:23:22,040 --> 02:23:23,920
- Thank you for saying that,
Justine.

2367
02:23:34,040 --> 02:23:35,880
- How could you even
speak to that man?

2368
02:23:36,960 --> 02:23:39,480
- He was my brother's
friend and heir.

2369
02:23:39,520 --> 02:23:41,000
- Oh, it's ridiculous.

2370
02:23:41,040 --> 02:23:44,480
My dear son would never have
done anything like that.

2371
02:23:44,520 --> 02:23:46,840
It's not only the money but
those Charles the Tenths chairs

2372
02:23:46,880 --> 02:23:49,400
are from the Altemus
side of the family

2373
02:23:49,440 --> 02:23:50,280
via Aunt Willaby.

2374
02:23:51,840 --> 02:23:55,720
Well, Uncle Laurance will just
contest the will, that's all.

2375
02:23:55,760 --> 02:23:58,160
- It's what Hubey wanted,
Mother.

2376
02:23:58,200 --> 02:24:00,760
Can't you at least
respect his last wishes?

2377
02:24:00,800 --> 02:24:03,560
- And have that man think
he is one of us?

2378
02:24:03,600 --> 02:24:04,440
Never.

2379
02:24:04,480 --> 02:24:07,400
- Well Hubey was one of us.

2380
02:24:10,200 --> 02:24:11,160
- Yes, he was.

2381
02:24:12,840 --> 02:24:15,560
[dramatic music]

2382
02:24:25,600 --> 02:24:28,200
[somber music]

2383
02:24:33,320 --> 02:24:35,200
- I wanna go back to New York,
Elias.

2384
02:24:36,680 --> 02:24:39,040
I can't stand hiding like
this any longer.

2385
02:24:40,480 --> 02:24:43,320
I wanna go back and face the
music, noisy as it may be.

2386
02:24:44,480 --> 02:24:45,960
- You know what that means.

2387
02:24:46,000 --> 02:24:48,960
Not only did I got to jail
but I'd have to give back

2388
02:24:49,000 --> 02:24:50,480
everything I made and more.

2389
02:24:51,480 --> 02:24:52,800
Where does that leave you?

2390
02:24:54,680 --> 02:24:56,720
- I've been poor most of
my life, Elias.

2391
02:24:57,560 --> 02:24:58,880
I can take care of myself.

2392
02:25:02,840 --> 02:25:04,720
- I wanted to take care of you,
Ruby.

2393
02:25:10,200 --> 02:25:12,800
[somber music]

2394
02:25:41,800 --> 02:25:43,960
- You have to walk home
from parties, Gus?

2395
02:25:44,000 --> 02:25:46,480
Don't you have a limo or
a private station wagon?

2396
02:25:46,520 --> 02:25:48,840
- I don't even have a bicycle,
Bernie.

2397
02:25:48,880 --> 02:25:50,440
Sorry to hear about
your and Justine.

2398
02:25:50,480 --> 02:25:51,960
- I'm sorry too.

2399
02:25:52,000 --> 02:25:54,000
I'll miss Justine but she
deserved better.

2400
02:25:54,040 --> 02:25:55,360
- Are you going away?

2401
02:25:55,400 --> 02:25:57,360
- No, Justine's put the
apartment up for sale

2402
02:25:57,400 --> 02:25:59,160
and she wanted me to get
the rest of my junk out.

2403
02:25:59,200 --> 02:26:00,160
Network sent a car for me.

2404
02:26:00,200 --> 02:26:01,440
Hop in, I'll give you
a ride home.

2405
02:26:01,480 --> 02:26:02,280
- Thanks.

2406
02:26:09,120 --> 02:26:12,040
According to Dodo, Lil
wanted to sue Juanito.

2407
02:26:12,080 --> 02:26:14,240
Laurance thought it would be
bad publicity for the family,

2408
02:26:14,280 --> 02:26:15,320
so Lil dropped it.

2409
02:26:15,360 --> 02:26:17,400
- The Van Degans are
a tough act.

2410
02:26:17,440 --> 02:26:18,360
- They're all tough,
those people.

2411
02:26:18,400 --> 02:26:19,600
- Tell me about it.

2412
02:26:19,640 --> 02:26:22,520
Ormonde Van Degan dies
and they stash his body

2413
02:26:22,560 --> 02:26:25,160
so as to not spoil the
First Lady's entrance.

2414
02:26:25,200 --> 02:26:26,840
- Yeah, well, there's
a strong indifference

2415
02:26:26,880 --> 02:26:28,320
to death everywhere, Bernie.

2416
02:26:28,360 --> 02:26:29,200
- I know, Gus.

2417
02:26:30,480 --> 02:26:31,480
It's about time for Lefty Flint

2418
02:26:31,520 --> 02:26:33,600
to be getting out of jail,
isn't it?

2419
02:26:33,640 --> 02:26:34,480
- So I heard.

2420
02:26:34,520 --> 02:26:35,920
- How're you gonna handle that?

2421
02:26:37,600 --> 02:26:39,680
- I'm gonna kill him.

2422
02:26:40,760 --> 02:26:42,600
But first I'm gonna
call out his name

2423
02:26:43,920 --> 02:26:45,520
because I want him looking at me

2424
02:26:46,760 --> 02:26:47,760
and know who it was.

2425
02:26:49,040 --> 02:26:51,200
- You're not really gonna
kill him, Gus, are you?

2426
02:26:54,600 --> 02:26:56,040
- Of course I am.

2427
02:27:02,120 --> 02:27:03,520
- I must tell you, Gus,

2428
02:27:03,560 --> 02:27:07,120
I've heard that you've
started declining invitations.

2429
02:27:07,160 --> 02:27:09,000
To Maisie's and Violet's.

2430
02:27:09,960 --> 02:27:11,880
You don't return calls.

2431
02:27:11,920 --> 02:27:13,600
You don't write thank you notes.

2432
02:27:15,920 --> 02:27:17,880
I say this as a friend, Gus.

2433
02:27:17,920 --> 02:27:19,600
No one will invite you anymore.

2434
02:27:19,640 --> 02:27:21,000
- I don't care.

2435
02:27:22,560 --> 02:27:24,120
- You don't care?

2436
02:27:24,160 --> 02:27:25,160
- I've seen enough.

2437
02:27:27,280 --> 02:27:28,560
- Well is it because of
what's happened

2438
02:27:28,600 --> 02:27:30,920
to your friends, the Renthalls?

2439
02:27:30,960 --> 02:27:35,240
I know you were especially
fond of what's her name, Ruby.

2440
02:27:35,280 --> 02:27:37,560
- No, it's not that, Lil.

2441
02:27:37,600 --> 02:27:40,600
- They never would have
fit in, you know, Gus.

2442
02:27:40,640 --> 02:27:42,720
Money can not equate
with breading.

2443
02:27:44,000 --> 02:27:45,280
- Well that may be my problem,
Lil,

2444
02:27:45,320 --> 02:27:47,160
I've never cared enough
about either.

2445
02:27:49,160 --> 02:27:50,760
- You must come to the country.

2446
02:27:50,800 --> 02:27:53,040
Come to Violet's with
me this weekend.

2447
02:27:53,080 --> 02:27:54,640
- I'm sorry, I can't, I'm busy.

2448
02:27:57,280 --> 02:28:00,280
[people chattering]

2449
02:28:03,000 --> 02:28:06,720
- Poor Lil, she's had so
much tragedy in her life.

2450
02:28:06,760 --> 02:28:09,280
Make the most wonderful book.

2451
02:28:09,320 --> 02:28:11,240
- I suppose Gus will
write it someday.

2452
02:28:11,280 --> 02:28:14,080
Carefully changing all of our
names to protect the guilty.

2453
02:28:15,280 --> 02:28:16,720
How disappointing.

2454
02:28:16,760 --> 02:28:19,360
[somber music]

2455
02:29:08,200 --> 02:29:09,480
- This was Hubey's jacket.

2456
02:29:10,320 --> 02:29:11,600
- I always liked it.

2457
02:29:11,640 --> 02:29:12,280
It's smart.

2458
02:29:13,320 --> 02:29:15,440
- Why are you here,
Miss Altemus?

2459
02:29:15,480 --> 02:29:18,560
- You really shouldn't
smoke, it's bad for you.

2460
02:29:25,560 --> 02:29:27,320
- What do you want?

2461
02:29:27,360 --> 02:29:29,680
- I'll pay you, whatever
you ask, for these.

2462
02:29:31,000 --> 02:29:33,360
- They're not for sale,
they're my possessions.

2463
02:29:35,600 --> 02:29:37,360
- It's really quite
charming here.

2464
02:29:38,760 --> 02:29:40,200
But it's so cold.

2465
02:29:48,040 --> 02:29:49,200
What do you think you're doing?

2466
02:29:49,240 --> 02:29:50,920
Those are priceless chairs!

2467
02:29:50,960 --> 02:29:53,040
Stop that!

2468
02:29:53,080 --> 02:29:54,360
For God sake.

2469
02:29:54,400 --> 02:29:55,240
What?

2470
02:29:56,240 --> 02:29:57,040
Stop it.

2471
02:29:57,080 --> 02:29:58,120
Stop that! Stop that!

2472
02:29:58,160 --> 02:29:59,360
You just stop that!

2473
02:29:59,400 --> 02:30:01,200
They're priceless!

2474
02:30:01,240 --> 02:30:02,040
Stop that!

2475
02:30:03,680 --> 02:30:05,400
- Now I can tell you,

2476
02:30:05,440 --> 02:30:08,080
had you bothered to
speak civilly to me

2477
02:30:08,120 --> 02:30:10,520
or offered me a seat at
Hubey's funeral

2478
02:30:10,560 --> 02:30:12,880
or invited me back to your
home afterwards

2479
02:30:12,920 --> 02:30:15,320
or if your lawyers hadn't
returned my letters unopened

2480
02:30:15,360 --> 02:30:16,760
in which I offered to return

2481
02:30:16,800 --> 02:30:18,600
the family heirlooms
I inherited,

2482
02:30:18,640 --> 02:30:21,080
I would've give you
those chairs.

2483
02:30:21,120 --> 02:30:23,720
But now there's no way.

2484
02:30:25,240 --> 02:30:28,200
- Whatever did my
son see in you?

2485
02:30:29,560 --> 02:30:32,440
- Love, Mrs. Altemus.

2486
02:30:34,000 --> 02:30:36,320
Please leave, now.

2487
02:30:38,840 --> 02:30:41,560
[dramatic music]

2488
02:30:57,400 --> 02:31:00,000
[somber music]

2489
02:31:32,840 --> 02:31:33,640
- Senora,

2490
02:31:34,720 --> 02:31:36,840
it's getting cold, I
brought you this.

2491
02:31:36,880 --> 02:31:38,600
- Oh, Candalaria, thank you.

2492
02:31:40,080 --> 02:31:41,320
That's so sweet of you.

2493
02:31:42,760 --> 02:31:43,800
Sit here.

2494
02:31:43,840 --> 02:31:45,640
- Oh no, no, no, gracias,
senora, no.

2495
02:31:47,920 --> 02:31:49,360
- There's a woman over there.

2496
02:31:50,400 --> 02:31:51,480
She sleeps here every night.

2497
02:31:51,520 --> 02:31:53,320
I see her from my
bedroom window.

2498
02:31:55,920 --> 02:31:57,480
Later, when it gets dark,

2499
02:31:59,680 --> 02:32:01,200
I want her to give you this.

2500
02:32:01,240 --> 02:32:03,240
- Oh, no, no, no, that's
too much, senora.

2501
02:32:03,280 --> 02:32:04,560
- No, no it's not.

2502
02:32:07,440 --> 02:32:09,240
Imagine what she must
think every night,

2503
02:32:09,280 --> 02:32:10,680
looking up to where we live.

2504
02:32:22,720 --> 02:32:23,560
- Ruby?

2505
02:32:24,400 --> 02:32:25,400
Hello.

2506
02:32:25,440 --> 02:32:26,680
- Justine.

2507
02:32:26,720 --> 02:32:29,320
Oh, Justine, it is so
good to see you again.

2508
02:32:29,360 --> 02:32:30,360
- You too.

2509
02:32:30,400 --> 02:32:32,120
Well do you mind if I join you?

2510
02:32:32,160 --> 02:32:33,000
- I'd love it.

2511
02:32:34,800 --> 02:32:38,080
I just had an urge to sit here
and look up at my own house.

2512
02:32:39,280 --> 02:32:40,400
Too big, I've decided.

2513
02:32:43,280 --> 02:32:45,000
I was so sorry to hear
about your brother.

2514
02:32:45,040 --> 02:32:47,680
- Yeah, well, thank you
for the lovely flowers.

2515
02:32:47,720 --> 02:32:48,720
That was very thoughtful.

2516
02:32:48,760 --> 02:32:50,560
- Somehow flowers
never seem enough.

2517
02:32:51,920 --> 02:32:53,520
How is your mother handling it?

2518
02:32:55,200 --> 02:32:57,680
- Well, she'll recover,
she always does.

2519
02:32:57,720 --> 02:33:00,080
Just takes some of us a
little longer, that's all.

2520
02:33:01,480 --> 02:33:04,080
- Well at least you have
Bernie to help you through it.

2521
02:33:05,720 --> 02:33:07,200
- Well, Ruby,

2522
02:33:07,240 --> 02:33:09,400
he finally told me his
deep dark secret.

2523
02:33:10,280 --> 02:33:12,120
He wanted a divorce.

2524
02:33:12,160 --> 02:33:13,000
- Oh, Justine.

2525
02:33:14,040 --> 02:33:15,480
- But

2526
02:33:15,520 --> 02:33:19,080
one wonderful thing did
happen while we were together.

2527
02:33:19,120 --> 02:33:20,440
I'm gonna have a child.

2528
02:33:20,480 --> 02:33:22,600
- Oh, how wonderful.

2529
02:33:22,640 --> 02:33:23,560
- Thank you.

2530
02:33:23,600 --> 02:33:26,000
- Oh, I've always
wanted children.

2531
02:33:26,040 --> 02:33:27,160
A whole house full.

2532
02:33:27,200 --> 02:33:27,840
- Me too.

2533
02:33:28,920 --> 02:33:31,040
But I think one's just
fine for now.

2534
02:33:31,080 --> 02:33:33,880
[laughing]

2535
02:33:33,920 --> 02:33:34,720
Ruby,

2536
02:33:36,360 --> 02:33:38,320
I want you to know how
much I admire you.

2537
02:33:39,760 --> 02:33:43,320
No matter how hard Mother
and the rest of the old guard

2538
02:33:43,360 --> 02:33:44,520
try to keep you out,

2539
02:33:45,800 --> 02:33:48,360
you always fought back
and never let them win.

2540
02:33:50,440 --> 02:33:52,600
All my life I wanted to
stand up to them

2541
02:33:52,640 --> 02:33:56,240
and make them accept me
for who I was

2542
02:33:57,240 --> 02:34:00,000
but I just never
found the courage.

2543
02:34:02,680 --> 02:34:04,320
- You're wrong about me,
Justine.

2544
02:34:05,720 --> 02:34:07,040
Oh, I wanted them to like me

2545
02:34:07,080 --> 02:34:09,760
but for who I'd become,
not for who I really was.

2546
02:34:12,000 --> 02:34:12,840
But it's over.

2547
02:34:14,200 --> 02:34:15,800
Now I can go back to
being myself

2548
02:34:15,840 --> 02:34:17,240
whether they like it or not.

2549
02:34:20,360 --> 02:34:22,000
- Well you make it
sound so easy.

2550
02:34:25,760 --> 02:34:26,600
- No.

2551
02:34:29,280 --> 02:34:30,400
It isn't easy at all.

2552
02:34:35,280 --> 02:34:38,040
- Well, I guess I
better be going.

2553
02:34:38,080 --> 02:34:40,760
It was really very good
to see you again, Ruby.

2554
02:34:40,800 --> 02:34:41,800
- Oh, good luck, Justine.

2555
02:34:41,840 --> 02:34:42,640
- Thank you.

2556
02:34:42,680 --> 02:34:43,920
- With everything.

2557
02:34:43,960 --> 02:34:45,000
You stay in touch.

2558
02:34:45,040 --> 02:34:45,880
- You too.

2559
02:34:57,680 --> 02:34:59,160
- How very sweet, Gus.

2560
02:34:59,200 --> 02:35:01,160
- They're from my terrace.

2561
02:35:01,200 --> 02:35:03,280
- I'll go put them in water.

2562
02:35:03,320 --> 02:35:04,720
Can I get you
something to drink?

2563
02:35:04,760 --> 02:35:05,800
Ice tea?

2564
02:35:05,840 --> 02:35:07,040
- No thanks, I can't stay long.

2565
02:35:07,080 --> 02:35:08,280
I just came by to wish you luck

2566
02:35:08,320 --> 02:35:09,720
when Elias' trial starts.

2567
02:35:09,760 --> 02:35:13,440
If you need anything, I'll
be in the courtroom everyday.

2568
02:35:13,480 --> 02:35:15,360
- You're a good friend, Gus.

2569
02:35:15,400 --> 02:35:16,240
- So are you.

2570
02:35:20,520 --> 02:35:23,720
- [Ruby] Anything new with
Lefty or his girlfriend?

2571
02:35:23,760 --> 02:35:24,640
- No, nothing new.

2572
02:35:25,560 --> 02:35:26,480
Still behind bars.

2573
02:35:29,760 --> 02:35:30,600
Take care.

2574
02:35:37,960 --> 02:35:39,280
[crowd commotion]

2575
02:35:39,320 --> 02:35:41,520
- I've realized I've committed
a very serious crime.

2576
02:35:41,560 --> 02:35:42,800
- Don't say too much.

2577
02:35:42,840 --> 02:35:45,880
- I can only hope that by
accepting responsibility

2578
02:35:45,920 --> 02:35:47,280
for what I've done,

2579
02:35:47,320 --> 02:35:49,880
I can easy the anguish that
I have cause my friends,

2580
02:35:49,920 --> 02:35:52,400
my colleagues and most of all,
my wife.

2581
02:35:52,440 --> 02:35:54,080
- How much are you worth
at present, Mr. Renthall?

2582
02:35:54,120 --> 02:35:55,360
- [Male Reporter] Any
comment from Mrs. Renthall?

2583
02:35:55,400 --> 02:35:56,640
- [Lawyer] No comment!

2584
02:35:56,680 --> 02:35:58,720
- It's impossible for any
observer not to notice

2585
02:35:58,760 --> 02:36:00,040
the courage of Mrs. Renthall.

2586
02:36:00,080 --> 02:36:02,800
She is a model of rectitude
at her husband's side

2587
02:36:02,840 --> 02:36:04,560
every time he's
appeared in court.

2588
02:36:04,600 --> 02:36:07,880
Silent, supportive, her eyes
hidden behind dark glasses.

2589
02:36:07,920 --> 02:36:10,680
Betraying little emotion
but admirable strength,

2590
02:36:10,720 --> 02:36:13,480
Ruby Renthall must be anxiously
awaiting the court's ruling

2591
02:36:13,520 --> 02:36:16,120
as the case against her
husband, Elias Renthall,

2592
02:36:16,160 --> 02:36:17,960
draws to its final conclusion.

2593
02:36:18,000 --> 02:36:20,000
That wraps up this
evening's edition of Focus.

2594
02:36:20,040 --> 02:36:20,960
I'm Bernard Slatkin.

2595
02:36:21,000 --> 02:36:22,320
Goodnight.

2596
02:36:22,360 --> 02:36:25,040
[knocking]

2597
02:36:25,080 --> 02:36:25,920
- [Ruby] Come in.

2598
02:36:32,400 --> 02:36:35,320
- I just wanted to say
goodnight and thanks.

2599
02:36:35,360 --> 02:36:37,120
Whatever happens tomorrow,
happens.

2600
02:36:40,080 --> 02:36:41,920
- Why don't you stay in
here tonight?

2601
02:36:44,240 --> 02:36:45,080
- Really?

2602
02:36:46,840 --> 02:36:47,680
- Really.

2603
02:36:50,480 --> 02:36:53,240
[dramatic music]

2604
02:37:16,560 --> 02:37:18,560
- [Woman] Step back, please,
excuse me.

2605
02:37:18,600 --> 02:37:21,080
[crowd commotion]

2606
02:37:21,120 --> 02:37:24,360
- Your crime, Mr. Renthall,
is too serious

2607
02:37:24,400 --> 02:37:26,360
to forgive and forget.

2608
02:37:26,400 --> 02:37:28,960
It would be a terrible
precedent for this court

2609
02:37:29,000 --> 02:37:31,480
to allow you to go unpunished.

2610
02:37:31,520 --> 02:37:34,360
Breaking the law is
breaking the law.

2611
02:37:35,320 --> 02:37:37,080
I have taken into consideration

2612
02:37:37,120 --> 02:37:39,040
the work you have done
for the homeless

2613
02:37:39,080 --> 02:37:41,000
for the last few months.

2614
02:37:41,040 --> 02:37:44,560
Never the less, I feel it
is my duty to sentence you

2615
02:37:44,600 --> 02:37:47,200
to five years in
Allenwood Prison.

2616
02:37:47,240 --> 02:37:50,080
[crowd commotion]

2617
02:37:59,640 --> 02:38:02,280
- I'm not gonna keep the
apartment, Elias.

2618
02:38:02,320 --> 02:38:04,320
- Why don't you move back out
to Rhinelander for awhile?

2619
02:38:04,360 --> 02:38:06,800
- Well I was thinking of moving
out to the country house.

2620
02:38:08,080 --> 02:38:10,160
- You'll miss your friends
stuck way out there.

2621
02:38:10,200 --> 02:38:11,800
- Gus is the only friend I have.

2622
02:38:12,920 --> 02:38:13,560
I will miss him.

2623
02:38:14,840 --> 02:38:16,720
Maybe he'll come out for
a weekend now and then.

2624
02:38:18,240 --> 02:38:21,120
- Maybe you'll come and see
me for a weekend now and then.

2625
02:38:23,800 --> 02:38:25,880
- You know I will.

2626
02:38:25,920 --> 02:38:28,360
[crowd commotion]

2627
02:38:28,400 --> 02:38:30,120
- [Reporter] Right now!
Right now!

2628
02:38:33,480 --> 02:38:36,320
[crowd commotion]

2629
02:38:42,520 --> 02:38:43,640
- I'm not gonna get out.

2630
02:38:43,680 --> 02:38:45,360
- No, of course not.

2631
02:38:47,760 --> 02:38:51,080
I can't find the words to
tell you how sorry I am

2632
02:38:51,120 --> 02:38:53,040
that I put you through all this.

2633
02:38:53,080 --> 02:38:54,640
- I know you are.

2634
02:38:54,680 --> 02:38:57,200
- And you know that I love you,
don't you?

2635
02:38:57,240 --> 02:38:58,760
- I know that too.

2636
02:38:59,840 --> 02:39:02,760
[report smooching]

2637
02:39:06,200 --> 02:39:06,880
Elias,

2638
02:39:08,160 --> 02:39:12,320
you've been great to me,
I will never forget that.

2639
02:39:14,280 --> 02:39:15,840
- [Female Reporter]
Here he comes.

2640
02:39:15,880 --> 02:39:18,680
[crowd commotion]

2641
02:39:25,280 --> 02:39:28,040
[dramatic music]

2642
02:39:45,840 --> 02:39:48,400
[somber music]

2643
02:39:51,200 --> 02:39:53,840
- [PA Announcer] Dr.
Barron to radiology.

2644
02:39:53,880 --> 02:39:56,000
Dr. Barron to radiology.

2645
02:39:58,640 --> 02:39:59,840
- [Man] Hi, Justine.

2646
02:39:59,880 --> 02:40:00,880
- Hi, Billy.

2647
02:40:03,120 --> 02:40:05,440
Would anyone like me
to write them a letter

2648
02:40:05,480 --> 02:40:07,280
or call someone?

2649
02:40:07,320 --> 02:40:10,640
- Justine?

2650
02:40:10,680 --> 02:40:11,520
Justine?

2651
02:40:14,280 --> 02:40:15,680
Don't you recognize me?

2652
02:40:17,160 --> 02:40:18,520
Do I look that bad?

2653
02:40:21,240 --> 02:40:23,160
- Oh, Juanito.

2654
02:40:23,200 --> 02:40:24,080
I didn't know.

2655
02:40:25,400 --> 02:40:26,800
- How're you doing, Justine?

2656
02:40:29,080 --> 02:40:32,360
- Well, I'm counting the
days till my baby arrives

2657
02:40:32,400 --> 02:40:34,800
and I'm inviting you to
the christening right now.

2658
02:40:34,840 --> 02:40:37,160
[chuckling]

2659
02:40:38,680 --> 02:40:40,800
- You know those Charles
the Tenth chairs

2660
02:40:40,840 --> 02:40:42,200
your mother wanted back?

2661
02:40:43,760 --> 02:40:47,680
Well I left them out on
the sidewalk one at a time

2662
02:40:49,120 --> 02:40:52,360
for people who take junk
to furnish their places.

2663
02:40:52,400 --> 02:40:55,320
[laughing]

2664
02:40:55,360 --> 02:40:58,280
Eleven poor people have
some priceless chairs

2665
02:40:58,320 --> 02:40:59,680
if they only knew of it.

2666
02:41:01,240 --> 02:41:02,680
- Well Hubey would like that.

2667
02:41:05,640 --> 02:41:08,680
- Justine, about the
money he left me.

2668
02:41:08,720 --> 02:41:10,200
- Juanito, I don't
care about that.

2669
02:41:10,240 --> 02:41:12,600
That was Hubey's money and
he wanted you to have it.

2670
02:41:13,840 --> 02:41:16,440
- I had Hubey's lawyer
come down to the loft

2671
02:41:16,480 --> 02:41:18,080
before I got so sick.

2672
02:41:20,520 --> 02:41:23,800
Hubey's money is going
to a hospice.

2673
02:41:23,840 --> 02:41:27,240
Some place for people who have
nobody to take care of them.

2674
02:41:28,080 --> 02:41:28,920
- Juanito.

2675
02:41:32,960 --> 02:41:35,520
- Your brother was the only one

2676
02:41:35,560 --> 02:41:37,360
who ever loved me in
my whole life.

2677
02:41:39,000 --> 02:41:40,080
- Don't you have any family

2678
02:41:40,120 --> 02:41:42,000
that you want me to get
in touch with?

2679
02:41:43,440 --> 02:41:44,320
- There's only my aunt

2680
02:41:45,440 --> 02:41:47,240
but she doesn't want to
hear from me.

2681
02:41:48,640 --> 02:41:50,200
- I'm so sorry, Juanito.

2682
02:41:51,240 --> 02:41:52,680
- I'm afraid to die, Justine.

2683
02:41:54,000 --> 02:41:54,840
Hubey wasn't.

2684
02:41:56,520 --> 02:41:59,440
- That's because he had you.

2685
02:42:00,840 --> 02:42:02,160
And now you have me.

2686
02:42:03,320 --> 02:42:06,320
[dramatic music]

2687
02:42:06,360 --> 02:42:07,840
- I want you to have this.

2688
02:42:10,600 --> 02:42:12,320
Your father gave it
to your mother

2689
02:42:14,440 --> 02:42:16,000
and Hubey gave it to me.

2690
02:42:20,040 --> 02:42:22,040
I want you to give it
to your child

2691
02:42:23,600 --> 02:42:26,080
so he can give it to
someone who he loves.

2692
02:42:31,160 --> 02:42:35,320
- Thank you for loving
my brother, Juanito.

2693
02:42:35,360 --> 02:42:38,120
[dramatic music]

2694
02:42:43,440 --> 02:42:46,120
[ominous music]

2695
02:42:50,360 --> 02:42:53,440
[prisoner commotion]

2696
02:43:18,400 --> 02:43:20,960
[somber music]

2697
02:43:45,080 --> 02:43:47,760
[ominous music]

2698
02:44:02,840 --> 02:44:04,400
- I can't bear that he's out.

2699
02:44:05,800 --> 02:44:08,520
I can't bear that he
should be happy.

2700
02:44:08,560 --> 02:44:10,080
- Sometimes I wonder why
they ever searched us

2701
02:44:10,120 --> 02:44:11,640
when we entered that courtroom.

2702
02:44:12,640 --> 02:44:13,760
Would've been so easy.

2703
02:44:15,440 --> 02:44:17,200
- What would've been so easy?

2704
02:44:20,240 --> 02:44:21,080
- Pow.

2705
02:44:24,440 --> 02:44:26,960
- I'm gonna call
Detective Jackson.

2706
02:44:27,000 --> 02:44:29,880
Ever since that letter, I know
that bastard's coming here.

2707
02:44:31,520 --> 02:44:33,280
I want a guard put
on this house.

2708
02:44:36,720 --> 02:44:38,480
- I don't want you to worry,
Peach.

2709
02:44:39,720 --> 02:44:40,840
He'll never come here.

2710
02:44:43,040 --> 02:44:44,720
I'm gonna take care
of everything.

2711
02:44:49,400 --> 02:44:50,680
- The geraniums are dying.

2712
02:44:51,760 --> 02:44:53,440
You can hardly kill a geranium.

2713
02:44:54,680 --> 02:44:57,840
Not enough tender loving care,
I suppose.

2714
02:44:59,920 --> 02:45:01,320
Not enough TLC.

2715
02:45:05,720 --> 02:45:06,560
- So long.

2716
02:45:10,440 --> 02:45:12,440
- You sound like you're
going on a trip.

2717
02:45:14,200 --> 02:45:15,040
- No.

2718
02:45:16,360 --> 02:45:17,560
- Gus,

2719
02:45:17,600 --> 02:45:18,600
are you all right?

2720
02:45:20,280 --> 02:45:21,120
- Goodbye, Peach.

2721
02:45:22,400 --> 02:45:25,040
[ominous music]

2722
02:45:44,200 --> 02:45:46,200
[knocking]

2723
02:45:46,240 --> 02:45:47,400
- [Marguerite] Who is it?

2724
02:45:47,440 --> 02:45:48,520
- Gus Bailey.

2725
02:45:52,600 --> 02:45:54,200
- Just go away, Mr. Bailey.

2726
02:45:55,440 --> 02:45:56,640
- Not until I see Lefty.

2727
02:45:58,120 --> 02:46:00,760
[ominous music]

2728
02:46:13,960 --> 02:46:17,480
- I should've listened to you,
Mr. Bailey.

2729
02:46:19,040 --> 02:46:21,720
You were just trying to help me.

2730
02:46:23,760 --> 02:46:26,000
But I didn't want to hear.

2731
02:46:26,040 --> 02:46:26,840
- Oh my God.

2732
02:46:27,960 --> 02:46:29,520
I've gotta get you to an
emergency room.

2733
02:46:29,560 --> 02:46:30,400
- I'll be okay.

2734
02:46:34,920 --> 02:46:36,000
He used me, you know,

2735
02:46:36,040 --> 02:46:38,440
just to have a place to
crash for awhile

2736
02:46:38,480 --> 02:46:39,800
when he got out of prison.

2737
02:46:41,560 --> 02:46:43,080
I guess I got off easy.

2738
02:46:43,120 --> 02:46:43,960
- Where is he?

2739
02:46:47,760 --> 02:46:49,440
- He left about half
an hour ago.

2740
02:46:49,480 --> 02:46:52,200
- You don't know where he went?

2741
02:46:52,240 --> 02:46:54,640
- Wherever Ruby Renthall is,
I guess.

2742
02:46:54,680 --> 02:46:56,160
Ever since she
testified against him,

2743
02:46:56,200 --> 02:46:57,880
she's all he ever talks about.

2744
02:46:57,920 --> 02:46:59,200
- I've gotta use your phone.

2745
02:46:59,240 --> 02:47:00,080
- Sure.

2746
02:47:05,800 --> 02:47:06,880
- Hello?

2747
02:47:06,920 --> 02:47:08,880
- Hello, Candalaria, this
is Gus Bailey.

2748
02:47:09,880 --> 02:47:10,920
- Mrs. Renthall is not at home.

2749
02:47:10,960 --> 02:47:11,960
She went to the city

2750
02:47:12,000 --> 02:47:13,800
and I don't think she'll
be back tonight.

2751
02:47:13,840 --> 02:47:15,480
- Is she at the Rhinelander?

2752
02:47:15,520 --> 02:47:16,880
- I don't know, Mr. Bailey.

2753
02:47:16,920 --> 02:47:18,240
- Well if you talk to her,

2754
02:47:18,280 --> 02:47:20,400
tell her Mr. Flint has left town

2755
02:47:20,440 --> 02:47:21,760
and may be coming to see her.

2756
02:47:21,800 --> 02:47:23,320
Tell her to be careful.

2757
02:47:23,360 --> 02:47:24,880
Very careful!

2758
02:47:24,920 --> 02:47:25,720
- [Candalaria] Yes, sir.

2759
02:47:25,760 --> 02:47:26,760
I'll tell her.

2760
02:47:26,800 --> 02:47:27,640
Goodbye.

2761
02:47:29,480 --> 02:47:32,320
[crowd commotion]

2762
02:47:36,080 --> 02:47:38,240
- The fabulous paintings
the Renthall's collected

2763
02:47:38,280 --> 02:47:39,560
in record time

2764
02:47:39,600 --> 02:47:42,360
are now being disposed
of in even less time

2765
02:47:42,400 --> 02:47:46,480
inside the prestigious Charles
and Charles Auction House.

2766
02:47:46,520 --> 02:47:48,880
And the vast Renthall
apartment has been bought by

2767
02:47:48,920 --> 02:47:51,200
an anonymous speculator
who plans to divide it

2768
02:47:51,240 --> 02:47:52,800
into three smaller dwellings.

2769
02:47:54,600 --> 02:47:57,360
[dramatic music]

2770
02:48:31,120 --> 02:48:33,800
[ominous music]

2771
02:48:42,160 --> 02:48:43,280
- Taxi!

2772
02:48:43,320 --> 02:48:45,560
[thudding]

2773
02:48:50,080 --> 02:48:52,600
[eerie music]

2774
02:49:18,000 --> 02:49:21,000
[people chattering]

2775
02:49:31,280 --> 02:49:33,920
[ominous music]

2776
02:50:49,160 --> 02:50:51,560
- Nice to see you again, Mrs.
Renthall.

2777
02:50:51,600 --> 02:50:53,560
- It's nice to see you
again too, Mike.

2778
02:50:55,120 --> 02:50:56,600
I have a favor to ask of you.

2779
02:50:59,360 --> 02:51:02,560
Think maybe I could take one
last look at our old apartment?

2780
02:51:02,600 --> 02:51:05,120
I know it's late and it's
probably not allowed but

2781
02:51:06,040 --> 02:51:07,200
do you think, maybe?

2782
02:51:09,200 --> 02:51:12,960
- Well, I'm not supposed
to but sure, why not?

2783
02:51:13,000 --> 02:51:14,320
The electricity's still on

2784
02:51:14,360 --> 02:51:16,760
and you can take a good
long look around the place.

2785
02:51:16,800 --> 02:51:19,400
Though you may not
recognize it much anymore.

2786
02:51:19,440 --> 02:51:20,440
- [Ruby] Thank you, Mike.

2787
02:51:20,480 --> 02:51:21,400
- Now come with me.

2788
02:51:21,440 --> 02:51:23,400
I'll have to let you
in upstairs.

2789
02:51:32,040 --> 02:51:34,520
[ominous music]

2790
02:51:34,560 --> 02:51:36,200
- Here , let me give you a
hand with that.

2791
02:51:36,240 --> 02:51:37,360
Looks like you could use a hand.

2792
02:51:37,400 --> 02:51:39,040
- Oh, thank you very much.

2793
02:51:40,080 --> 02:51:43,320
[keys jingling]

2794
02:51:43,360 --> 02:51:45,120
Thank you again, young man.

2795
02:51:45,160 --> 02:51:46,920
- I'd be happy to carry them
to the elevator for you,

2796
02:51:46,960 --> 02:51:47,680
if you want.

2797
02:51:47,720 --> 02:51:48,600
- Oh, no, there's no need.

2798
02:51:48,640 --> 02:51:49,800
- Whatever you say.

2799
02:51:49,840 --> 02:51:51,240
- Oh.

2800
02:51:51,280 --> 02:51:53,920
Well, if you wouldn't
mind, just to the elevator.

2801
02:51:53,960 --> 02:51:54,800
- Sure.
- Thank you.

2802
02:51:56,280 --> 02:51:58,960
[ominous music]

2803
02:52:02,120 --> 02:52:04,720
[somber music]

2804
02:52:13,480 --> 02:52:14,920
[thudding]

2805
02:52:14,960 --> 02:52:15,800
- Mike?

2806
02:52:19,320 --> 02:52:21,800
[eerie music]

2807
02:52:52,880 --> 02:52:56,720
[pleasant instrumental music]

2808
02:53:23,680 --> 02:53:26,000
[ominous music]

2809
02:53:26,040 --> 02:53:29,640
- Imagine having your
own ballroom.

2810
02:53:29,680 --> 02:53:31,120
You did good, Ruby,

2811
02:53:32,080 --> 02:53:33,080
for a stewardess.

2812
02:53:34,560 --> 02:53:35,400
- Lefty.

2813
02:53:38,160 --> 02:53:39,000
What do you want?

2814
02:53:40,400 --> 02:53:42,280
- Your forgiveness, of course.

2815
02:53:43,800 --> 02:53:46,440
I forgave you for testifying
at my parol hearing

2816
02:53:46,480 --> 02:53:48,960
and now it's your
turn to forgive.

2817
02:53:49,000 --> 02:53:51,680
[ominous music]

2818
02:53:56,560 --> 02:53:58,320
I want to hear you say it, Ruby.

2819
02:54:03,000 --> 02:54:03,880
And if you don't,

2820
02:54:05,760 --> 02:54:07,800
I'll make you scream it!

2821
02:54:07,840 --> 02:54:10,160
[ominous music]

2822
02:54:11,440 --> 02:54:13,760
- I laughed at my husband
when he gave me this.

2823
02:54:14,840 --> 02:54:16,720
He said to me over
and over again,

2824
02:54:16,760 --> 02:54:18,000
"There are crazy
people in the world

2825
02:54:18,040 --> 02:54:19,840
"who are out to get
people like us."

2826
02:54:21,520 --> 02:54:23,080
A smart man, my husband.

2827
02:54:23,120 --> 02:54:25,760
[chuckling]

2828
02:54:25,800 --> 02:54:29,200
- Not so smart, he went and
wound up in jail just like me.

2829
02:54:30,520 --> 02:54:31,960
- There's one big difference.

2830
02:54:33,120 --> 02:54:35,160
He can pay back the money.

2831
02:54:35,200 --> 02:54:39,600
You can never give back
the life you took.

2832
02:54:39,640 --> 02:54:44,560
Don't you come another step
near me, you son of a bitch.

2833
02:54:45,160 --> 02:54:46,000
- Hold it, Lefty.

2834
02:54:50,560 --> 02:54:54,400
You can't imagine how
long I've waited for this.

2835
02:54:58,600 --> 02:55:00,040
- I paid my dept, Bailey.

2836
02:55:00,080 --> 02:55:01,440
- You haven't begun to pay.

2837
02:55:02,800 --> 02:55:04,240
An eye for an eye.

2838
02:55:04,280 --> 02:55:06,240
Isn't that what the Bible says?

2839
02:55:06,280 --> 02:55:08,480
- It also preaches forgiveness.

2840
02:55:08,520 --> 02:55:09,880
- I never got to that part.

2841
02:55:12,440 --> 02:55:14,960
- Killing me will not
bring Becky back.

2842
02:55:16,160 --> 02:55:18,280
- I never thought it would.

2843
02:55:18,320 --> 02:55:19,920
[ominous music]

2844
02:55:19,960 --> 02:55:20,760
[gun clicking]

2845
02:55:20,800 --> 02:55:21,600
- Gus!

2846
02:55:27,240 --> 02:55:29,400
[booming]

2847
02:55:30,400 --> 02:55:33,160
[dramatic music]

2848
02:55:43,040 --> 02:55:44,760
- You're right.

2849
02:55:44,800 --> 02:55:45,800
You bastard.

2850
02:55:47,440 --> 02:55:49,400
Killing you would never
bring her back.

2851
02:56:07,240 --> 02:56:09,040
- [Gus Voiceover] Dear Peach.

2852
02:56:09,080 --> 02:56:11,840
It's rather ironic I should
be sent to Vacaville Prison

2853
02:56:11,880 --> 02:56:14,280
where Lefty Flint, I am
pleased to say,

2854
02:56:14,320 --> 02:56:15,920
is remembered without affection.

2855
02:56:17,440 --> 02:56:20,200
For the first time in
years I feel calm.

2856
02:56:21,280 --> 02:56:23,120
Lefty is no longer in
my thoughts.

2857
02:56:24,440 --> 02:56:25,640
All those nights in New York

2858
02:56:25,680 --> 02:56:27,960
when I was talking
about one thing

2859
02:56:28,000 --> 02:56:29,040
and thinking another.

2860
02:56:30,640 --> 02:56:31,920
How strange life is.

2861
02:56:33,400 --> 02:56:35,720
The way I planned it, I'd
probably be here 20 years

2862
02:56:35,760 --> 02:56:37,080
for murdering Lefty Flint.

2863
02:56:38,280 --> 02:56:40,360
Instead, I'm here for
wanting to kill him.

2864
02:56:41,360 --> 02:56:43,000
"Intent to kill,"
they called it.

2865
02:56:44,640 --> 02:56:46,160
But you know something, Peach,

2866
02:56:47,280 --> 02:56:50,160
at the very end, when
he came at me,

2867
02:56:51,360 --> 02:56:54,160
even then I knew I
couldn't kill him.

2868
02:56:56,400 --> 02:56:58,720
Life never is the way
you imagined it to be.

2869
02:56:59,640 --> 02:57:00,680
The good and the bad.

2870
02:57:02,120 --> 02:57:03,200
You know what I think?

2871
02:57:04,320 --> 02:57:06,440
I think it's possible to
be happy again.

2872
02:57:07,800 --> 02:57:09,080
Even here.

2873
02:57:10,160 --> 02:57:12,080
With love, Gus.

2874
02:57:14,040 --> 02:57:16,960
- I told you, you don't need
to keep coming back here, Ruby.

2875
02:57:17,000 --> 02:57:19,480
- You're always telling
me that and I come anyway.

2876
02:57:21,200 --> 02:57:22,080
Do you need anything?

2877
02:57:22,120 --> 02:57:22,720
- No.

2878
02:57:23,960 --> 02:57:26,920
This place isn't the
Rhinelander but I'm okay.

2879
02:57:26,960 --> 02:57:27,800
Now how about you?

2880
02:57:27,840 --> 02:57:29,040
I told Max to look out for you.

2881
02:57:29,080 --> 02:57:30,520
If you need anything,
anything at all.

2882
02:57:30,560 --> 02:57:31,480
- I'm fine, Elias.

2883
02:57:33,280 --> 02:57:34,960
I told you, I can take
care of myself.

2884
02:57:35,960 --> 02:57:37,200
- You always could, Ruby.

2885
02:57:42,600 --> 02:57:43,440
Well,

2886
02:57:45,120 --> 02:57:46,360
I gotta go back inside.

2887
02:57:50,560 --> 02:57:51,440
I love you, Ruby.

2888
02:57:55,640 --> 02:57:56,480
- I love you too.

2889
02:57:59,200 --> 02:58:00,280
- [Max] How's he doing?

2890
02:58:00,320 --> 02:58:01,440
- [Ruby] He seems fine.

2891
02:58:03,280 --> 02:58:05,040
- [Max] Elias wants you to
be happy, Ruby.

2892
02:58:05,080 --> 02:58:06,800
It's all he's ever wanted.

2893
02:58:06,840 --> 02:58:07,800
- I know, Max.

2894
02:58:08,640 --> 02:58:10,040
I want that for him too.

2895
02:58:11,480 --> 02:58:12,680
I just don't need
the same things

2896
02:58:12,720 --> 02:58:14,480
Elias needs to be happy anymore.

2897
02:58:16,600 --> 02:58:18,640
But I won't get a divorce.

2898
02:58:18,680 --> 02:58:19,720
Not until he's released.

2899
02:58:19,760 --> 02:58:21,720
He's been too good to me.

2900
02:58:21,760 --> 02:58:23,720
I owe him at least that.

2901
02:58:23,760 --> 02:58:24,560
- I understand.

2902
02:58:35,000 --> 02:58:37,400
- Paris is over, my dear.

2903
02:58:37,440 --> 02:58:40,080
Hundreds and hundreds of
dollars for one room at the Ritz

2904
02:58:40,120 --> 02:58:41,720
and not even suite.

2905
02:58:41,760 --> 02:58:43,600
And those ghastly common women

2906
02:58:43,640 --> 02:58:45,520
with those horrid little dogs

2907
02:58:45,560 --> 02:58:47,840
having lunch at the Rally Plaza.

2908
02:58:47,880 --> 02:58:50,400
And Arabs everywhere.

2909
02:58:50,440 --> 02:58:51,840
And the clothes are a disaster.

2910
02:58:51,880 --> 02:58:53,080
Skirts up to here.

2911
02:58:53,120 --> 02:58:54,120
It's just ridiculous.

2912
02:58:55,200 --> 02:58:56,720
- Well I have some news for you,
mother.

2913
02:58:56,760 --> 02:58:57,880
- Getting married again?

2914
02:58:57,920 --> 02:58:59,360
If you want to make your
mother really happy,

2915
02:58:59,400 --> 02:59:00,880
that's what she wants to hear.

2916
02:59:03,240 --> 02:59:04,200
- No, I'm not.

2917
02:59:05,800 --> 02:59:07,480
I've been asked to be the
executive head

2918
02:59:07,520 --> 02:59:10,040
at the Hubert Altemus
Junior Hospice.

2919
02:59:11,520 --> 02:59:12,560
- Well I believe that money

2920
02:59:12,600 --> 02:59:14,160
should've been given
anonymously,

2921
02:59:14,200 --> 02:59:16,360
without anyone's name
being exploited.

2922
02:59:17,760 --> 02:59:18,800
Is that your news?

2923
02:59:20,560 --> 02:59:21,560
- Yes it is.

2924
02:59:22,960 --> 02:59:24,680
- Well how long will
this Florence Nightingale

2925
02:59:24,720 --> 02:59:26,720
performance of yours go on?

2926
02:59:26,760 --> 02:59:28,600
- As long as I'm needed.

2927
02:59:28,640 --> 02:59:30,560
- Well what about your baby?

2928
02:59:30,600 --> 02:59:31,440
Your child?

2929
02:59:32,600 --> 02:59:35,080
- My child has a name, Mother.

2930
02:59:35,120 --> 02:59:36,640
He's six month old and
you've never called him

2931
02:59:36,680 --> 02:59:38,400
anything but "your child,"
never Hubey.

2932
02:59:39,840 --> 02:59:42,720
- That's not a very attractive
tone of voice, Justine!

2933
02:59:46,720 --> 02:59:49,000
Parker, I think we'll just
have coffee in the living room

2934
02:59:49,040 --> 02:59:51,880
and tell Gertie the
eggplant souffle was yummy.

2935
03:00:02,400 --> 03:00:05,560
- Mother, I just wish you
would try to understand.

2936
03:00:05,600 --> 03:00:07,480
All my life I've been identified

2937
03:00:07,520 --> 03:00:09,360
as Laurance Van Degan's niece

2938
03:00:09,400 --> 03:00:11,920
or Mrs. Van Degan Altemus'
daughter.

2939
03:00:11,960 --> 03:00:14,240
Oh, or even worse, the
Van Degan heiress,

2940
03:00:14,280 --> 03:00:16,320
as Dolly always refers
to me in her column.

2941
03:00:16,360 --> 03:00:18,880
- And now you're just
Justine Slatkin.

2942
03:00:18,920 --> 03:00:20,640
- Yes, Mother, yes.

2943
03:00:20,680 --> 03:00:24,080
Without even that terrible word
"socialite" in front of it.

2944
03:00:24,120 --> 03:00:25,280
- Why can't they call it

2945
03:00:25,320 --> 03:00:28,440
the "Juanito whatever
his name was Hospice?"

2946
03:00:39,200 --> 03:00:40,080
- Goodbye, Mother.

2947
03:00:41,400 --> 03:00:42,760
- You're not staying for coffee?

2948
03:00:42,800 --> 03:00:44,080
- No, I'm not
staying for coffee.

2949
03:00:44,120 --> 03:00:46,360
I'm going home to my son.

2950
03:00:46,400 --> 03:00:47,240
To Hubey.

2951
03:00:52,840 --> 03:00:55,440
[somber music]

2952
03:01:00,240 --> 03:01:02,200
- You love me, don't you?

2953
03:01:02,240 --> 03:01:03,240
You love me.

2954
03:01:04,320 --> 03:01:06,080
You love me.

2955
03:01:06,120 --> 03:01:08,720
[somber music]

2956
03:01:28,520 --> 03:01:30,600
[crying]

2957
03:01:34,160 --> 03:01:35,680
[knocking]

2958
03:01:35,720 --> 03:01:37,720
- Come on in, it's open.

2959
03:01:39,200 --> 03:01:41,680
- Why didn't you tell
me you were out?

2960
03:01:41,720 --> 03:01:43,080
I had to read about your release

2961
03:01:43,120 --> 03:01:45,640
in Dolly Dulongpre's column,
thanks a lot.

2962
03:01:45,680 --> 03:01:47,200
- Good to see you again, Ruby.

2963
03:01:48,080 --> 03:01:48,920
- Same here.

2964
03:01:52,480 --> 03:01:53,320
What's all this?

2965
03:01:54,520 --> 03:01:57,000
- I'm selling the
apartment, I'm moving on.

2966
03:01:57,040 --> 03:01:58,400
- Where are you going?

2967
03:01:58,440 --> 03:01:59,720
- Oh, I don't know.

2968
03:01:59,760 --> 03:02:01,040
A block or two away.

2969
03:02:01,080 --> 03:02:01,920
Maybe.

2970
03:02:01,960 --> 03:02:03,320
Maybe out of New York.

2971
03:02:03,360 --> 03:02:04,840
I haven't decided.

2972
03:02:12,240 --> 03:02:13,880
Why don't you and I
talk outside?

2973
03:02:15,400 --> 03:02:18,320
I can't tell you how good it
feels to be alive and free.

2974
03:02:19,440 --> 03:02:21,000
I was lucky to get out
in nine months.

2975
03:02:21,040 --> 03:02:22,560
Good behavior.

2976
03:02:22,600 --> 03:02:23,520
How is Elias doing?

2977
03:02:24,400 --> 03:02:25,880
- As well as can be expected.

2978
03:02:27,400 --> 03:02:29,480
Why didn't you answer any
of my letters?

2979
03:02:29,520 --> 03:02:30,960
- Well, you had enough
on your mind.

2980
03:02:31,000 --> 03:02:33,240
Didn't want you to
worry about me.

2981
03:02:33,280 --> 03:02:34,320
- You saved my life, Gus.

2982
03:02:34,360 --> 03:02:36,280
- Yeah and my own too, I guess.

2983
03:02:38,320 --> 03:02:40,040
- That's what Becky
would have wanted.

2984
03:02:41,760 --> 03:02:42,560
- I know.

2985
03:02:43,720 --> 03:02:44,480
I'm glad it's over.

2986
03:02:44,520 --> 03:02:45,880
- So am I.

2987
03:02:47,200 --> 03:02:49,240
Have you seen or heard
from any of the old crowd?

2988
03:02:49,280 --> 03:02:50,360
[chuckling]
- Hardly.

2989
03:02:50,400 --> 03:02:51,160
What about you?

2990
03:02:51,200 --> 03:02:52,040
- Oh heavens, no.

2991
03:02:53,360 --> 03:02:54,680
- I tell you what,

2992
03:02:54,720 --> 03:02:56,920
why don't we go over
to Clarence's

2993
03:02:56,960 --> 03:02:58,000
and see what happens?

2994
03:02:59,360 --> 03:03:01,600
[laughing]

2995
03:03:03,000 --> 03:03:05,240
- But I thought Elias as
bared from trading for life.

2996
03:03:05,280 --> 03:03:06,440
- That's not to say

2997
03:03:06,480 --> 03:03:08,840
he can't get somebody
else to trade for him.

2998
03:03:08,880 --> 03:03:10,400
Max Luby, for instance,

2999
03:03:10,440 --> 03:03:12,040
with Elias calling the shots.

3000
03:03:12,080 --> 03:03:12,880
- I understand.

3001
03:03:12,920 --> 03:03:14,240
- But let's talk about you.

3002
03:03:14,280 --> 03:03:15,720
I hear you been keeping diaries.

3003
03:03:15,760 --> 03:03:20,040
You know, the public loves to
read about people like you.

3004
03:03:20,080 --> 03:03:22,400
- Ever since the dreadful
Stock Market crash,

3005
03:03:22,440 --> 03:03:24,880
no one is buying odd.

3006
03:03:24,920 --> 03:03:26,280
Which, of course, my dears,

3007
03:03:26,320 --> 03:03:29,960
everyone knows is the
most sensible investment.

3008
03:03:30,000 --> 03:03:32,840
- I heard Laurance Van
Degan knew the Stock Market

3009
03:03:32,880 --> 03:03:35,200
was going to crash
because Elias Renthall

3010
03:03:35,240 --> 03:03:37,920
called him from
prison and told him

3011
03:03:38,960 --> 03:03:40,760
to get out of the
market a week ago.

3012
03:03:40,800 --> 03:03:41,560
- Wish he called me.

3013
03:03:41,600 --> 03:03:43,520
- Oh my dear word.

3014
03:03:43,560 --> 03:03:46,880
Can you believe who just
walked into this restaurant?

3015
03:03:46,920 --> 03:03:48,680
[people chattering]

3016
03:03:48,720 --> 03:03:50,920
- Oh, I love all this drama.

3017
03:03:50,960 --> 03:03:52,520
So much better than television.

3018
03:03:54,320 --> 03:03:55,280
- [Ruby] So tell me, Gus,

3019
03:03:55,320 --> 03:03:57,120
did you make any new
friends in jail?

3020
03:03:57,160 --> 03:03:58,600
Elias has.

3021
03:03:58,640 --> 03:04:00,760
- No friends but I wrote a book.

3022
03:04:00,800 --> 03:04:02,680
- [Ruby] I always
said you would.

3023
03:04:02,720 --> 03:04:03,520
- Oh, Maisie.

3024
03:04:03,560 --> 03:04:04,800
- Gus Bailey.

3025
03:04:06,000 --> 03:04:07,160
- You know Ruby.

3026
03:04:07,200 --> 03:04:08,000
- Hello, how are you?

3027
03:04:08,040 --> 03:04:09,640
- How are you?

3028
03:04:09,680 --> 03:04:11,480
Oh, it's been ages.

3029
03:04:11,520 --> 03:04:13,440
- Nine months, two days,

3030
03:04:13,480 --> 03:04:16,120
14 hours and 10 seconds.

3031
03:04:16,160 --> 03:04:17,760
Prison life teaches you
to keep track of time.

3032
03:04:17,800 --> 03:04:20,080
[laughing]

3033
03:04:21,040 --> 03:04:22,400
- Gus,

3034
03:04:22,440 --> 03:04:24,680
I'm having a small
dinner party on Thursday.

3035
03:04:24,720 --> 03:04:26,240
I'd love you to come.

3036
03:04:26,280 --> 03:04:28,120
- I can't on Thursday.

3037
03:04:28,160 --> 03:04:30,000
- Well then come to the
country for the weekend.

3038
03:04:30,040 --> 03:04:31,200
- I can't this weekend.

3039
03:04:33,240 --> 03:04:37,400
- I suppose it must be difficult
to meld back into society

3040
03:04:37,440 --> 03:04:38,400
after being in,

3041
03:04:39,560 --> 03:04:40,680
after being away.

3042
03:04:42,040 --> 03:04:42,880
See you.

3043
03:04:47,680 --> 03:04:48,880
- You did that well.

3044
03:04:50,680 --> 03:04:52,320
- I thought a lot
about these people

3045
03:04:54,040 --> 03:04:55,720
and I realized all the
money in the world

3046
03:04:55,760 --> 03:04:58,760
can't protect anyone from
tragedy and heartbreak.

3047
03:05:00,560 --> 03:05:02,280
And yet, you look at them,

3048
03:05:02,320 --> 03:05:04,000
you think they didn't
have a care.

3049
03:05:05,400 --> 03:05:07,120
They cover their
feelings so well.

3050
03:05:09,560 --> 03:05:12,080
But I can't hide in their
world anymore.

3051
03:05:13,200 --> 03:05:15,040
I have to start living
my life again.

3052
03:05:16,680 --> 03:05:17,520
- Me too.

3053
03:05:19,560 --> 03:05:20,840
- Welcome back, Gus.

3054
03:05:20,880 --> 03:05:21,840
- Hello, Jake.

3055
03:05:21,880 --> 03:05:23,080
- It's wonderful to see you,
Ruby.

3056
03:05:23,120 --> 03:05:23,960
- Thanks, Jake.

3057
03:05:24,960 --> 03:05:27,440
Listen, Jake, we're not staying.

3058
03:05:29,120 --> 03:05:30,880
- That's just what I
was gonna say.

3059
03:05:32,400 --> 03:05:35,040
[pleasant music]

3060
03:05:35,080 --> 03:05:36,520
- [Woman] Of all the nerve.

3061
03:05:36,560 --> 03:05:38,400
Who do they think they are?

3062
03:05:42,160 --> 03:05:44,920
[dramatic music]

3063
03:05:46,720 --> 03:05:47,560
- Taxi!

3064
03:05:51,120 --> 03:05:53,200
Can I drop you somewhere?

